<FIRST>u i AM-China-Economy     08-30 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Economy,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Acts To Reassert Controls Over Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official press reported Thursday that the
government is taking new steps to re-establish order in an economy
reeling from speculation and profiteering in scarce materials and
widespread tax evasion.
   The steps include measures to reassert controls over the
distribution and pricing of raw materials such as coal and steel,
the reports said.
   The state will also begin a campaign against what it says is
rampant tax evasion among China's 14.5 million privately owned
enterprises, the China Daily reported.
   Xie Mingan, an official of the Ministry of Materials and
Equipment, said the state will tighten controls on prices of some
raw materials such as coal, rolled steel and non-ferrous metals.
   He said redundant middlemen will be eliminated, illegal dealers
and officials trading power for money will be disciplined and state
supplies of materials to production enterprises will be maintained.
   One aspect of the economic reforms _ decentralization of controls
over raw materials _ has led to hoarding, speculation and
price-gouging. Middlemen, often with links to influential party and
government officials, buy up scarce materials at low government-set
prices and sell them for huge profits on free markets.
   Jin Xin, director of the State Tax Administration, told a
conference Wednesday that if the problem of tax evasion among
private businessmen goes unsolved, ``it will certainly sap the
morale of the dominant working classes and bring adverse effects on
the enthusiasm of intellectuals.''
   China's conservative leadership has singled out private
entrepreneurs as an example of unhealthy disparities in income
levels. Many private businessmen, some operating from simple street
stalls, earn more in a day than a worker or teacher makes in a
month. A young worker earns about $27 a month.
   Jin said the state was not trying to add to the financial burdens
of private businessmen, who have been a stimulus in China's economic
growth over the past decade.
   He also promised no change in the preferential terms on taxation
for foreign investors in China.
   The Central Committee of the National People's Congress, China's
parliament, was also told Wednesday that more than 2,800 companies
lost their business licenses and nearly 800 party and government
officials were punished after the government began a drive against
shady business practices in October.
   The moves come against the backdrop of a return to Marxist
orthodoxy in the political sphere following the military crackdown
on the pro-democracy movement in June and a general reassessment of
the pace of the nation's market-oriented economic reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
