<FIRST>r a AM-TropicalWeather     08-30 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Gabrielle Forms Off Cape Verde</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Gabrielle formed late Wednesday off
the West African coast with top winds of 40 mph, becoming the
seventh named storm of the Atlantic hurricane season, forecasters
said.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, the center of Gabrielle was near latitude 11.0
north and longitude 25.8 west, or about 435 miles southwest of the
Cape Verde Islands.
   The storm, heading west at 20 mph, was expected to strengthen
over the next day, according to the National Hurricane Center in
suburban Coral Gables.
   The storm formed less than a day after its predecessor, Felix,
dwindled to a tropical depression. It carried winds of 30 mph
Wednesday night and was centered about 920 miles south of the
westernmost Azores in the north Atlantic.
   A depression becomes a tropical storm when its winds reach 39
mph. A tropical storm becomes a hurricane once its winds hit 74 mph.
There have been three hurricanes so far during the hurricane season,
which runs from June 1 to Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
