<FIRST>r w AM-HomicideRate 1stLd-Writethru a0405 08-30 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homicide Rate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0405,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs grafs 2 and 3 to CORRECT time element from Monday to Tuesday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Record Killing Pace Surpasses 300 in Nation's Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Killings in the District of Columbia,
continuing at a record pace that police say is largely driven by a
burgeoning drug trade, has passed the 300 mark for the year.
   The city's 300th homicide victim, recorded early Tuesday, was a
suburban Maryland man gunned down in a northwest Washington drug
market, police said.
   At least 10 people were shot or stabbed in the city Tuesday,
police said, and three died.
   One woman was seriously injured by a stray bullet as she stood
outside her northest Washington home.
   The deaths bring the district's 1989 homicide count to 301,
compared to 216 at this time last year. The city's homicide record
of 372 was set last year.
   Police say about 60 percent of the city's killings are related to
drugs. Drug-related violence has also hiked the murder rate in
Washington's suburbs, according to police.
   Twelve people have been killed so far this year in Montgomery
County, Md., compared to nine at this time last year. In Prince
George's County, Md., 77 people have been killed this year, compared
to 53 at this time in 1988.
   Fairfax County, Va., has had 19 killings this year, compared to
12 last year, and Alexandria, Va., has eight compared to three last
year.
</TEXT>
