<FIRST>r i PM-Tourism-PLO     08-30 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tourism-PLO,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tourist Group Votes to Put Off Admitting Palestine as Member</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Tourism Organization voted to put off
consideration of a membership application by the PLO's self-declared
state of Palestine until the organization meets again in 1991.
   The United States, supported by Hungary and Australia, forced the
vote Tuesday to delay the membership consideration afer daylong
discussions. The vote was by secret ballot.
   The U.S. effort was led by John Bolton, assistant secretary of
state for international organizations, who said he was ``very
gratified'' by the outcome.
   The vote was 40-34 to postpone the issue, with six absentees, six
abstentions and five blank votes.
   One diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it was
the first time he could recall a Soviet bloc country supporting a
U.S. resolution at an international meeting.
   The United States maintains that bids by the Palestine Liberation
Organization to join international bodies threatens Middle East
peace efforts.
   Omar Massalha, head of the PLO's observer mission to the
Paris-based U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization,
called the vote ``a bad decision.''
   Massalha said the PLO would continue its efforts to join
international organizations.
   The PLO's National Council, a sort of parliament-in-exile,
proclaimed the state of Palestine last November. Washington, backed
by most Western allies, says it does not fulfill international
criteria because it has no defined territory.
   The World Tourism Organization, with headquarters in Madrid, is
an intergovernmental group set up in 1975 to promote and develop
tourism.
</TEXT>
