<FIRST>u p AM-Pepper'sSeat 9thLd-Writethru a0433 08-30 0973</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper's Seat, 9th Ld-Writethru, a0433,1002</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ros-Lehtinen First Cuban-American Elected To Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 26 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from winner, loser,
Republican and Democratic chairmans, editing to conform; picks up 20th
graf, `Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, a ...' Should stand for AMs. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen
pronounced ill-ee-AHN-ah ross-LAYT-ih-nen.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Havana-born Republican state senator rode heavy
support from Miami's Hispanic community Tuesday to become the first
Cuban-American elected to Congress, winning the seat held by the
late Claude Pepper for nearly three decades.
   With all precincts reporting in the ethnically divisive race,
state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, 37, received 49,638 votes, or 53
percent, to 43,759, or 47 percent, for Brooklyn-born attorney Gerald
Richman.
   The 48-year-old Democrat, who is Jewish, had been making his
first run for elective office.
   The race was made necessary by Pepper's death May 30 at 88.
Pepper, a Democrat, had held the seat since its inception 27 years
ago.
   The 93,000-plus turnout was nearly 51 percent, far higher than
normal for a special election and higher than election officials' 43
percent projection.
   The outcome was delayed more than an hour late Tuesday by a Dade
County elections computer problem that temporarily halted
vote-counting. Higher final counts for both candidates were revised
early Wednesday because of the counting problems.
   The unofficial returns indicated that predominantly Hispanic
precincts, with turnouts of more than 60 percent, boosted Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen with 80 to 90 percent margins, while Richman was
favored by margins of 80 to 90 percent in predominantly black or
non-Latin white precincts.
   In her victory speech, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen said she wanted to unify
and heal the community and ``provide leadership ... which is based
on acaring conscience and conservative convictions.
   ``We do not have the luxury to waste time on divisive politics,''
she told cheering supporters at the Airport Hilton Hotel. ``We must
focus on what we have in common and not ponder on the negative.''
   Richman, addressing disappointed supporters at the Clarion Castle
Hotel in Miami Beach, said, ``We have done incredibly well and we
did it on a positive theme.''
   He said Ms. Ros-Lehtinen outspent him and had campaign help from
President Bush, Vice President Dan Quayle and Sen. Connie Mack,
R-Fla.
   The Democrat, noting that more Hispanics turned out than blacks
or non-Hispanic whites, said, ``We've got to get everyone in this
community to get out and exercise their right to vote. If that had
happened, we would have won tonight.''
   The Democrats, mindful that August is vacation month for many
Miami residents, had tried to build an absentee-vote margin for
Richman. But election officials said Richman had only 3,933 absentee
votes to 3,599 for Ms. Ros-Lehtinen.
   The victory gave the GOP an 11-8 majority in Florida's
congressional delegation, and Republican National Chairman Lee
Atwater called it a Republican milestone in the South.
   ``That seat has been a Democratic seat since it was created,'' he
said in a telephone interview from Washington. ``For us to win it is
a major victory.''
   Democratic Chairman Ron Brown, who campaigned for Richman,
expressed disappointment in a statement issued by his Washington
office, but said, ``The Democrats ran a surprisingly competitive
race after an admittedly divisive primary.''
   Ethnic-bloc campaigning dominated the short, tense race between
Ms. Ros-Lehtinen and Richman for the remaining 14 months of Pepper's
term. Richman had come under fire for declaring, ``This is an
American seat.''
   Richman had hoped to capitalize on the 30,000-plus edge that
Democrats, mostly blacks, Jews and retirees, hold in registration.
Ms. Ros-Lehtinen looked to the Hispanic community, which makes up 40
percent-plus of the vote.
   Polls in the final week of the race had indicated it was too
close to call.
   `It's been a very controversial election,'' said Dade County
Elections Supervisor David Leahy. ``There has been a tremendous
amount of media exposure, and we think both camps are getting a lot
more people out to vote.''
   Pepper's seat was one of five openings in the U.S. House. The
others were caused by the resignations of Tony Coelho, D-Calif., and
Jim Wright, D-Texas, and the deaths of Mickey Leland, D-Texas, and
Larkin Smith, R-Miss., in plane crashes.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen had refused to appear with Richman during the
campaign, charging his ``American seat'' message was bigoted.
   However, the same charges were made against her campaign over a
Spanish-language mailing that urged Hispanics to show how American
they were even though they weren't born in Brooklyn and didn't speak
English like Richman.
   Richman's said his ``American seat'' remark was an appeal to
voters to decide on qualifications, not birthplace. He also said it
was a response to GOP National Chairman Lee Atwater's statement that
the party wanted to elect a Cuban-American.
   But many saw Richman's theme as anti-Hispanic code.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, a legislator for seven years, emphasized
experience and populist appeal in her campaign. Her campaign
chairman was the president's son Jeb.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, whose husband, Dexter Lehtinen, is U.S.
attorney in Miami, portrayed herself as tough on crime and drugs.
   But Richman argued that her legislative record against gun
control showed softness on crime, because it allowed criminals easy
access to guns.
   Richman also tried to make abortion an issue; he's pro-choice,
Ms. Ros-Lehtinen is for further restrictions on abortion. With polls
indicating most voters were pro-choice, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen claimed it
wasn't an issue.
   Richman, a former Florida Bar Association president, stunned the
Democratic establishment by breaking out of a seven-candidate pack
to win narrowly the party's Aug. 1 primary, then trouncing erstwhile
front-runner Rosario Kennedy in an Aug. 15 runoff. Ms. Ros-Lehtinen
won the GOP nomination in the Aug. 1 primary.
   The district covers black neighborhoods such as Liberty City,
most of Miami, Miami Beach and Miami Springs and sections of
blue-collar Hispanic Hialeah and upscale Coral Gables and Key
Biscayne.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
