<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     08-30 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Say Banned Pesticides Enter U.S. in Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group says new laws are needed
to prevent chemical companies from manufacturing highly toxic
pesticides banned in this country and sending them abroad.
   The practice ``has created a circle of poison'' where some food
tainted by the toxic chemicals is imported into the United States,
said Sandra Marquardt, who has followed the issue for the
environmental group Greenpeace.
   Greenpeace cited the practices of the Velsicol Chemical Corp.,
which from its plant in Memphis, Tenn., is the world's only producer
of the pesticides chlordane and heptachlor.
   Both pesticides are banned for agricultural use in the United
States and for virtually all other uses because they were found to
cause cancer. They are also banned or severely restricted in 48
countries.
   Nevertheless, Ms. Marquardt said Tuesday, Velsicol exported
nearly 5 million pounds of the pesticides to 25 countries between
1987 and the middle of this year. More than 330,000 pounds went to
Argentina and another 510,000 pounds to Australia, countries that
import meat and other products into the United States.
   In a statement from company headquarters in Rosemont, Ill.,
Velsicol called the Greenpeace report ``grossly inaccurate.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Appeals Court OKs Random Drug Tests for Some Army Civilians</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court says the Army may
subject more than 6,500 civilian workers, including law enforcement
and aviation personnel, to random drug tests.
   The Army in 1986 implemented drug testing for more than 9,000 of
its 450,000 civilian employees.
   In a 3-0 decision Tuesday, the U.S. Court of Appeals said 3,700
civilian police and guards should face mandatory drug tests because
of the threat to public safety posed by ``drug-impaired, gun-toting
civilian officers.''
   The 2,800 civilians who fly and service the Army's airplanes and
helicopters also should undergo random drug testing due to the
possibly ``calamitous consequences'' of a single drug-related lapse,
the appeals court said.
   A small group of civilian lab workers don't have to undergo
mandatory, random testing, said Appeals Court Judge David Sentelle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Banking Chairman Will Reopen Probe of Lincoln S&amp;L</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Banking Committee
says he'll reopen his panel's investigation of the failure of
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, expected to require the
government's largest thrift rescue.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, branded the collapse of the Los
Angeles thrift a ``mini-Watergate,'' and said his committee had
suspended its probe only because of the pressing need to pass
emergency legislation bailing out the S&amp;L industry.
   The probe is sure to examine political contributions from Charles
H. Keating Jr., chairman of Lincoln's parent company, American
Continental Corp. of Phoenix, to five senators who later met with
regulators about Lincoln.
   They are Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; John Glenn, D-Ohio;
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; John McCain, R-Ariz.; and Donald W.
Riegle Jr., D-Mich. Riegle, who is chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, later returned Keating's contribution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Regulators Urge Quick Decision on Selling Nuclear Plant</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is urging a
California utility to decide soon whether to sell or dismantle its
Rancho Seco nuclear power plant, which voters said last June should
close.
   Thomas Murley, director of the NRC's office of nuclear reactor
regulation, told officials of the Sacramento Municipal Utility
District on Tuesday that uncertainty about the fate of the
913-megawatt plant was making it difficult to plan regulatory
changes there.
   The NRC must approve any transfer of the utility district's
nuclear license to another operator, but it also must approve the
various regulatory adjustments required if the plant is
decommissioned and dismantled.
   David A. Boggs, general manager of the utility district, said
efforts to sell the 15-year-old plant probably will be abandoned if
no agreement is reached by Friday with Quadrex Corp. of Campbell,
Calif.
   The Rancho Seco station has been closed since June 7, the day
after utility district residents voted against keeping it running.
It was the first time an operating nuclear power plant was closed by
voter initiative.
</TEXT>
