<FIRST>u a AM-PhoneStrikes     08-30 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Strikes,0373</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By DENISE BEZICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana Bell reached a tentative contract
agreement Tuesday night with the union representing 4,200 striking
telephone workers, bringing parent company Ameritech closer to
ending a 17-day-old strike.
   The three-year pact between Indiana Bell and the Communications
Workers of America made Michigan Bell the only one of five
subsidiaries of Ameritech, a regional ``Baby Bell'' company, without
a contract agreement.
   The CWA has instructed all 37,000 members in Ameritech territory
to stay off the job until agreements are reached with all five
companies.
   Tentative settlements were reached over the weekend with Ohio
Bell and Wisconsin Bell, and on Monday with Illinois Bell.
   Talks with Michigan Bell resumed Tuesday, and continued early
Wednesday, said spokesmen for the utility and the union.
   The Indiana Bell agreement was announced by the utility and the
union. A ratification vote must be held within 45 days of strikers'
returning to work.
   Until strikers return, the company will continue operating with
management and supervisory personnel, said Indiana Bell spokesman
Estel Gibson.
   The Ameritech walkout began Aug. 13, seven days after strikes
began at three other regional phone companies formed in the 1984
breakup of AT&amp;T. The strikes have involved 200,000 workers in 20
states.
   Indiana Bell spokesman Dennis McCabe said the contract meets the
needs of employees while keeping the company competitive. He said
the tentative agreement includes salary hikes, improved pensions,
new family care features and profit sharing, McCabe said.
   Details of the pact will not be released until the company and
the union have had a chance to share the information with employees,
said Fredric A. Hunn, Indiana Bell vice president of human resources
and corporate development.
   Bell Atlantic workers in six states and Washington, D.C., ended
their strike Monday after agreements were reached with CWA locals in
Pennsylvania and Delaware. A tentative contract settlement has also
been reached at Pacific Telesis, serving California and Nevada.
   A strike continued at NYNEX Corp., serving New York and most of
New England, with talks scheduled to resume Wednesday with the CWA
and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
</TEXT>
