<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0258EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Argentina     08-30 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Argentina,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Menem Willing to Meet Thatcher to Discuss Falklands Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentine President Carlos Menem was quoted in an
interview today as saying he wants to meet with British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher in an attempt to resolve the Falkland
Islands dispute that led to a 74-day war in 1982.
   Menem suggested such a meeting could take place during next
month's session of the U.N. General Assembly in New York. But Menem,
in office since July, said he would welcome direct talks with Mrs.
Thatcher ``in England, in Argentina or in any part of the world,''
The Times of London reported.
   Menem also said in the interview that he ruled out the
possibility of Argentina forcefully trying to recover the Falklands,
which it calls the Malvinas and has claimed since 1833. Their brief
but bloody South Atlantic war cost the lives of nearly 1,000 British
and Argentine soldiers.
   ``This is completely ruled out, at least during my government.
... We will not use weapons to recover what we believe and are
convinced is ours,'' Menem was quoted as saying.
   Menem added that he would invite Mrs. Thatcher to the Argentine
capital of Buenos Aires if diplomatic relations between the two
countries, which have been severed since the war, were restored, the
paper reported. ``I am planning to do so if Mrs. Thatcher is willing
to talk to me,'' it quoted him as saying.
   The exclusive interview was by Times correspondent Michael Llanos
in Buenos Aires but the paper did not say when it was conducted.
   There was no immediate reaction from Mrs. Thatcher's government.
But the British domestic news agency Press Association reported
without attribution: ``The view in Whitehall (British government
circles) is that if President Menem's words and proposals are
accurately represented, this is an attitude which Britain welcomes.
   ``However, while his words will be studied closely in (Mrs.
Thatcher's) Downing Street (office), the feeling is that any
British-Argentine dialogue should move forward one step at a time.''
   Representatives of the two governments agreed during three days
of talks in New York this month to hold a meeting of officials Oct.
17-18 in the Spanish capital of Madrid to discuss proposed
normalization of relations between the two nations.
   Similar talks in Bern, Switzerland, in July 1984 broke off over
the issue of sovereignty, with Britain refusing to discuss
sovereignty of the islands and Argentina insisting it stay on the
agenda.
   Mrs. Thatcher's government has consistently refused to discuss
sovereignty. But Menem has dropped the insistence of the previous
Argentine government headed by President Raul Alfonsin that
Argentina's sovereignty claim must be the first issue considered in
normalization talks.
   Argentina invaded the Falklands 325 miles off its southeast coast
in April 1982 but Britain sent a task force and recaptured them in a
war that eventually led the Argentine junta, which had ruled harshly
for nearly eight years, to relinquish power upon the election of
Alfonsin.
   Argentina claims the windswept islands as an inheritance from the
days of Spanish colonial rule and says the British, who have ruled
them as a colony since 1833, stole the islands.
   Argentina has never formally declared an end to hostilities with
Britain since the 1982 war.
   Asked in the interview in The Times if he thought island
sovereignty would be negotiated at any stage during his six-year
term, Menem was quoted as saying: ``It might, but it might not. We
have waited 156 years (to recover the islands). We can certainly
wait a bit longer.''
   Nearly 2,000 staunchly pro-British Falkland Islanders are
fiercely opposed to Argentina ever gaining sovereignty.
   Menem was quoted in the interview as saying that if full
diplomatic relations between Britain and Argentina were restored,
his government would allow airline flights and shipping services
between Argentina and Britain and Argentina and the Falklands.
   He was quoted as saying that this included the Indiana I, the
Falklands' own merchant vessel that caused a stir in recent months
by docking in neighboring ports in Uruguay and Chile.
</TEXT>
