<FIRST>r a PM-Congressman-Prostitute     08-30 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressman-Prostitute,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank Not Discussing Re-election Until Charges Cleared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Barney Frank says will not talk about
running for a sixth congressional term until he has cleared the air
of the controversy caused by a male prostitute he once employed.
   When it was reported that Frank had paid Steve Gobie for sex and
then hired him to do household chores, the Massachusetts Democrat
said he did not believe the controversy should affect his political
plans.
   But Gobie has continued to allege that he procured sex partners
for Frank and that Frank knew Gobie was running a prostitution ring
out of Frank's Washington, D.C., home, charges the congressman
strongly denies.
   ``Before I have disposed of those charges, it's not fair for me
to be saying, `Hey I'm gonna run anyway,''' Frank said in an
interview Tuesday. ``I'm not going to talk about running again until
I can get the forum to clear those up.''
   The proper forum, Frank said, is the House ethics committee. On
Monday he asked Chairman Julian C. Dixon, D-Calif., to investigate
Gobie's allegations ``to ensure that the public record is clear.''
   Frank has been re-elected since disclosing his homosexuality. But
after the disclosure that he paid for sex, some Republican leaders
called for his resignation.
   ``If everything Gobie said was true I should resign,'' Frank
said. ``The focus should not be on my political career. It should be
on the accuracy of these charges.''
   Gobie reportedly is looking for possible book and movie deals. He
said he has received hundreds of messages on his telephone answering
machine since his story appeared Friday in The Washington Times.
   ``Just leave a message on my answering machine _ if you can find
room on the tape,'' an early version of Gobie's message said.
   ``I'm an open person. I'll listen to all offers,'' he told the
Boston Herald.
   Gobie, who will be 33 years old on Monday, has said that he was
inspired to publicize his story by the television movie ``Mayflower
Madam,'' about Sydney Biddle Barrows, the New York City madam who
ran a high-class brothel.
   He told The Washington Post that he was motivated by money and
notoriety. Frank said he believes greed is leading Gobie to
embellish his story.
   ``There seems to be some change in the story, and it seems
someone told him that the more lurid the story, the more money there
will be for him,'' Frank said.
   Frank has said he employed Gobie, who has a history of
involvement with male prostitution and drugs, with hopes of
reforming him.
   Gobie's number was published in the City Paper, Washington's
weekly arts and entertainment guide, in an advertisement that
offered ``Total Pleasure _ Full body massage will make you feel it.
Young, handsome masseur avail. by appt.''
   Callers were greeted with background music of the '60s rock hit
``Light My Fire.''
   Gobie did not return a message left on his machine Tuesday, and
his outgoing message was toned down: ``I will return your call as
soon as possible or one of my associates will return your call as
soon as possible.''
   The congressman said Herb Moses, the man he currently lives with,
has been helping him through the ordeal of disclosure.
   ``He has made such an enormous difference in my life that this
has been a tolerable experience,'' Frank told The Boston Globe. ``I
only wish I met him five years earlier. He has provided emotional
and intellectual support that make a big difference _ the absence of
which contributed to the extent to which I was stupid personally
earlier.''
</TEXT>
