<FIRST>r a PM-FreeBird     08-30 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Free Bird,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spooked Bird Flees Authorities in Fast Footrace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLISON J. PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCITUATE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flightless bird the size of a Boston
marathoner gave authorities a good run and kicked an animal control
officer before police surrounded him and ended his two-hour escapade.
   The bird, a relative of the ostrich, fled in terror Tuesday after
he was accidentally freed from his owner's back yard.
   The owner's sons and police chased the emu, named PeeWee, through
streets in this seaside town southeast of Boston until police
finally surrounded him with a wire fence in a pasture.
   PeeWee was taken to Tufts New England Veterinary Medical Center
in North Grafton and given three stitches for a cut in the neck. The
bird was expected to go home today.
   Emus are flightless Australian birds with long legs and huge
three-toed feet. Owner Myrin Borysenko estimated PeeWee to be more
than 6 feet tall.
   Borysenko said he got the bird as a chick three years ago. He
said PeeWee was friendly but not very smart.
   ``Once he's outside the back yard, he has no point of reference.
If I'm in the yard he will recognize me. But if he's outside the
yard, he gets spooked,'' said Borysenko, who is a doctor of
immunology and anatomy.
   He said a neighborhood child probably opened the backyard gate,
letting PeeWee loose.
   Andrei Borysenko and his brother, Justin, went to the front yard
to collect the bird, but PeeWee became terrified and took off.
   ``As my son likes to say, as soon as he got out, his turbo kicked
in and he was flying down the street,'' Broysenko said.
   At the town common, animal control officer Lesley Cook got a
noose around PeeWee, but he leapt away and kicked her in the leg.
``His kick was about as hard as my horse could do, but I wasn't
hurt,'' she said.
   After police surrounded him, animal rescuers took the bird to the
medical center in a van. But Borysenko said his troubles aren't over.
   ``Now all I have to do is figure out how to get him home,'' he
said. ``I guess I'll have to get a van.''
</TEXT>
