<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-30 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Tokyo Stocks Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against the Japanese yen today,
and prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined sharply.
   The dollar closed at 143.08 yen, down 1.07 yen from Tuesday's
close of 144.15 yen. After opening at 142.86 yen, it ranged between
142.78 and 143.20 yen.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's fall was in response to its
slide on the New York market Tuesday.
   ``The dollar's decline halted after it dipped into the 142-yen
range, when everybody felt it had reached the lower end of its
range,'' said a trader at a major commercial bank in Tokyo, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   A dealer at Daiichi Kangyo Bank said the dollar was likely to
remain within a narrow range until the release of U.S. economic
data, including unemployment figures for August, on Friday.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, a 80.24-point gainer Tuesday, fell 215.99 points, or 0.61
percent, closing at 34,471.66.
   Dealers said trading was relatively dull as many institutional
investors retreated to the sidelines after profit-taking outpaced
small-lot buying.
   Among the few gainers were banks, including Mitsui Bank and Taiyo
Kobe Bank, which announced plans on Tuesday to merge.
   Led by the two banks, other bank shares gained moderately, said a
dealer at Nikko Securities Co., also speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
