<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0431EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lutherans     08-30 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lutherans,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lutherans in To-And-Fro Tangle Take Neutral Stance on Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lutherans grappled with the issue of
abortion in an assembly that briefly adopted a resolution some
considered pro-choice before delegates reconsidered and maintained a
neutral position.
   As the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America's first legislative
assembly neared its close today, it recognized that society was in a
``time of crisis'' about abortion, with ``mounting hysteria, fear,
polarization and violence.''
   The newly merged 5.3-million-member denomination settled on a
resolution Tuesday that advised ``information, counseling and
competent Christian guidance'' on abortion. This should be ``based
in the Lutheran traditions of Biblical grounding and social and
individual responsibility,'' the resolution said.
   The delegates avoided defining a position about abortion itself,
leaving that for a two-year study on sexuality and decision by the
next assembly in 1991.
   One delegate, Guy Erwin of New Haven, Conn., unsuccessfully
sought a speeded up process for developing a stand on this
``excruciating, sensitive'' issue, adding, ``We must begin to lead
or be led.''
   The assembly reconsidered and rejected an orginally approved
measure that many delegates interpreted as pro-choice.
   The Rev. Paul Hinlicky of Delhi, N.Y., exclaimed during the
debate, ``I will not obey this call for free access to abortion on
demand.''
   A nurse, Betty Jane Reisner of Whitehall, Pa., pleaded for
retaining the original, saying ``pro-choice allows pro-life. The
reverse is not true.'' To not permit it is ``taking away our
freedom.''
   In the end, delegates reinstated a revised version eliminating a
phrase calling for provision of ``free access to services.''
   Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom, church president, said that if the
original was taken literally it would be contrary to previous church
statements.
   The three denominations that merged into the new body had taken
varying positions, one seeing human life as beginning at conception,
another less definite about it, but both upholding the sanctity of
unborn life.
   On another topic, the assembly urged ``loving care and
compassion'' toward AIDS sufferers, saying they often have been
``met with apathy, indifference or even antagonism and denial.''
   The church affirmed the ``rights and dignity of all persons
living with AIDS,'' and pledged to include them ``in the life and
worship of the church.''
   Steps also were taken for fuller inclusion of youngsters in
future assemblies, and to provide resources to meet needs of the
deaf and other disabled, and also those whose primary language is
not English.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0527EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TwoForks     08-30 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Two Forks,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Review Condemns Proposed $500 Million Water Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of the proposed $500 million Two Forks
dam reacted with anger after a five-month federal review condemned
the water project as unnecessary and environmentally damaging.
   Lee DeHihns, an Environmental Protection Agency deputy regional
administrator from Atlanta who conducted the review, announced
Tuesday that he was recommending the EPA press on with efforts to
kill the project.
   Denver's Water Board said in a statement that the decision was
``a classical example of EPA bureaucratic arrogance that shows a
full disregard for the competency and expertise of a host of
federal, state and local agencies'' that supported the plan.
   ``You simply can't leave us high and dry,'' Mayor Federico Pena
told reporters Tuesday in reaction to DeHihns' announcement. ``We
have not been given a fair, objective appraisal of this project.''
   The 615-foot-high dam to be built 25 miles southwest of Denver
near the confluence of the South Platte River and its North Fork
would flood 30 miles of scenic river valley and canyon and the town
of Deckers, which has fewer than 100 residents.
   ``The Two Forks dam and reservoir project would result in the
loss of a major aquatic resource which provides irreplaceable stream
fishery habitat and recreational resources near the Denver
metropolitan area,'' DeHihns said.
   Peter A.A. Berle, National Audubon Society president, said
DeHihns deserves ``the heartfelt praise and gratitude of all
concerned Americans'' for his balanced review.
   ``His finding that EPA should proceed with a veto of this project
is a major victory in the continuing battle to protect the world
class wildlife habitat downstream on the Platte River in central
Nebraska, as well as Colorado's magnificent Cheesman Canyon,'' Berle
said.
   DeHihns said he was recommending continuation of a veto process
started March 24 by EPA administrator William Reilly. The next step
is two months of hearings. The final decision will be made at EPA
headquarters in Washington.
   DeHihns said vetoes are rarely overturned, and that about 7,000
pieces of mail his office received about Two Forks ran about 10-1
against the project.
   In response to criticism by the mayor and water board, DeHihns
said, ``I'm not happy they're upset. But I'm obliged to carry out my
responsibilities under the law.''
   Denver area water providers, contending new water resources are
needed for a growing metropolitan area, already have spent $40
million in research and planning for Two Forks.
   DeHihns said metropolitan Denver appears to have adequate water
supplies for now. He suggested Denver could put more water
conservation measures in place before.
   EPA officials said DeHihns could have let project proceed or
attach additional environmental requirements. His report said Two
Forks dam and reservoir ``was the most environmentally damaging of
the alternatives examined.''
   Besides flooding a prized trout stream, Two Forks would eliminate
about 300 acres of wetlands, and it would alter the river channel
with possible effects on threatened and endangered species
downstream, including in Nebraska, where officials have been
strongly opposed to the project.
   ``I caution that there are still powerful forces aligned against
us,'' Sen. Jim Exon, D-Neb., said in a statement.
   Sen. Bill Armstrong, R-Colo., called the decision a major setback.
   ``This decision was made by unelected officials applying
subjective standards to a project Coloradans have studied, decided
upon, and funded,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
