<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0555EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-DeGreiff     08-30 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-De Greiff,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Woman Threatened by Drug Lords</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Minister Monica de Greiff, who
drug traffickers want dead, summed up the dangers of her job after
taking office six weeks ago: ``If they want to kill you, they will _
with or without escort.''
   At the time it was merely a realistic statement by a woman who at
32 holds one of the most dangerous government posts in the world.
   Then she became a target in an anonymous phone call from a man
who said: ``You will be the next.''
   Since 1984, her ministry has been a post few covet. In that year,
drug traffickers murdered Justice Minister Rodrigo Lara Bonilla.
   Then, a former justice minister, Enrique Parejo Gonzalez, was
wounded in Budapest, Hungary, where the government had sent him as
ambassador because traffickers had threatened his life.
   Mrs. de Greiff was threatened Thursday, according to press
reports, and hours later she boarded a plane for Washington _ three
days before her original schedule _ amid rumors she had resigned.
   The reasons for her rush to confer with U.S. officials may help
Mrs. De Greiff meet one of her goals as a minister: to obtain money
to pay for protection for Colombia judges threatened by drug barons.
   The traffickers have vowed to kill 10 judges for every drug lord
extradited to the United States.
   As justice minister, Mrs. de Greiff is a member of a committee
deciding on extraditions.
   ``People should not be afraid of carrying out their duties,'' she
said in a Colombian radio interview three weeks ago.
   She told reporters in Washington earlier this week that she did
not intend to quit and that she was asking the Bush administration
for $19 million to build a security system to protect judges and
high officials in her ministry.
   The administration approved $65 million in emergency aid earlier
this month for Colombia's war on drugs.
   Mrs. de Greiff has made it clear that being a Cabinet minister is
the high point for her career as a lawyer. ``I got this job because
I have experience,'' she said recently.
   She graduated in 1980 from the exclusive Bogota University of The
Rosary, a Roman Catholic institution.
   After working for a few months with her father, also a lawyer,
she worked for other private firms developing administrative
experience.
   Mrs. de Greiff entered government service in 1986, when Virgilio
Barco became president. Her career began at the Urban Development
Office of Bogota. She later was appointed general secretary of the
Energy Ministry.
   She became justice minister on July 16 and took an immediate
dislike to the tight security surrounding her and her husband,
Miguel Paley, an Argentine public relations consultant, and their
3-year-old son.
   ``With all those armed guys protecting you, one must avoid going
out. But that is part of the price being in the post,'' she said.
   ``I love my family, but I have less and less time with them,''
she added. ``I hope this situation will improve soon.''
   It did not and when death squads killed leading presidential
hopeful Luis Carlos Galan Aug. 18, Mrs. de Greiff became involved in
an all-out government offensive against drug traffickers.
   As the government conducted raids across the nation, arresting
suspected drug dealers and confiscating millions of dollars in
property, said: ``I am not prepared for times of war like these.''
   The statement was considered untimely, and rumors that she
planned to resign became common in Bogota.
   She said Tuesday in Washington: ``The threats are out there, but
I am satisfied with my protection right now. I am determined that
the integrity of our justice system survives this crisis and I hope
to play my full part in assuring this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
