<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0701EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Burma     08-30 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Deaths in Uprising Not `Worth Mentioning:' Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So few students were killed during last
year's pro-democracy uprising in Burma that they weren't ``worth
mentioning,'' the country's health and education minister said.
   Dr. Pe Thein, addressing a Rangoon meeting Tuesday of scholars
just back from education overseas, said ``students must see the
truth behind last year's incidents.'' A transcript of his remarks,
reported in an official Radio Rangoon broadcast, was seen today in
Bangkok.
   Diplomats, dissidents and international human rights groups
estimate several thousand people were killed last year in a series
of army clampdowns on student-led unrest from March to September.
   According to witness accounts and independent reports, scores of
students were among those killed as troops fired indiscriminately
into crowds of peaceful demonstrators.
   ``I don't mean to say that there were no casualties, only that
there were few casualties, of which students constitute so small a
number as to be not worth mentioning,'' Pe Thein said.
   The military government admitted killing hundreds as it crushed
dissent in September, but it said most were ``looters'' or
``destructive ... unscrupulous elements.''
   Last June, all schools and universities throughout the country
were closed because of the unrest. Though primary and middle schools
recently re-opened, university and high schools remain closed.
   The minister said the country needed technocrats and
intellectuals to reconstruct the nation, but ``school teachers
(must) guide their students to becoming clever people and ...(to)
avoid taking part in destructive acts.''
   Pe Thein told the scholars that attempts were being made to try
to divide the army and the people in Burma.
   He accused foreign broadcasting stations of using ``human rights
issues to portray themselves as the only ones who love the country
and report that the defense forces do not love the nation.''
   ``The defense forces have been portrayed by some as a barbaric
force,'' he said.
   He warned teachers, as public servants, to stay clear of party
politics. ``Despite repeated warnings, we have had to part ways with
some (teachers) because of their contacts with political parties,''
he said.
   Western diplomats in Rangoon have reported authorities arrested
at least 2,000 people since putting the two leaders of the main
opposition group under house arrest on July 20.
   Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo, who head the National League for
Democracy, were accused of trying to divide the people and the
military after criticizing the government's human rights record.
   The U.S. Embassy in Rangoon says it has received ``credible''
reports that many pro-democracy activists have been tortured,
sometimes fatally, after being arrested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
