<DOCNO> AP890830-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0707EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor     08-30 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe of L.A. Mayor Reportedly Uncovers No Criminal Impropriety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City investigators who have spent nearly five
months scrutinizing the personal finances of Mayor Tom Bradley have
uncovered no evidence of criminal wrongdoing, it was reported today.
   Bradley could be fined for alleged improper financial
disclosures, but the man recently re-elected to an unprecedented
fifth term is unlikely to face any criminal charges, the Los Angeles
Times and Los Angeles Herald Examiner reported.
   A final report from City Attorney James K. Hahn is expected
sometime in September. ``The process still is going on. Anything can
happen in two weeks,'' the Times quoted an unnamed source as saying.
   Bradley has said he would not comment on the investigation until
the report is released.
   Hahn's inquiry focuses on the 71-year-old mayor's connection to
Far East National Bank, which paid Bradley $18,000 as a consultant.
   After some inquiries by Bradley, City Treasurer Leonard
Rittenberg subsequently had $2 million in city funds deposited with
the bank. Bradley said he did not pressure Rittenberg and Rittenberg
says he has not been pressured.
   Bradley later returned the $18,000 fee.
   The city attorney also is looking into whether Bradley violated
conflict-of-interest laws by accepting payments from Valley Federal
Savings &amp; Loan Association, as well as more than 100 errors in the
mayor's disclosures regarding extensive stock portfolio and property
holdings.
   Hahn plans to recommend that the city fine Bradley about $200,000
for his financial reporting violations, the newspapers reported.
   In addition to the local probe, federal investigators are probing
Bradley's many investments with Drexel Burnham Lambert and Michael
Milken, the former junk-bond king who recently resigned after being
indicted for fraud.
</TEXT>
