<FIRST>r a PM-Swindall     08-30 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swindall,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swindall Airs Story of Abuse As A Child</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after he was sentenced to a year
in prison for perjury, Pat Swindall said he decided not to testify
at his trial to avoid revealing that he and his siblings were abused
by their father.
   The former congressman said Tuesday he decided to disclose the
family secret after discussions with his brothers, Kevin and Philip,
and his sister, Theresa. Kevin and Theresa joined him at his home in
suburban Atlanta for the news conference.
   ``My father's a very sick man,'' Swindall said.
   Swindall's father, Nathan, denied the allegations of abuse.
   Swindall, a Republican who represented Georgia's 4th District in
Congress for two terms until his defeat in 1988, was sentenced
Monday to a year in prison for his conviction on nine counts of
perjury. He also was fined $30,000 plus $450 in court costs.
   The former congressman said immediately after his trial that he
did not take the stand because a deposition taken in connection with
a dispute with his father ``contained information about something my
father did to a family member.''
   Swindall said Tuesday he felt certain that prosecutors would have
asked him on the witness stand about the alleged incidents, which he
described a day earlier as ``so disgusting I will not even publicly
disclose it.''
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr said Tuesday night he did not believe
the prosecution would have raised the allegations during the June
trial.
   ``As far as I can tell this has nothing to do with his case; he's
having a severe case of Monday morning quarterbacking,'' Barr said.
   Swindall's sister said her father had sexually abused her as a
young teen-ager, but that her siblings had agreed not to discuss the
matter publicly until now.
   Nathan Swindall denied abusing his daughter.
   ``When anybody accuses me of incest he better be proving it. I
deny that completely,'' he said.
   Swindall, 38, remains free on his own recognizance pending an
appeal.
   Swindall was convicted June 20 lying to a federal grand jury in
1988 about his negotiations for an $850,000 loan from a federal
agent posing as a drug money launderer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
