<FIRST>r a PM-Newspage-NFL-Steroids 1stLd-Writethru a0chFees.ByJoyceA.Venezia.Shouldstand.
08-30 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage-NFL-Steroids, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirteen Players Suspended After Testing Positive for Steroids</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2nd graf to indicate these are the first suspensions
of any professional athlete for steriod use. A longer version moved on
sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE GOLDBERG ^AP Football Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Football League suspended 13 players
who tested positive for steroids, indicating that warnings of a
crackdown on the muscle-building drugs months ago may have worked.
   The action marked the first time U.S. professional athletes had
been suspended for steriod use. No other league conducts mandatory
tests for the drugs.
   The small number of suspensions under the new steroid policy
seemed to please even the NFL Players Association, which has
challenged the accuracy of tests and the suspensions.
   ``The fact that so few players have been suspended for alleged
steroid use indicates that the public perception of the steroid
problem in the NFL is greatly exaggerated,'' said Gene Upshaw,
executive director of the union and former All-Pro guard.
   Of the 13 players suspended for four weeks, only Pro Bowl guard
Ron Solt of the Philadelphia Eagles was of any prominence.
   Meanwhile, two other prominent players were suspended for using
illegal drugs. All-Pro cornerback Leroy Irvin of the Los Angeles
Rams and tight end Orson Mobley of Denver will miss the final
exhibition game and the first three regular-season games.
   Commissioner Pete Rozelle announced the steroid policy on March
21, saying he wanted to allow time for players who might be using
steroids to get them out of their system before the start of
training camp. A letter detailing the plan was sent 10 days later to
all players.
   In both 1987 and 1988, 6 percent of the players had positive
steroid tests, but no suspensions were imposed.
   The percentages were much lower this time. The NFL tested more
than 2,200 players for both illegal drugs and steroids. An
unspecified number of players tested positive but already have been
cut from their teams, the league said.
   The warnings seem to have worked, even by the testimony of one of
those caught, linebacker Mark Mraz of the Los Angeles Raiders.
   ``He was very disappointed and very emotional,'' coach Mike
Shanahan said. ``He said he was aware of the new policy since April
1. He informed me that he had not been on them since then.''
   But Coach Lindy Infante of Green Bay, who lost offensive linemen
Keith Uecker and Mike Ariey, said the warnings may not have been
enough.
   ``After all that was mentioned about it and all the letters that
had gone out and all the notoriety about the decision to test for it
and punish the people caught for it, I'm quite shocked that anybody
would run the risk of this happening,'' Infante said.
   The 13 players also included three Buffalo Bills _ brothers Tom
Doctor, a linebacker, and Sean Doctor, a fullback, and linebacker
Matt Jaworksi.
   Others were defensive back Maurice Douglass of the Chicago Bears,
running back Vince Amoia and wide receiver Bobby Riley of the New
York Jets, tight end Vernon Kirk of the Los Angeles Rams, and
running back Keith Henderson and nose tackle Rollin Putzier of San
Francisco.
   Coach Joe Walton of the Jets said he would release Amoia and
Riley.
   But General Manager Harry Gamble of the Eagles said he would
welcome back Solt. And Buffalo general manager Bill Polian said all
three of his suspended players will make the team.
   ``They are not druggies,'' Polian said. ``They're good kids who
made a mistake and are paying the penalty for it.''
   Upshaw said some players had called the union claiming they were
innocent. He suggested that tests may have mistaken other medication
as steroids or ``masking agents'' designed to hide the their
presence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
