<FIRST>u i PM-Glemp 1stLd-Writethru   08-30 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Glemp, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0481,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>Primate's Comments on Jews Stir New Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to MOVE UP Polish newspaper criticism, and
edits to conform. Pickup 11th pvs, `Referring to...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic journalist, in a rare
criticism of the church, said Cardinal Jozef Glemp's remarks about
Jews may be ``deeply wounding'' to people who lost loved ones in the
Nazi holocaust.
   Criticism of Glemp's comments on Jewish-Catholic relations spread
worldwide on Tuesday, although some Catholic clerics said the Polish
primate's remarks may have been misconstrued.
   Glemp told pilgrims at Jasna Gora Monastery at Czestochowa on
Saturday that Polish anti-Semitism would disappear if Jews abandon
``anti-Polonism,'' or anti-Polish sentiments.
   He asked Jews to understand that it offended Poles' religious
sensibilities and feelings of sovereignty to insist on removal of a
Carmelite convent set up on the edge of the former Nazi death camp
at Auschwitz.
   ``Dear Jews, do not talk to us from the position of a nation
elevated over all others and do not put to us conditions that are
impossible to meet,'' Glemp said.
   But he intensified charges of anti-Semitism by using language
that invoked the image of Jews spreading communism and by saying
that Jews collaborated with Nazis during World War II, that Jews as
businessmen neglected or detested Poles and that Jews have easy
access to mass media.
   Polish Catholic journalist Krzysztof Sliwinski said: ``The
expressions used by the primate, even contrary to his intentions,
pose a danger of deeply wounding the feelings of many of those who
are descendants and brothers of the Holocaust victims.''
   The rare published criticism appeared Monday in the Polish
opposition's Gazeta Wyborcza newspaper.
   Cardinal Albert DeCourtray, archbishop of Lyon in France, said
Tuesday it was unlikely that Glemp's words were meant the way they
were received.
   He said the ``primate and bishops of Poland cannot be accused of
an anti-Semitism, which they denounce.''
   Referring to Glemp's comment about easy Jewish access to mass
media, the International League against Racism and Anti-Semitism
said in Paris that he had ``made use of arguments used against Jews
by the Nazis yesterday and by the extreme right in France today.''
   Yossi Sarid, a legislator from the left-wing Citizens Rights
Movement in Israel, said Tuesday in Jerusalem, ``Anti-Semitism has a
long history in Poland, and I think it is ridiculous to talk about
`anti-Polonism.'''
   Rome's chief rabbi, Elio Toaff, said in a newspaper interview
that the question of anti-Semitism is something the church ``has to
face. ... The analysis has to be deep enough to eradicate once and
for all the anti-Semitism that still exists in many countries, like
Poland.''
   ``It is particularly serious that it was Glemp, one noted for
diplomacy and political gifts, who confused cause and effects,''
said Tullia Zevi, head of the Union of Italian Jewish Communities,
quoted in the same article Monday in Rome's I Messaggero.
   The Representative Council of Jewish Institutions of France
issued a statement Monday calling Glemp's comments ``malicious and
out of place.''
   John Cardinal O'Connor, the archbishop of New York, said Tuesday
he was ``shocked'' by Glemp's ``harmful'' remarks.
   In a news conference, O'Connor also called on Polish church
officials to honor their commitment to move the Carmelite convent at
Auschwitz.
   The convent site has been criticized as offensive because an
estimated 2.5 million of the 4 million victims of Auschwitz-Birkenau
were executed simply for being Jewish.
   Only several thousand Jews live in Poland today compared with a
pre-war Jewish population of 3.5 million.
   Relations between the Catholic Church in Poland and Jewish groups
have been strained since Aug. 10 when Cardinal Franciszek Macharski
of Krakow, whose diocese includes the camp, announced the church was
suspending a 1987 agreement to move the convent. He said it could
not fulfill the agreement in an atmosphere of ``aggressive demands.''
   O'Connor said Glemp's comments could be construed to shift ``the
blame to the Jews for demanding that a signed accord be carried
out.''
   ``I don't think that is just, and I don't think that is
charitable. And it certainly doesn't represent my position,''
O'Connor said.
   The proposal to remove the convent, founded in 1984 just outside
the Auschwitz fence, has found little sympathy in Poland. Poles have
argued that thousands of the victims at Auschwitz were Polish
political prisoners, including many priests and nuns.
   Most Poles acknowledge that anti-Semitism still exists in Poland.
But some say its depth is exaggerated and note that many Poles
risked their lives to protect Jews during the war.
</TEXT>
