<DOCNO> AP890830-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0948EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     08-30 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians, Christians Battle; Rounds Hit Near Peace Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces battled for
six hours with artillery in Beirut today, and mortar rounds exploded
near a meeting between a French peace envoy and a Moslem leader.
   Police said one person was killed and 19 wounded in the fighting.
The latest casualties raised the toll from the nearly six months of
clashes to at least 803 killed and 2,287 wounded.
   The French envoy, Francois Scheer, drove from the Christian
sector across Beirut's dividing Green Line into Moslem west Beirut
during mortar and sniper exchanges. He met with Sheik Mohammed Mehdi
Shamseddine, the senior Shiite Moslem cleric in Lebanon.
   Scheer traveled with an escort of two carloads of bodyguards.
   During a 45-minute meeting at Shamseddine's second-floor
apartment in the Tallet Khayat district, five mortar rounds exploded
nearby.
   Scheer and Shamseddine moved from his living room to an interior
hallway for safety while they finished their discussions, according
to an Associated Press photographer at the meeting.
   The Christian Voice of Lebanon radio said two Frenchmen with an
engineering team, Alain Guigard and Pierre Paron, were wounded by
mortar shrapnel in Christian east Beirut today. Telephone lines were
out, and French Embassy officials could not be reached.
   Today's fighting flared early this morning after Syrian gunners
bombarded the 28-mile coastline of the besieged Christian enclave
north of Beirut.
   ``Their radar must have detected some ship movements off the
Christian enclave,'' said a spokesman on condition of anonymity.
   No ships were reported hit today.
   A Maltese-flagged tanker, the Sunshield, was hit and set on fire
by Syrian shells Tuesday as it tried to run the Syrian blockade.
Seven crewmen were killed and two were wounded. Police said two were
missing and believed dead.
   Before meeting Shamseddine, Scheer met with Patriarch Nasrallah
Sfeir, spiritual leader of the Maronite Catholic sect, for 90
minutes at his seat in the mountain-peak resort of Bkirki north of
Beirut.
   No details of the talks were reported. In addition, the envoy
declined comment on other talks he held Tuesday with Gen. Michel
Aoun, the Christian leader, and acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a
Sunni Moslem.
   Scheer, secretary-general of France's Foreign Ministry, arrived
in Beirut Tuesday after two days of talks with Syrian leaders in
Damascus.
   The French peace plan calls for lifting blockades by both sides,
a halt to arms deliveries to the warring factions, political reforms
to distribute power equally between Christians and Moslems, and the
withdrawal of Syrian and Israeli forces from Lebanon.
   Another peace envoy, Soviet Gennady Tasarov, left Iraq for Moscow
today after talks with the Palestine Liberation chairman, Yasser
Arafat, and Iraqi leaders. He has been trying to revive a stalled
Arab League peace effort.
   After the fighting broke out in March, Aoun declared a ``war of
liberation'' to drive the Syrians out of Lebanon. The troops came
under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate, but Aoun says they
are really backing the Moslems in the nation's 14-year-old civil war.
</TEXT>
