<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SovietUnrest     08-30 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Unrest,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moldavians Considering Language Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moldavia's Communist Party chief, in an effort to
placate outraged minority groups, proposed today that the republic
adopt a weaker version of a law making Moldavian the official
language, an activist said.
   The compromise, which reportedly resulted from a telephone
conversation between the party chief and President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, is aimed at stopping widespread strikes and other
protests in the republic.
   The initial proposed law would substitute Moldavian for Russian
in virtually all government and business transactions in the
republic. Russians and other minorities in the republic say the
proposal is discriminatory.
   The proposed compromise, outlined to the Supreme Soviet by
Moldavian party chief Semen Grossu, would make Moldavian the
language for government officials and documents, and Russian the
tongue for everyday contact among the republic's ethnic groups.
   The compromise was reported by Vasily Nestase, a leader of the
pro-Moldavian People's Front who spoke by telephone from the
republic's capital, Kishinev.
   Moldavia, which borders Romania, now has no law specifying which
language is to be used, but Russian has traditionally been the
tongue for government affairs.
   Grossu proposed the compromise after reporting he had spoken with
Gorbachev by telephone Tuesday night about the language controversy.
The Moldavian party chief did not say whether Gorbachev had
suggested the compromise, but Nestase said it was widely believed
this was the case.
   ``We think this is the most realistic compromise,'' Nataly
Pascal, another People's Front member, said in a telephone
interview. ``We support this compromise and we're not the only
ones.''
   The Moldavian Supreme Soviet began debating the proposal on
Tuesday, and Nestase said the session would continue Thursday.
   Gorbachev has quietly been involved in several attempts recently
to quell nationalist unrest breaking out in may of the Soviet
Union's republics. He told the Lithuanian party chief during the
weekend that the independence movement there had gone too far.
   Gorbachev also ``worked out'' with other members of the ruling
Politburo a tough party statement Saturday condemning nationalism,
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told a news briefing
Tuesday. The statement by the policy-making Central Committee warned
that independence movements were leading the country into an
``abyss.''
   A strike organizer in the Moldavian city of Tiraspol, where
Russians and other minorities walked off their jobs last week to
protest the proposed language law, said strikers were willing to
consider the compromise even though they would still prefer that
Russian and Moldavian be given equal status.
   The weekly Moscow News today highlighted unemployment as a factor
in the republic's unrest. It said at least 150,000 of the republic's
4.2 million people are unemployed, and the number is growing.
   Pravda repeated earlier criticism of People's Front activists,
accusing them of ``spreading the seeds of separatism and
nationalism'' and claiming that Moldavian parliamentarians ordered
Pravda correspondent to leave the republic.
   The Supreme Soviet session addressing the law opened Tuesday, and
several thousand people, some carrying red-yellow-and-blue Moldavian
banners, gathered after the debate in downtown Kishinev to show
support for the People's Front.
   ``We have to seize the moment,'' said Ala Myndycanu, a member of
the People's Front governing council. ``We have to solve our
problems before Moscow does.''
   But non-Moldavian activists, members of the Russian-language
group Yedinstvo, warned that ``life won't be quiet'' if the original
law was passed over the objections of strikers.
   Disgruntled Russian-speaking residents of the republic are
striking at almost 200 factories and offices to protest the bill,
said Vsevolod Yampolsky of the Tiraspol strike committee. Most of
the strikes are in cities with large Russian populations.
   Tass reported today that railroad workers in several Moldavian
cities had joined the strike.
   The portion of the bill that would be cut out under the
compromise would have made Moldavian the language among Russians,
Ukrainians, Jews, Bulgarians, and other nationalities in the
republic. That goes farther than the language laws in a number of
other republics.
   Many non-Moldavians do not speak Moldavian, but they share some
knowledge of Russian as a result of Soviet schooling.
   The law also would restore the Latin alphabet, replacing the
Cyrillic imposed by dictator Josef Stalin after he annexed Moldavia
from Romania in 1940. Stalin imposed the Cyrillic, used in Russian,
to back up his claim that Romanians and Moldavians are two distinct
nationalities.
   Ethnic Moldavians make up 64 percent of the republic's 4.2
million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
