<FIRST>u i PM-Poland     08-30 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Lawmaker: Break Communist Monopoly on Foreign Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Solidarity lawmaker criticized the
Communists' foreign policy record today and suggested a
non-Communist official should be named foreign minister in Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki's new government.
   Bronislaw Geremek, head of the Solidarity parliamentary
delegation, also said in the pro-Solidarity Gazeta Wyborcza
newspaper today that the Communists should assume at least one
economic ministry so the party would have a sense of
``co-responsibility'' for economic policy.
   Communist leaders have been pressing to keep the ministry of
foreign affairs in the hands of current Foreign Minister Tadeusz
Olechowski, a party member.
   The post is one of several areas of conflict as Mazowiecki, a
longtime Solidarity activist, forms the East bloc's first government
led by non-Communists.
   Geremek has said that the new government would be announced
before Sept. 10. Mazowiecki assumed office on Aug. 24.
   ``Experiences in Polish foreign policy ... indicate that the
(Communist Party) does not serve'' national interests, Geremek said
in the interview published today.
   He cited a recent agreement with Warsaw Pact ally East Germany
over disputed waters in the Baltic Sea near the port of Szczecin,
which many Poles believe was settled to Poland's disadvantage.
   Geremek noted that the information department of the foreign
ministry legally ``functions as a service unit for the Central
Committee'' of the party. This ``does not correspond to the
requirements of the new period,'' he said.
   Although Geremek did not say specifically that the ministry
should be taken away from the party, his remarks about breaking the
party's monopoly on foreign policy appeared to indicate that the
ministry should go either to Solidarity or one of two minor allied
parties, the United Peasants and the Democrats.
   Communist Party Secretary Leszek Miller, who is acting as the
party's envoy in the coalition talks with Mazowiecki, argued
strongly Tuesday for the party to retain control of the ministry.
   ``We think that the best candidate is Tadeusz Olechowski,'' he
said in an interview with the party paper Trybuna Ludu. ``If
professionalism is a criterion, then undoubtedly Olechowski is an
expert of the highest class.''
   He also cited Poland's alliances in the East bloc that he said
have protected national security.
   ``No matter what you accuse the party of, its foreign policy is
not subject to criticism,'' Miller said. ``It has guaranteed us a
safe, stable place in Europe, Poland's favorable position in the
world and alliances which allow us a feeling of national security.
   ``Society needs this feeling and it has to be maintained.''
   Geremek said he favored only limited participation by the
Communists in the Mazowiecki government. ``Broad participation .. .
would not be understandable to public opinion,'' he said.
   Solidarity already has promised the Communists control of the
important defense and interior ministries, which control the army
and police.
   Geremek reiterated in today's article that the party ought to
take one of the five economic ministries: finance, agriculture,
foreign trade, labor or industry. That way it ``could not be in
opposition to the government's economic policy and spread social
demagogy,'' he said.
   He suggested that non-Communist adminstrators serve just below
the defense and interior ministers.
   Another controversial area is control of the mass media. Geremek
said the committee that oversees state radio and television should
be put under control of parliament, where Solidarity and its allies
hold a majority.
   Personnel decisions in radio and television will be one of the
quickest signs of change under the new government, Geremek said.
</TEXT>
