<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BushAppointments 1stLd-Writethru a0428 08-30 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Appointments, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Say Bush Isn't Filling Top Vacancies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs graf 8, A telephone call, with White House comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration appears to be largely
``on automatic pilot'' because of the president's failure to fill
many top executive branch positions, Democratic congressional
researchers say.
   Bush had not nominated anyone by Aug. 9 to fill 160 of the top
394 positions requiring Senate confirmation, the Democratic Study
Group said Tuesday.
   ``It is believed that this number of vacancies so late in a
president's first year in office is without precedent,'' the report
said.
   Among them, although Bush has said he wants to be remembered as
an ``education president,'' are five of the seven assistant
secretaries of education, it said.
   Four assistant administrator slots are vacant at the
Environmental Protection Agency and the president has not nominated
anyone as chairman of the Council on Environmental Quality, the
report said. Openings were also listed for three undersecretaries
and 13 assistant secretaries in other departments.
   ``It appears as though a significant portion of the government is
on automatic pilot,'' said the DSG, an organization of House
Democrats that provides research papers to members of Congress.
   The DSG said it did not have comparable figures for past
administrations, although its analysis in May showed that four
previous presidents had made appointments during their first six
weeks in office at a pace two to four times as fast as Bush.
   Deputy White House Press Secretary Stephen Hart, reached by
telephone in Kennebunkport, Maine, where the president is
vacationing, said the administration's count is not the same as the
DSG's.
   ``Their numbers conflict because they wanted to go with the
broadest brush to try and add to the sensational nature of their
conclusions,'' Hart said.
   The White House counts 308 presidential appointments within the
Cabinet departments. Hart said appointees to 129 of these posts have
been confirmed, and 38 are awaiting confirmation. He said 25 Reagan
appointees had been retained and 84 candidates were now being
cleared for appointment. He said most of the remaining 37 vacancies
had candidates under consideration.
   ``The notion that somehow George Bush has been crippled by the
fact that he hasn't got all of his assistant secretaries in place
just doesn't make any sense,'' Hart said.
   The DSG report dealt with a larger figure because it included
posts outside of the Cabinet departments.
   The report said that as of Aug. 10, only 156 of the 394 positions
were filled by an appointee confirmed by the Senate. Nominations for
60 positions were awaiting confirmation, and remain so since
Congress has been in recess.
   Two nominations, of John Tower to be secretary of defense and
William Lucas to be assistant attorney general for civil rights,
were rejected. Tower was turned down by the full Senate and Lucas by
the Judiciary Committee.
   For 16 positions, appointees of former President Reagan have been
asked to remain on the job.
   ``It is not clear how the failure to fill so many key positions
in a timely manner will affect the Bush administration or the
country generally,'' the report said. ``It does, however, appear to
set the administration on a course that is virtually 180 degrees at
variance with the prevailing view of scholars and former White House
officials on how the presidency should be managed.''
   Defenders of the administration have argued that Bush did not
need to move quickly because he succeeded a president of his own
party and thus did not need to make major policy changes.
   The DSG, however, said the slower pace ``could be as important a
liability to the Bush administration as it would be to any other.''
   Even if the remaining nominations are made and confirmed quickly
this fall, those people would have missed most of the planning for
next year's budget and legislative initiatives, the report said.
   All of the Cabinet positions have been filled. However, posts for
which no nomination has been made and no Reagan holdover is in place
include two assistant secretaries of agriculture, an undersecretary
of commerce, a deputy undersecretary and six assistant secretaries
of defense, an assistant secretary of energy, two assistant
secretaries of health and human services, two assistant secretaries
of housing and urban development, an assistant secretary of the
interior, a deputy attorney general and associate attorney general,
an undersecretary and an assistant secretary of state, an
undersecretary and an assistant secretary of the treasury and three
assistant secretaries of veterans' affairs.
   The only department at which all the top posts have been filled
is Transportation, the report said.
</TEXT>
