<FIRST>u w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0522 08-30 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Calls Special OAS Meeting on Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with official statement, British call for
Noriega's ouster, deadline of Panama's president; picks up at pvs 5th graf,
The OAS ^By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At U.S. request, the Organization of American
States will hold a special meeting Thursday to present evidence of
the alleged involvement of Panama's military leader Manuel Antonio
Noriega in drug trafficking, it was announced today.
   Thursday is the expiration date of the term of Panama's
provisional president, Manuel Solias Palma, appointed by the
National Assembly last year. U.S. officials and Panama's opposition
parties are concerned that Noriega will name a puppet government and
ignore calls for free elections.
   The meeting will come just one week after the OAS dealt a blow to
U.S. hopes of ousting the general by adopting a resolution that
stopped short of calling on Noriega to step down.
   In requesting the meeting, the United States said it wants to
present ``a summary of the evidence and elaboration of the United
States position on the critical situation in Panama,'' the OAS press
office said.
   The decision to call for a meeting of the hemispheric council
came in response to a challenge by Panama's delegate at last week's
session for the United States to present evidence of Noriega's
alleged wrongdoings, said U.S. officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   They said it was not yet clear whether the evidence will be
presented by Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger, who
represented the United States at last week's session, or by another
official.
   In London, meanwhile, the British Foreign Office today urged
Noriega to step down and ``open the way to a peaceful, democratic
resolution of Panama's problems.''
   The OAS resolution last week expressed deep concern over the
failure of a mediating team dispatched by the organization to
promote a democratic transfer of power in Panama.
   The document called on Panamanians to settle their differences by
Sept. 1, the date on which the constitution calls for the
installation of a new president.
   Most OAS delegates viewed U.S. demands that Noriega step down as
a dangerous precedent for intervention in the internal affairs of
member states.
   The United States has been pressing Noriega to step down since
February 1988, when he was indicted by two federal grand juries in
Florida on charges involving drug trafficking.
   Noriega has claimed the efforts are an attempt to renege on the
U.S. pledge to hand over the Panama Canal to his country's control
next year.
   Noriega has served as commander of the Panamanian Defense Forces
for six years. U.S. officials believe he will install a puppet
successor next month, after voiding results of May 7 elections that
observers agree gave a wide majority to the U.S.-backed opposition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
