<FIRST>r a PM-PesticideEvacuation     08-30 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pesticide Evacuation,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burning Pesticides Force Temporary Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAVENNA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 people were allowed home after
they were evacuated early today because of burning pesticides at a
nearby feed store.
   Several residents reported breathing problems and a few
firefighters were overcome by smoke, but there were no serious
injuries, said Lt. Andrew Casciato of the Ravenna Fire Department.
   A three-block area, which included apartments and group homes for
the elderly, was evacuated, he said.
   The fire was under control but still smoldering at 9 a.m., more
than three hours after it was reported at the Ravenna Landmark
Grainery.
   The fire broke out in a section that contained fertilizers and
pesticides, Casciato said. The area was destroyed, Casciato said.
   ``The product itself was being consumed by the fire. We didn't
want to put water on it because that would allow it to contaminate
the ground,'' he said.
   The fertilizers and pesticides were allowed to burn out, although
some water was initially used to cool down the area and keep the
fire from spreading to adjoining buildings, he said.
   Timothy Hickin, a duty officer at the Ohio Environmental
Protection Agency in Columbus, said investigators would be sent into
the building when the fire was completely extinguished.
</TEXT>
