<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary-Refugees     08-30 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Refugees,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan Reportedly in Works to Transport East Germans to West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Red Cross is working on
a plan to transport at least 1,500 East German refugees from Hungary
to the West in the next few days, an Austrian government source said
today.
   The report came amid heightened speculation that officials were
formulating a plan to deal with thousands of East Germans who have
traveled to Hungary in an effort to flee their Communist homeland
for the West.
   A report in the Munich-based Abendzeitung newspaper today said
15,000 East Germans would be allowed to go West from Hungary by the
weekend.
   The crush of East Germans, who have also tried to flee this
summer through East Berlin and Czechoslovakia, has created friction
between East Germany and several other nations and forced West
Germany to close diplomatic facilities that have been overwhelmed by
refugees in several East bloc cities.
   The Austrian government source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the International Red Cross plan involves
transporting the refugees from Hungary to Austria and then to West
Germany. The source said it was not yet clear if they would leave
Hungary by train or airplane.
   There was speculation that a West German envoy sent to Austria
today was trying to work out the reported plan.
   West Germany dispatched the senior diplomat to meet Austrian
Foreign Minister Alois Mock, Foreign Ministry spokesman Walter
Greinert said.
   The spokesman said Bonn envoy Michael Jansen thanked Mock for
Austria's role in offering help to thousands of East Germans who had
already fled across the Hungarian-Austrian border. He declined to
comment on whether Jansen was working on a Red Cross plan.
   Rezsoe Sztuchlik, head of the Foreign Relations department of
Hungary's Red Cross, said he had no knowledge of such a plan.
   In Budapest, however, a senior Foreign Ministry official, Gyula
Szelei, told The Associated Press that Hungary is working with both
East and West Germany to deal with the refugees.
   The rush of refugees began in Hungary after reform-minded
Communist Hungarian authorities began removing border fences in May.
   Some refugees say they are fleeing the hard-line Communist system
in East Germany, but others say they are simply looking for a better
economic life.
   Last week, Hungary allowed 108 East Germans holed up in the West
German Embassy in Budapest to go to West Germany in a plan also
organized by the Geneva-based International Red Cross.
   But Bonn and Budapest said it was a one-time occurrence.
   There are 2,200 East Germans in camps set up by the Hungarian Red
Cross for those who want to flee West, with 150 new arrivals each
day, said Sztuchlik.
   At least 200 other East Germans are holed up in Bonn's closed
missions in East Berlin and Prague hoping to go to West Germany,
where they receive automatic citizenship and assistance in starting
a new life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-NorthernIreland 2ndLd-Writethru a0521 08-30 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0521,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protestant Gunmen Say Leaked Police Data Led to Murder</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to CLARIFY that Cope not ruling out possibility
that documents were stolen sted leaked. Pickup graf 9th pvs, `In his...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British official today said
authorities will investigate whether security forces in Northern
Ireland leaked documents that helped Protestant gunman identify a
Roman Catholic man they later killed.
   However, John Cope, the minister of state for Northern Ireland,
also suggested that the Protestant group members made the claim to a
reporter of the British Broadcasting Corp. in order to discredit the
police.
   BBC reporter Chris Moore said in a television report Tuesday that
he had met with four masked men from the outlawed Ulster Freedom
Fighters, or UFF, over the weekend. He said he was taken to a house
where he was shown the police documents and a videotape about
suspected members of the Irish Republican Army.
   The predominantly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the 60 percent Protestant province with
the 95 percent Catholic Irish Republic.
   Among those named in the police material was 28-year-old Loughlin
Maginn, who was shot to death Friday in his home in Rathfriland.
   The Ulster Freedom Fighters, a cover name for the Protestant
Ulster Defense Association, claimed it killed Maginn because he was
a member of the IRA. Maginn's family has denied the claim and said
he had been harassed by security forces for a year.
   Moore said he was told the group got the documents through a
``breach of security at security force bases,'' but he said they did
not elaborate. In his comments, Cope did not rule out that the
documents could have been stolen rather than leaked.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, or RUC, the police force of the
British province, also said it was investigating the claim.
   In his comments, Cope said, ``One can only speculate as to why
the UFF have chosen to talk to the media in this way.''
   ``Like the IRA, the UFF has every reason to hate the RUC whose
efforts have put many of its members behind bars. It is not
surprising that they will do their best to try to discredit the
police and use the media for this purpose,'' he said.
   The government of Ireland, which has a consultative role in the
province's affairs, said it was seeking an ``urgent clarification''
on the report from the British government.
   The Ulster Defense Association was formed in September 1971 as a
coordinator for paramilitary groups that supported continued British
rule of Northern Ireland.
   The Freedom Fighters group, like the IRA, is outlawed in Northern
Ireland and its members are barred from appearing on television or
radio.
   There have been past cases in which members of the Ulster Defense
Regiment, a local army unit that is being converted to a full-time
force, were involved in sectarian murders.
   In 1980, several police informers were killed after the IRA
obtained information from reserve police officers.
</TEXT>
