<FIRST>r w PM-Corcoran-Protests     08-30 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Corcoran-Protests,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gallery Boycott Leads to Postponement of Exhibits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boycott by some artists of the Corcoran
Gallery over its cancellation of a photography exhibit including
pictures of genitalia has led to the ``indefinite postponement'' of
two other scheduled contempory art exhibits, gallery officials said
today.
   The scheduling and then cancellation in June of the exhibit by
Robert Mapplethorpe touched off a political controversy that
resulted in Congress moving to restrict federal subsidies for
artists.
   The gallery said today contemporary artist Annette Lemieux has
pulled what it described as her ``first major one-person museum
exhibition'' scheduled to run from Oct. 28 to Dec. 31. and that six
scupltors also have canceled a show of their work scheduled to run
from next Feb. 3 to April 8.
   Deborah Shriver, a spokeswoman for the Corcoran, acknowledged
that l0 American painters, including Ms. Lemieux, featured in a
joint U.S.-Soviet exhibition to be featured next spring also have
threatened to deny the gallery the right to display their work.
   ``As far as we know, that show is still on,'' Ms. Shriver said of
the spring 1990 exhibit _ ``10 plus 10: Contemporary Soviet and
American Painters,'' a touring show arranged by the Modern Art
Museum of Fort Worth. ``But we realize that the artists are upset.''
   Ms. Lemieux notified the gallery in a letter last week that she
was withdrawing her exhibit. A week earlier, two of the six
sculptors in the exhibit titled ``The Resonance of the Odd Object,''
notified the Corcoran they were canceling their show.
   ``We believe the Corcoran, by its regrettable decision, not only
compromised its own curatorial standards, but also demonstrated its
complicity with the punishment subsequently attempted against other
art instititions,'' sculptors Buss Spector and Donald Lipski wrote.
   The Corcoran canceled the Mapplethorpe exhibit two weeks before
it was to go on display after protesting members of Congress
objected to three pictures of genitalia and homosexual activities in
it.
   The House later voted to cut the National Endowment of the Arts'
budget by $45,000 _ the total of federal grants received by
Mapplethorpe and Andres Serrano, a photographer whose picture of a
crucifix in a jar of urine also touched off a protest.
   And the Senate last month approved legislation by Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., that would prohibit federal financng of sexually
explict artwork.
   ``This is what we feared from day one,'' Christina Orr-Cahall,
the Corcoran's director, told The Washington Post. ``We're in the
middle of the storm.''
</TEXT>
