<FIRST>r w PM-SchoolLunch     08-30 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Lunch,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Fat-Laden Foods Barrier to Healthy School Lunches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Free ``fat-laden foods'' given to schools by
the Agriculture Department are key obstacles to healthy school lunch
programs, a consumer nutrition group said today.
   Sixty-seven percent of the school food service directors
questioned this spring by Public Voice for Food and Health Policy
said the USDA's commodity distribution program is one of the most
significant barriers to their efforts to provide nutritious meals.
   The school lunch programs depend upon commodities provided free
of charge by the federal government to help them stay afloat
financially, ``yet the commodities offered include a high proportion
of fat-laden foods,'' said the report, which is a followup to
previous studies assessing the progress being made to reduce fat in
school lunches.
   Scott Dunn, acting administator of USDA's Food and Nutrition
Service, said the department is committed to dietary guidelines
developed jointly with the Department of Health and Human Services.
   But he said the guidelines don't set quantitative standards for
fat, and ``there is no scientific consensus on appropriate levels of
fat in children's diets.''
   More than 80 percent of the directors agreed that efforts are
needed to reduce fat in their school lunches and said they have
taken some steps toward that end.
   Yet many of the directors said they were unaware that most health
authorities agree that fat in children's diets should be reduced to
about 30 percent of calories, Public Voice said. Twenty-eight
percent were uncertain of the proper average level of fat in school
lunches.
   ``The U.S. Department of Agriculture has provided only limited
guidance to the directors on how to cut back on fat to achieve this
level, such as through comprehensive hands-on training in meal
preparation or guidance on working with food suppliers,'' said the
study.
   Other findings included:
   _Only 6 percent of the directors have established target levels
or ranges for fat in their programs. Central city school districts
are eight times more likely to establish such limits than are rural
districts.
   _Twenty-three percent of those questioned said they did not
receive any guidance or guidelines on how to purchase foods or
modify recipes to reduce fat. The rest reported having limited
access to written materials or training programs.
   _When asked to identify the single most important thing that
could be done to help reduce fat, 50 percent said change the
commodity program and 26 percent said provide nutrition education.
   Public Voice recommended that the Agriculture Department provide
greater leadership in educating school food service directors and in
offering assistance in planning monthly menus, including suggesting
how often specific foods should be served.
   The USDA also should significantly expand the availability of
lower-fat commodities to the schools, the group added.
   Dunn said ``it is important to remember that no matter what level
is deemed appropriate, that level must be applied to a person's
entire diet, not to a single food or a single meal. USDA cannot at
this time support setting quantitative fat standards or recommended
frequency of serving certain foods.''
   The variety of foods donated to schools is under constant review,
he said in a statement, adding that ``over the years significant
progress has been made in providing more and more healthy, wholesome
foods, including additional low-and reduced-fat foods.''
   In addition, the agency promotes and coordinates nutrition
education and technical assistance for all involved in the school
lunch program, he said. But states ``have great flexibility in how
they spend the money they have available for training.''
   ``Technical assistance and educational materials have recently
been revised and distributed to school food service directors,''
Dunn said. ``These include recipe cards, a commodity foods
newsletter and information on fat and cholesterol.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
