<SECOND>PM-Seabrook Drill,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Staff Recommends On-Site Drill Be Graded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission should
disregard a request by operators of the Seabrook nuclear power plant
that they not be graded on an emergency exercise scheduled next
month, the NRC staff says.
   Operators of the long-delayed, $6.1 billion plant asked the NRC
early this month not to grade the Sept. 27 drill, saying plant foes
will object to any ruling on the test and further delay commercial
operation with an ``endless loop'' of litigation.
   Similar drills in the past few years have been followed by a
lengthy process of appeals and challenges.
   But the NRC staff said in documents released today that there is
no basis for plant operator New Hampshire Yankee's fear. The staff
also said Seabrook employees have not recently demonstrated their
ability to handle emergencies.
