<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Strike     08-30 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Strike,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal, Communications Workers in Pay Walkout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telephone and mail service was disrupted
Wednesday, the second day of a strike by 1,500 postal and
communications workers.
   Riot police stood outside post offices in the capital after
Witness Mangwende, the minister for Information, Posts and
Telecommunications, declared the stoppage illegal and ordered the
strikers back to work.
   The strike began Tuesday, with workers asking that their starting
pay be doubled. Months of negotiations have failed to resolve the
dispute.
   Under emergency powers invoked by the government earlier this
month, strikes by workers in essential services such as
communications are outlawed, with violators risking dismissal, as
well as a prison sentence of two years and a fine of about $450.
   No action was taken against the strikers by late Wednesday
despite Mangwende's warning.
   The protesters include most Harare telephone operators and
communications technicians. Hundreds of telex machines were
paralyzed and operator-service telephone calls were suspended.
Incoming direct-dial telephone calls were still being received.
</TEXT>
