<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Arctic     08-30 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Arctic,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Soviet Policies Pave Way For Arctic Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finland is convening an environmental
conference on the arctic, a meeting made possible by changing Soviet
attitudes toward ecology, a Foreign Ministry official said Wednesday.
   ``The Soviets used to consider pollution a capitalistic vice, but
no longer, and they have shown a willingness to reduce their own
trans-boundary pollution in the Kola Peninsula,'' said the official,
Esko Rajaskoski. ``Three or four years ago such a conference would
have been impossible.''
   The Sept. 20-26 conference will be attended by all eight nations
with territory above the Arctic Circle: the United States, Canada,
the Soviet Union, Sweden, Norway, Iceland, Finland and Denmark,
which is responsible for Greenland.
   ``The environmental damage in the arctic is much more extensive
than we expected and there has not been near enough research in this
area,'' said Olli Paasivirta of Finland's Environment Ministry.
   Oil and gas exploration, refining and transportation, as well as
chemical and heavy metal discharges, are causing problems for some
animal and plant life in the region, Paasivirta said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
