<FIRST>r i PM-Austria-Accident 1stLd-Writethru   08-30 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Austria-Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0499,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING TO ADD EDS NOTE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trains Collide; 1 Dead, 27 Hurt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE casualties. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two passenger trains collided head-on in
western Austria today, killing at least one person and injuring 27
people, a railway spokesman said.
   Three cars derailed when the trains crashed while traveling at
relatively low speeds between Bregenz, capital of Voralberg
province, and the small town of Wolfurt, the spokesman said.
   Authorities found one body in the wreckage. The Austria Press
Agency identified the victim as Alfred Rainer Heller, a 48-year-old
engineer from Bodolz, West Germany.
   Sixteen people, including the drivers of each train, were
hospitalized and 11 other people treated for slight injuries, a
railroad spokesman on condition of anonymity.
   The spokesman said 72 passengers were on the ``Montfort,'' the
express train between Bregenz and Vienna; and 75 were on the
``Bavaria,'' the express train between Munich and Zurich.
   The railway spokesman said it seemed that human error was
probably to blame since the ``Montfort'' had been erroneously
switched to the same track as the other train.
   The crash occurred in Voralberg near the site of a train accident
that killed five people and injured 46 exactly one year ago, on Aug.
29, 1988.
</TEXT>
