<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--SAfrica-US     08-30 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--SAfrica-US,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Ambassador to South Africa Arrives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador William Swing
arrived Wednesday to take up his new post and said he was ``looking
forward to the opportunity and challenge'' of the job.
   Swing is expected to present his credentials to Acting President
F.W. de Klerk after the Sept. 6 elections, but before the new
Parliament convenes.
   Swing, 54, replaces Edward Perkins, who left South Africa in May
to become director-general of the U.S. Foreign Service.
   Swing served his first foreign diplomatic post in South Africa as
vice-consul in Port Elizabeth from 1963-66. After posts in
Washington and West Germany, Swing returned to Africa from 1974-76
as deputy chief of mission in the Central African Republic. He was
ambassador to the Congo and Liberia from 1981-87. Since then he has
been deputy assistant secretary of state for personnel.
   Swing is fluent in French and German, and he has been studying
Zulu and Afrikaans.
