<FIRST>u a PM-TrainDerailment     08-30 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Derailment,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Train Collides With Rig, Two Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 94-car freight train collided with a
tractor-trailer rig today, killing two people, derailing at least 19
cars and snarling traffic for miles, police said.
   It was not immediately clear how many of the Union Pacific
freight train cars left the tracks; reports ranged from 19 to 30
cars. Many of the train's cars were empty and it was not known what
the others held. Officials said they did not contain hazardous
materials.
   Two bodies were pulled from the wreckage, both believed to have
been in the truck, which was dragged about 50 yards on impact, said
state Police Chief Charles Gruber. Their identities were not
released.
   Three people aboard the train were reported injured, although
none seriously.
   The train and truck, leased to Southeastern Frozen Foods of
Louisiana, collided about 6:20 a.m. on a major city thoroughfare,
said state police Lt. Rudy Crain.
   The accident, near the Louisiana State University-Shreveport
campus, tied up traffic in the area for miles, officials said.
Witnesses said freight cars were piled atop one other, scattered
down a hillside and stuck on the ground.
   The Shreveport Journal quoted eyewitnesses as saying the accident
occurred when the truck drove past warning lights in front of the
train.
</TEXT>
