<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1343EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ArtProtest     08-30 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Art Protest,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Artists Boycott Corcoran Gallery Over Exhibit Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An artist boycott has forced the cancellation
of two scheduled exhibitions at the Corcoran Gallery, which in June
amid a swirling political controversy abruptly canceled a show that
included sexually explicit photos.
   Gallery officials said Wednesday that contemporary artist Annette
Lemieux has withdrawn her one-woman show scheduled for Oct. 28 to
Dec. 31 and that an exhibit by six sculptors scheduled for next Feb.
3 to April 8 also has been ``indefinitely postponed.''
   ``We're hoping to reschedule both at some point,'' said Deborah
Shriver, a spokeswoman for the private gallery, which has been
trying in recent years to establish itself as a showcase for
contemporary art.
   Ms. Lemieux, whose work was subsidized by the federal government
through the National Endowment of the Arts, described the withdrawal
of her show as a ``indefinite postponement ... until they (the
Corcoran) demonstrate a definite change in policy.''
   Both she and two of the six sculptors said in letters to the
gallery their decisions were based on the Corcoran's cancellation in
June of an exhibit of 150 photographs by the late Robert
Mapplethorpe, who died last March from AIDS.
   ``We believe the Corcoran, by its regrettable decision, not only
compromised its own curatorial standards, but also demonstrated it
complicity with the punishment subsequently attempted against other
art instititions,'' wrote sculptors Buss Spector and Donald Lipski.
   The Mapplethrope exhibit _ which included photographs of
children's genitalia, homoerotic and sadomasochistic images _ became
embroiled in a vehement controversy over the federal funding of
sexually explicit art through the National Endowment of the Arts.
   The exhibit, which toured several other museums, was funded
partially through a $15,000 grant by the endowment.
   Since then, congressional critics led by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., and Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, have pushed bills through the
House and Senate cutting the endowment's budget and restricting the
type of art it can fund.
   ``This is what we feared from day one,'' Christina Orr-Cahall,
the Corcoran's director told The Washington Post. ``We're in the
middle of the storm.''
   Ms. Shriver said 10 American painters, including Ms. Lemieux,
featured in a joint U.S.-Soviet exhibition to be featured next
spring also have threatened to deny the gallery the right to display
their work.
   ``As far as we know, that show is still on,'' she said of the
spring 1990 exhibit _ ``10 plus 10: Contemporary Soviet and American
Painters,'' a touring show arranged by the Modern Art Museum of Fort
Worth. ``But we realize that the artists are upset.''
</TEXT>
