<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia 3rdLd-Writethru a0552 08-30 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0552,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodia Peace Conference Fails</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with conference issuing final statement,
deciding to suspend its work. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates at an international conference on Cambodia
failed to produce a peace accord today and decided to suspend their
work until the warring factions are ready to compromise.
   Last-minute haggling delayed by seven hours the issuing of a
final statement that fell far short of the comprehensive settlement
delegates from 19 nations hoped to achieve when the meeting opened
in late July.
   The statement _ issued as the delegates began a last plenary
session that was expected to be brief _ said the meeting had
``achieved progress in elaborating a wide variety of elements
necessary for the reaching of a comprehensive settlement to the
tragic conflict in Cambodia.''
   But, it added, ``It is not yet possible to achieve a
comprehensive settlement. It was therefore decided to suspend the
conference.''
   France and Indonesia, whose representatives chaired the meeting,
offered to assist in mediating within the next six months between
the Vietnam-installed government of Prime Minister Hun Sen and the
three resistance factions led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the
hereditary ruler of the Southeast Asian nation.
   The delegates left open the possiblity of using the committees
set up under the auspices of the international conference as a forum
for future talks between the belligerents.
   France and Indonesia ``will begin consultations within six months
with the participants in the conference with a view to reconvening
the conference,'' the statement said.
   France called the conference when it appeared that an
international political climate of greater cooperation favored a
possible settlement.
   But over three weeks of negotiations in small working groups, the
positions among the Cambodian factions hardened.
   The failure at the negotiating table in Paris increased the
liklihood of full-scale civil war after the scheduled withdrawal of
26,000 Vietnamese troops before Sept. 27, some delegates said.
   ``It will be like Afghanistan; there will be more fighting,''
said the spokesman for the Singapore delegation, Tommy Koh. ``The
two sides are preparing for war, they're already fighting.''
   ``The parties won't come back until they've tested each other on
the battlefield and have reached an impasse,'' Koh said.
   Negotiations broke down over five points, including the
composition of a transitional government after the troop pullout, a
mechanism for monitoring the withdrawal and the use of the word
``genocide'' in describing the Khmer Rouge rule between 1975 and the
Vietnamese invasion three years later, French Foreign Minister
Roland Dumas reported. The Khmer Rouge is believed to have killed 1
million Cambodians during its rule.
   Intransigence marked the meeting up until the end, delaying the
final plenary session that was scheduled to begin in the morning but
was delayed until late afternoon.
   The points of disagreement included an item in a draft of the
final statement calling for the Cambodian parties to intensify their
``efforts to achieve national reconciliation.''
   Both China, who supports the Khmer Rouge resistance, and Sihanouk
objected to the reference national reconciliation, and the wording
was deleted.
   Their position remains that the Phnom Penh government led by Hun
Sen is strictly a Vietnamese puppet.
   In a statement released on the last day of the conference,
Sihanouk said that the resistance would reject any international
monitoring of the troop withdrawal ``before the dismantling of the
illegal regime of Phnom Penh and its replacement by a Cambodian
provisional quadrapartite government'' composed of the three
resistance members and Hun Sen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0097 </DOCNO>
