<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0553 08-30 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0553,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Vows to Try to Hold Line on Taxes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; cuts last 9 grafs to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush promised today to keep
trying ``to hold the line on taxes'' and to fight for a lower tax on
capital gains.
   Speaking to an appreciative audience of fellow residents and
merchants of this summer resort, the vacationing president appealed
for their support as he heads back to Washington next week to
grapple with Congress over taxes and the deficit.
   Bush later in the day was welcoming Canadian Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney and family to his oceanfront home, where he has spent the
past two weeks.
   Bush, standing on a blue-draped temporary platform erected on a
hotel shuffleboard court, with the rocky coastline and blue waters
of the Atlantic at his back, noted that the Kennebunk-Kennebunkport
Chamber of Commerce was composed of ``a lot of entrepreneurs.''
   ``I'd be remiss at a meeting like this if I didn't ask you to
give me strong support as I go back to Washington to fight for a
capital gains tax differential,'' he said.
   Bush wants to reduce the levy on capital gains _ profits made
from the sale of property or securities _ from 28 percent to 15
percent but has met resistence from Democrats who control Congress.
   Calling small businesses ``the backbone of this country in any
ways,'' Bush said he wants to reduce the levy to stimulate the
economy and reward ``those who have the courage to go off on their
own and start new businesses.''
   ``I do believe we're going to get a good agreement on the budget
deficit reduction package. I think it will be accomplished without
raising the taxes on the American working man,'' the president said.
   ``I am going to continue to try to hold the line on taxes,'' he
told the crowd of several hundred.
   Bush made no apologies for his 20-day vacation, which ends on
Labor Day.
   ``We are doing some work, but I have confessed at the very outset
that this is a pure, total vacation, and I'm not going to look busy
in order to convince people in America that it's something other
than a vacation,'' he said to applause. ``It's the way it is.''
   Bush also said he planned to call the editor of the Portland
Press Herald and ask him to stop running a graphic chronicling his
futility at fishing.
   He said this morning he was at the helm when a companion caught a
bluefish.
   ``I think they should knock off that advertisement on the front
of the Portland paper that shows a bluefish with a big `X' through
it telling me that yet a 13th day I haven't caught one,'' he said.
``I'm going to appeal to them on that one.''
   The president said this was a place where he and Barbara
``refurbish our souls and get our batteries all charged up and enjoy
life really to the fullest.''
   Bush has spent every summer of his life here except 1944, when he
was flying Navy bombers in the Pacific during World War II.
   A bright sun broke through the morning haze and clouds in time
for the Chamber of Commerce event.
   ``I can't wait to show off this heaven to the prime minister of
Canada, his wife and his four kids,'' he told the local boosters.
   Bush's national security adviser said Tuesday that U.S.-Canadian
relations are in good shape thanks to progress on acid rain and
trade as the two leaders hold their friendly, private visit.
   Mulroney, his wife Mila and their four children were to arrive in
late afternoon at Bush's Walker's Point compound for an overnight
visit.
   Bush's national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, said Tuesday
the private visit would give the two leaders ``a chance to relax
(and) a chance to exchange views'' on world events, including the
dramatic changes in Poland as well as the crises in Lebanon and
Colombia.
   Scowcroft said the two old friends share ``a close similarity of
views ... on world affairs and a kind of unique personal closeness
and frankness in exchanging views.''
   Scowcroft said U.S.-Canadian ties are ``in basically pretty good
shape,'' with efforts under way to implement the sweeping Free Trade
Agreement signed last year by former President Reagan and Mulroney.
   He said Bush's proposed revision of the Clean Air Act, which
would seek to sharply curb emissions from utility plants, factories
and other sources of pollutants that cause acid rain, ``has set us
on the road to dealing with one of the other major problems between
us, that is the issue of cross-border pollution'' such as acid rain.
</TEXT>
