<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   08-30 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0829</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the country:
   Aug. 25
   Owatonna (Minn.) People's Press on education:
   U.S. Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos did not actually point an
accusing finger at educators and schools when he complained of
rising education costs and falling returns.
   He was careful to say parents, teachers and all Americans must
become involved if education is to succeed.
   But his underlying tone was an accusatory one _ once again, he
implied, education is falling down on the job.
   If Cavazos genuinely believes such a direct relationship can be
discerned between money spent on education and children's
achievement, he does not understand how people learn.
   It is not the fault of the education system that families break
apart and create insecure homes for kids, keeping their minds off
learning. It is not the fault of the educational system that
children are abused, throwing up barriers to learning. It is not the
fault of the educational system that teen-agers get pregnant and, to
compound the problem, try to raise their babies themselves, in
poverty.
   A failure in education is a failure in society as a whole. We
cannot mend our school system until we mend our social failings. It
is a cyclical relationship; to a large degree, education is the
answer to our social failings.
   The circuit breaker we need is in the cycle of poverty and crime,
not in the money we spend on education.
   Then again, it is possible that Cavazos realizes these
complexities. If so, he is playing politics with children's futures
and that is unforgivable.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 23
   The News Tribune, Woodbridge, N.J., on the cost of AZT:
   The encouraging news that the drug AZT will stall the deadly
effect of the AIDS virus is dampened by the news that the bill for
this drug might approach $5 billion annually.
   Should limited public funds be used to help these patients with
their terminal virus, or should they be used to help poor women get
proper prenatal care, or allow poor schoolchildren hot lunches?
   Providing AZT to all who need it, regardless of their ability to
pay, is the compassionate thing to do. But is it fiscally
responsible to do so in a nation with a mounting debt and an
exploding health bill?
   What this dilemma does is offer an additional reminder that
massive education, and changes in habits are needed to prevent the
spread of this preventable disease. It also highlights the need for
research to find a cure for AIDS as well as the need for discovery
of affordable means of treatment.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 27
   Picayune (Miss.) Item on Voyager 2:
   Twelve long years and billions of miles after launching, the
plucky Voyager spacecraft rendezvoused with the distant planet
Neptune, sending back a wealth of spectacular pictures and other
information. It was a dramatic climax to a remarkable mission.
   This is technology at its best. Technology often gets a bum rap
these days. People ask why we should spend so much on such
adventures when there are so many problems here on Earth.
   Voyager tells us why. We want to know what's there, over the next
hill. Mankind always has. Maybe what we find will be good or
beneficial, maybe it won't. But we don't know till we look, till we
use our human resources to invent, to dream, to venture beyond our
safe little backyards.
   The desolation of the other planets that Voyager has so
graphically shown us has been a lesson in itself. Our Earth is a
special place, a unique oasis of beauty and knowledge in the
vastness of space.
   We must preserve it, to be sure, but we must also make the most
of what we have _ always thankful for our blessings, always willing
to use them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 25
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on Colombia's drug crackdown:
   It is with a sense of deep satisfaction Americans watch the
courageous move by the imperilled Colombian government as it rounded
up close to 10,000 drug suspects in an all-out search for the five
men who control the Medellin cartel and their associates. ...
   This effort to stop the production and flow of cocaine and crack
in Colombia comes too late for 550 provincial judges, the country's
leading presidential candidate, and countless drug enforcement
officers, senators, farmers, witnesses, bystanders, all killed by
the cartel for getting in the way of the flow of coke from Colombia
to the streets of the United States.
   It comes too late for the thousands killed in this country each
month in crack-related violence.
   But Colombia is finally doing something. It is doing more than
its best consumer, our own country. Without the relentless demand
here, Colombian cocaine would disappear.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
