<DOCNO> AP890830-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   08-30 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: would disappear.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 23
   The Register-Guard, Eugene, Ore., on Colombia's drug crackdown:
   Political leaders in the United States often speak of the need
for a war against drugs, but in Colombia they're fighting the real
thing.
   Colombia is under violent siege by powerful narcotics
traffickers, and the killings there are directly traceable to the
failure to control the drug problem here. ...
   The United States is being less effective than it needs to be in
its efforts to help Colombian society withstand the cartel's corrupt
and violent influence. ...
   U.S. economic aid to Colombia has been cut, and military aid
ended last year. Meanwhile, ghetto addicts and yuppie thrill-seekers
finance the private armies of the cartel. ...
   Those who stand up to the drug lords in Colombia are valuable
allies. ... And when such allies are killed, it underscores the
United States' responsibility to do more to curtail the demand for
drugs, which is the assasins' ultimate source of strength.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 28
   Argus Leader, Sioux Falls, S.D., on Colombia's drug crackdown:
   President Bush has responded belatedly but appropriately to the
bloody battle unfolding in Colombia. But even more U.S. help may be
required, at taxpayer expense.
   Bush said Friday that the United States would send $65 million
worth of helicopters, weapons and other equipment to help Colombia
in its battle against drug barons.
   The situation in Colombia will test the sincerity of Bush and
members of Congress who have been loudly advocating an all-out fight
against illegal drugs.
   The stability of a foreign nation is at stake. Drug lords must
not be allowed to prevail.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 26
   South Bend (Ind.) Tribune on Voyager 2:
   If you yawned it had to be the hour, not the event. Not since our
distant ancestors emerged from the caves has humankind been treated
to such sights.
   The marvelous journey of Voyager 2 to the edge of the solar
system humbled and excited at the same time, as great human
achievements have always done.
   The pictures of Neptune and its mysterious moons may have lacked
the clarity of a telecast game show, but they were vivid testimony
of what man can do in his better moments. What scientists have
dreamed about for decades was delivered to you on your own TV
screen. ...
   Putting it all in perspective will take time. Drama aside, the
information supplied by Voyager 2 is of enormous value in our
understanding of the universe. ...
   The thousands of scientists and technicians involved in the
Voyager expedition deserve a warm salute from those of us who sit
wondering in front of the tube.
   As it sinks in, we can be permitted to wonder about this strange
creature called man. We can reach out to the stars; we can eliminate
a scourge such as polio, but tolerate war and hunger.
   If we can do some great things, why not others?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 24
   The Arizona Republic, Phoenix, on the Federal Reserve's
independence:
   It is billed as an effort to put an end to secrecy in the Federal
Reserve System, but that is window dressing.
   The fact is that a bill introduced by Rep. Lee Hamilton of
Indiana would factor raw politics into the financial equations of
the Fed, creating nothing short of economic pandemonium. ...
   Hamilton and other critics complain that, like the U.S. Supreme
Court, the Fed is autonomous. Guided by a handful of appointed
experts, it moves interest rates up and down as it pleases. It is
accountable to no one. Its deliberations are conducted in secret.
Its decisions may not be appealed.
   All that is true, and let us be grateful. The alternative _ at
least the alternative favored by ... Hamilton _ is to authorize the
congressionally run General Accounting Office to audit the Fed's
monetary transactions, which are now protected from such scrutiny,
and recommend changes.
   It is not difficult to see how this would give Congress, whose
impulses are unfailingly political, leverage over the Fed's
decisions. ...
   Hamilton also wants to make the Treasury Secretary a voting
member of the Fed, thereby enhancing White House influence, too.
   In justification, he argues that the Fed's monetary policy is not
democratic enough. Of course it isn't democratic. It is not supposed
to be democratic. The genius of the Federal Reserve is precisely
that it insulates monetary decisions from politics. ...
   The purpose of the Hamilton bill is as plain as it is alarming.
... Hamilton hopes to undermine the independence of the Federal
Reserve, the economy's chief protection against a free-wheeling,
free-spending, politically driven Congress. The mechanism may not be
perfect, but it works.
   Only at our enormous peril will Congress be permitted to
``adjust'' it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
