<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     08-30 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 200, Including Tutu's Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested more than 200
women, including the wife of Archbishop Desmond Tutu, during a
protest march in central Cape Town as part of a nationwide defiance
campaign.
   Many of the women, blacks and whites, sat on the street and
chanted freedom songs before police led or carried them into vans.
   In Pretoria, eight blacks and two whites were arrested for trying
to desegregate the capital's whites-only buses, another phase of the
defiance campaign. The two whites were women who bought bus tickets
for blacks.
   Twice this week, shots have been fired into the homes of
organizers of the Pretoria campaign.
   Police stopped the throng of placard-carrying women in Cape Town
after they emerged from a church hall to begin a march to the
British Embassy. They intended to ask Britain to protest the South
African government's handling of student unrest in the Cape Town
area and to intercede on behalf of three black activists facing
execution for a 1986 killing.
   In addition to Leah Tutu, those arrested included Mary Burton, a
white who heads the Black Sash civil rights group, and Dorothy
Boesak, wife of the Rev. Allan Boesak, a prominent mixed-race
activist who is president of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
   Many of the marchers sat in a street adjoining a small plaza
until they were led into police vans and driven away. Scores of
onlookers cheered them.
   Police said the women would be charged with participating in an
illegal gathering.
   A white activist involved in the defiance campaign, Willie
Hofmeyer, was admitted to a Cape Town hospital Wednesday with
suspected internal bleeding, his father said. Hofmeyer has been on a
hunger strike since he was detained by police last week during a
protest at a branch of First National Bank, sponsor of an ongoing
tour by an international rugby team which activists say violates the
sports boycott of South Africa.
   The South African Council of Churches, which supports the
defiance campaign, announced plans for an outdoor rally Saturday in
Soweto, the vast black township outside Johannesburg. The church
council's general secretary, the Rev. Frank Chikane, said the rally
was intended as a forum for blacks to express their opposition to
the white-controlled government in a peaceful manner.
   Outdoor rallies are illegal unless authorized by the government,
and Chikane said he hoped Saturday's event would be approved. Tutu
and Boesak are among the scheduled speakers.
   Before dawn Wednesday, a bomb exploded at the home of a member of
the Indian chamber of Parliament, causing damage but no injuries.
Police said the explosion wrecked a door and several windows at the
home of Ahomed Lambat in Alberton, southeast of Johannesburg. There
was no claim of responsibility.
   Anti-apartheid militants are urging a boycott of the Sept. 6
elections for the mixed-race and Indian chambers of Parliament,
which is dominated by a whites-only chamber and excludes the black
majority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1401EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   08-30 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0925</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ``adjust'' it.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 24
   The Clarksburg (W.Va.) Exponent on the King-Leland legacies:
   The two black Americans achieved their measure of fame by living
radically different lives. One was a clergyman, the other a
politician. Yet both served humanity with an identically relentless
love.
   Today, a national holiday enshrines the transfiguring legacy of
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. But it is too soon to predict
whether America will carry out the legacy of Rep. Mickey Leland in
the aftermath of his tragic death in Ethiopia.
   We are a nation that thrives on the empty grandeur of symbols. It
is far more convenient to erect a graven image to the prophet than
to adopt his philosophy. After King died, we named streets,
buildings and schools after him. Twenty-one years later, those
schools are more likely to be completely segregated.
   Like King, Leland believed one should live his religious
convictions. Like King, he suffered an untimely death while
searching for peace.
   Unlike many of his colleagues, Leland did not believe in
traveling abroad on junkets camouflaged as ``legislative oversight
missions,'' ... to luxuriate in the world's best hotels and savor
the food at its most elegant restaurants. ...
   Instead of flying to Paris ... Leland flew into Ethiopia's foggy
mountainous terrain to visit dirt-poor refugee camps.
   But we do what Mickey Leland deplored: extolling him with words
instead of exploring legislative ways to carry out his ideals.
   The only monuments Leland would care about would be for this
nation to make a commitment to feeding the hungry, preventing the
erosion of civil rights at home and seeking the sovereign dignity
for all peoples abroad.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 29
   Philadelphia Inquirer on the Legal Services Corp.:
   President Reagan's war against legal services to the poor should
have ended when he left office, but it didn't. Unfortunately, the
people he chose are still running the Legal Services Corp., which
passes federal funds to agencies that represent poor people in
litigation.
   As (President) Bush has dallied in nominating people to fill the
11 seats on the LSC's board of directors, the lame ducks now in
charge have continued to discredit themselves.
   Several months ago, the LSC hired an outside lawyer to produce a
10-page legal memorandum that argued, weakly, that the Legal
Services Corp. itself is unconstitutional. This continued the
tradition of Reagan-era embarrassments, which included lucrative
consulting contracts for some LSC leaders.
   If ... Bush longs to rekindle the extremism of the Reagan era, he
could simply choose some of the 11 potential directors put forward
by Phyllis Schlafly, Howard Phillips and other fringe-dwellers.
   But if he backs the premise of the Legal Services Corp. _ that
every American has the right to effective legal representation ... _
he will fill those seats with outstanding Americans whose own work
has shown their commitment to legal services to the poor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 29
   The Jackson (Mich.) Citizen Patriot on Indian remains:
   American Indians have a bone to pick with one of the white man's
cultural institutions _ the museum.
   Meeting in Albuquerque (N.M.) recently, the National Congress of
American Indians estimated that the bones of 2.5 million of their
ancestors are held in U.S. museums. Those remains should be
returned, Indians say.
   Museum officials put the figures at much less. They admit to
having the remains of between 100,000 and 250,000 Indians. Indeed,
the Smithsonian Institution in Washington, D.C., has 18,600 Indian
remains stacked in boxes in a hallway closed to the public.
   We don't want to refight old wars. But here's a thought to
ponder: Numbers of remains aside, if those were the bones of
American slaves, would the museums get away with this? Of course not.
   What, then, makes it OK to unearth the remains of Indian
ancestors and ``bury'' them in display cases and boxes as an
anthropological curiosity? Because ``we'' beat the red man? Because
to the victor go the spoils?
   Sometimes we're not sure the right side won.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 26
   Daily Register, Portage, Wis., on tranquilizing bears:
   The New Mexico Department of Game and Fish encountered harsh
criticism from animal rights advocates and the public in general ...
after an incident in which a bear, tranquilized after climbing a
utility pole, came in contact with live wires and fell to the ground.
   And well it should.
   The agency, whose primary purpose is to maintain guidelines to
ensure the survival of fish and game _ including bear _ did not seem
to consider this when tranquilizing the bear, which had climbed the
pole after wandering into a town in search of its cub.
   After the bear climbed up the pole, the agency's first step
should have been to cut electrical power.
   Next, it should have prepared for the bear's fall _ in the form
of a safety net _ if the bear fell after being shot with the
tranquilizer gun.
   Instead, the state agency did neither. The result was a 25-foot
fall and contact (with) transformer coils _ in the form of 7,200
volts.
   The bear survived _ thankfully.
   A game and fish department official, after getting a host of
calls criticizing the methods, said the agency was ``only concerned
about the safety of residents.'' So much for its mission of ensuring
the survival of fish and game.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
