<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1405EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-LeonaProfile     08-30 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leona Profile,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Queen Tarnished: Testimony Destroys Carefully Cultivated Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Helmsley Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She entered federal court nine weeks ago as Leona
Helmsley, Hotel Queen, ruler of a multibillion-dollar empire. But
the image of a different woman emerged at the trial _ tyrannical,
nasty, sharp-tongued, cheap.
   It's been quite a change for Mrs. Helmsley, the one-time
Chesterfield cigarette girl who was used to getting her way _ and,
witnesses in her tax evasion trial testified, turning ugly when she
didn't.
   She was convicted Wednesday of evading $1.2 million in income
taxes by charging personal expenses to her business.
   No one figured it would lead to fingerprints when Mrs. Helmsley _
born Leona Mindy Rosenthal, daughter of a Brooklyn hatmaker _
married billionaire Harry Helmsley in 1972 and thrust herself into
the spotlight.
   Once a featured guest on ``60 Minutes,'' Mrs. Helmsley spurned
interviews during her trial. Portrayed as a regal perfectionist in
her ads, she was dumped by her advertising agency this month amid
charges of meddling.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, is Harry's second wife; she, too, was married
before, to a lawyer she divorced in 1959. The couple had a son, who
died in 1982; mention of his death brought her near tears at her
trial, the only emotion she's shown in the packed courtroom.
   Her 80-year-old husband, indicted with her, avoided trial on
grounds of mental incompetence.
   Leona was a successful model who had moved into real estate when
she met Helmsley in 1971. She quickly became a $500,000-a-year
senior vice president. Within a year, she became Mrs. Helmsley.
   No one questions the couple's devotion. Leona called Harry
``gorgeous one'' and ``pussycat'' in a People magazine interview;
Harry bathed the Empire State Building _ one of his real estate
holdings _ in red, white and blue light for her birthday in 1976.
   ``It was less than a necklace,'' Helmsley said of the $100,000
treat.
   The couple enjoyed an opulent lifestyle: an $11 million
Connecticut mansion (the focus of the tax charges), a Manhattan
duplex, a Palm Beach penthouse. They travel in their private plane;
their $5 billion real estate empire includes 27 hotels.
   Mrs. Helmsley took control of the Helmsley hotels in 1980. Her
face adorned ads for the hotels; her persona _ the demanding boss
bent on perfection _ became her company's motto.
   ``Service and appointment fit for royalty _ you _ our guest,''
read one Helmsley Palace ad. ``The only palace in the world where
the queen stands guard,'' promised another.
   Mrs. Helmsley's legal woes prior to her indictment last year were
limited to reports about a scam to avoid state sales tax. She was
never charged, although it was reported she received immunity for
her cooperation.
   The real Leona-bashing began with her trial.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch and developer Donald Trump, who rarely agree
on anything, concurred on Leona: the mayor dubbed her ``the wicked
witch,'' while Trump called her ``a sick woman.''
   In opening arguments, her own lawyer labeled her ``a tough
bitch;'' in closing, a prosecutor attacked her ``selfishness, greed
and sheer arrogance.'' Former employees detailed an abrasive boss
who hired and fired on a whim.
   Defense attorney Gerald Feffer argued it was proper for the
Helmsleys to bill their business for expenses at Dunellen Hall
because they used the estate for business. The employees who
testified, he argued, were motivated by spite.
   It was one of those employees, housekeeper Elizabeth Baum, who
provided the most memorable line on Leona:
   ``We don't pay taxes,'' she quoted Mrs. Helmsley as telling her.
``Only the little people pay taxes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
