<FIRST>u a PM-Kaifu 1stLd-Writethru a0478 08-30 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kaifu, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0478,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede TOKYO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Arrives for Summit Talks in U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Kaifu landing in San Francisco;
Picks up 3rd graf, `Kaifu, 58...'; Changes byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu
arrived today on a trip designed to foster closer ties and establish
the diplomatic credentials of his new adminstration.
   During his first overseas trip since taking office Aug. 9, Kaifu
hopes to use baseball diplomacy and meetings with U.S. officials and
academics to ease trade tensions between America and Japan, Foreign
Ministry officials said.
   Kaifu was greeted here this morning by Nobuo Matsunaga, Japanese
ambassador to the United States; Shunji Yanai, Japanese consul
general in San Francisco; and several local officials.
   Kaifu, 58, is not expected to propose any major trade or
diplomatic initiatives in his talks Friday with President Bush.
   But he hopes to ``establish a close and credible working
relationship with the president and other American leaders,'' said
Yukio Okamoto, director of the Foreign Ministry's First North
America Division.
   Kaifu also will use the 12-day tour, which will take him to
Mexico on Sept. 4-6 and to Canada Sept. 7, to enhance his stature at
home, analysts say.
   Kaifu, who has little diplomatic experience but is considered an
excellent speaker, will address scholars and journalists in San
Francisco, Washington and Boston, where he plans to watch a Red Sox
baseball game from the owner's box.
   ``Mr. Kaifu wants to initiate a much more increased level of
intellectual dialogue with the United States, and especially with
its people,'' Okamoto said.
   In their meeting, Kaifu and Bush are expected to talk about
so-called structural problems that impede an improvement in the U.S.
trade deficit with Japan, which totaled $55 billion in 1988,
according to U.S. figures.
   Kaifu is expected to explain Japan's efforts to reduce the trade
imbalance, and express its willingness to focus on issues like its
complex distribution system and business practices that Americans
say block foreign access to the Japanese market.
   But the prime minister also will emphasize the need for the
United States to address problems such as its large budget deficit
and low investment rate, Foreign Ministry officials say.
   U.S.-Japanese talks on such non-tariff trade barriers are
scheduled to begin Sept. 4, but Kaifu's Liberal Democratic Party is
under strong pressure at home not to make additional concessions on
trade.
   Recent election losses suffered by the party were attributed in
part to the unhappiness of farmers over Japanese concessions on
agricultural trade.
   ``It will take a long time to solve the trade imbalance and in
the meantime we have to live with it,'' a ministry official said.
``To defuse the tension caused by the imbalance, we need a more
objective understanding of each other.''
   Kaifu also will reassure Bush and other U.S. officials of Japan's
political and diplomatic stability, ministry officials said.
   Some Japanese foreign policy initiatives have been stalled in
recent months as the Liberal Democrats grappled with a series of
money and sex scandals and an election setback that led to the
resignation of Kaifu's two predecessors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1408EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-RacialAttack 2ndLd-Writethru a0562 08-30 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Attack, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0562,0881</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Indicted on Murder Charges in Black Teen's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with funeral under way, governor
and mayor booed, quotes. Pickup 5th graf, `This is nothing...' DELETES
grafs 8-9 pvs, bgng `Gov. Mario...' now outdated.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two white teen-agers were indicted today on
murder charges in the killing of a black youth last week that has
set off a racial furor in the city.
   The indictments were returned in Brooklyn Criminal Court just one
hour before the funeral of Yusef Hawkins, 16. A crowd of about 300
people heckled Gov. Mario Cuomo and New York City Mayor Edward I.
Koch as they arrived for the service. Koch had been jeered when he
attended a wake for Hawkins Tuesday.
   Keith Mondello, 18, and Pasquale Raucci, 19, of Brooklyn, were
charged with murder, riot, assault, criminal possession of a deadly
weapon, unlawful imprisonment and civil rights violations.
   Mondello was the alleged leader of a gang of up to 30 whites,
armed with baseball bats and golf clubs, that allegedly attacked
Hawkins and three friends Aug. 23 in the predominantly white
Bensonhurst neighborhood.
   ``We're surrounded by Martin and Malcolm. We're surrounded by
Eleanor Bumpurs. We're surrounded by Michael Griffith,'' said the
Rev. Timothy Mitchell, a Brooklyn civil rights activist, to start
the service at Glover Memorial Baptist Church in Brooklyn. ``They
all speak to us and say, `No more.'''
   Martin and Malcolm are Martin Luther King and Malcolm X. Michael
Griffith is the black man who was killed when a gang of whites
chased him onto a highway in Howard Beach; Eleanor Bumpurs was a
black woman killed when police tried to evict her from her apartment.
   Among those at the crowded memorial service were the Rev. Louis
Farrakhan and Cedric Sandiford, who had also been attacked in the
1986 Howard Beach incident. He accompanied Michael Griffith's
mother, Jean.
   ``Go home!'' the crowd chanted at Cuomo, while the mayor and
Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward were booed. Mayoral candidates
Harrison J. Goldin and David Dinkins were also at the funeral.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson was among 1,600 people who attended a wake
Tuesday for Hawkins.
   ``This is nothing more than a political indictment,'' charged
Mondello's lawyer, Stephen Murphy, after his client was charged.
``They know he wasn't the shooter. How can they obtain a murder
indictment? It's absurd.''
   Police are looking for Joseph Fama, 18, of Brooklyn, who has been
identified as the gunman in the killing.
   Judge Seymour Gerschwer allowed Mondello to remain free on
$100,000 bail and Raucci on $75,000 bail. The grand jury that
indicted the two was still considering charges against the other
suspects in the case.
   The night of the attack, Hawkins and three black friends went to
the Brooklyn neighborhood of Bensonhurst to look at a used car for
sale. A group of 10 to 30 whites, armed with at least one gun, bats
and golf clubs, chased the four and surrounded them.
   Hawkins was shot twice in the chest.
   Six young white men have been charged with assault, riot and
other counts. Five have been released on bail.
   One of the six, Joseph Serrano, 20, was arraigned Tuesday and
held on $75,000 bail. Assistant District Attorney David Neier told
the judge that witnesses had placed Serrano at the scene with a bat
and a pistol.
   There have been reports that Fama may have fled to Italy, where
his parents were born. Police have asked the State Department to
help find him, Sgt. Pete Berry said.
   The FBI has begun a preliminary inquiry into Hawkins' death, said
Ann Driscoll, a spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney. The
U.S. Attorney's office also has offered assistance to the office of
Brooklyn District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman, which is handling the
case.
   Such steps are not unusual in cases that may involve federal
civil rights violations, Driscoll said.
   Police said Hawkins and his friends were innocent victims of a
feud between the white gang and 18-year-old Gina Feliciano. She had
been dating a Hispanic man and invited black friends into the mostly
white neighborhood.
   One of those arrested was a former boyfriend who had been spurned
by Ms. Feliciano, police said.
   Political, religious and community leaders continued to call for
greater efforts to root out racism.
   Cuomo, in a statement, called on New Yorkers to pray ``that we
will make this moment of shame a time for honesty and renewal.''
   Roman Catholic Cardinal John J. O'Connor said, ``We like to
pretend that racial relations aren't broken. Well, they are broken.
They're bleeding.''
   O'Connor, Brooklyn Bishop Francis J. Mugavero and state Human
Rights Commissioner Douglas H. White joined leaders from the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People and the
Coalition of Italo-American Associations in warning against
condemning the entire Bensonhurst community.
   ``These people are good, the majority,'' said Mugavero, who
described the Italian-Jewish neighborhood as ``a community that
really has very deep basic values.''
   But Hazel N. Dukes, president of the state conference of NAACP
branches, said, ``When good people do nothing, evil people take
over.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
