<DOCNO> AP890830-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1416EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Honecker     08-30 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honecker,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Drop Surgery Because East German Leader Too Ill, Sources
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German leader Erich Honecker
underwent gall bladder surgery but doctors had to halt the operation
because of the condition of the organ had deteriorated, West German
security sources said Wednesday.
   East Germany denied the reports about Honecker, 77. A Foreign
Ministry spokesman in East Berlin, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said he was ``progressing toward recovery.''
   Honecker was reported to have undergone a gall bladder operation
two weeks ago. The East German government said on Aug. 24 he was
``continuing on the road to recovery.''
   But the Hessicher Rundfunk radio on Wednesday said the West
German government has received intelligence information indicating
Honecker's condition is more serious than official East German
reports suggest.
   Government security sources confirmed the radio report, but would
provide few details.
   According to the sources, Honecker's surgeons were forced to
abandon the gall bladder operation ``because of the condition of the
tissue.''
   The information was relayed to the West German government by the
country's intelligence service, the sources said. There were no
further details.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also speculated
whether Honecker's illness may be one reason the East German
government has not yet taken decisive steps to deal with an exodus
of refugees out of the Communist country.
   At least 6,000 East Germans have fled to West Germany through
Hungary since Hungary began dismantling its border barriers in May.
Scores more are holed up in West German missions and embassies in
East Berlin and Prague, demanding they be allowed to emigrate.
   The situation has created tensions between the two Germanies, as
well as between Hungary and East Germany.
   Hungary is among East bloc nations experimenting with liberal
reforms while East Germany remains a hard-line Communist state.
   Hans Klein, spokesman for West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl,
said there has been ``zero movement'' by the East German government
on the refugee problem.
   ``But I do not know if this has any connection with Mr.
Honecker's condition,'' Klein said.
   Klein also said Kohl's offer still stands to talk with Honecker
about the refugee problem.
   ``But there is a question about whether Mr. Honecker would be
able to do that,'' Klein said.
   Other high-ranking East German officials also are ailing, say
sources in East Berlin.
   Premier Willi Stoph has a stomach ailment and has not appeared in
public for some time and Guenter Mittag, who is responsible for
economic affairs, has been suffering from acute leg pains, said the
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Stoph is 75 and Mittag is 62.
   Honecker has not been seen in public since his operation.
   Werner Kohlhoff, spokesman for the West Berlin government, said
Mayor Walter Momper had hoped to meet with Honecker at the Leipzig
trade fair on Sunday but that city officials have learned the East
German leader will not be there.
   Sources in East Berlin said Mittag also would not be at the fair.
   East Germany's leadership attaches enormous prestige to the
Leipzig trade fair and Honecker traditionally opens the biannual
international event.
   Honecker has been hospitalized twice this summer.
   Illness forced him to leave a Warsaw Pact summit in Bucharest on
July 8 before its conclusion, and the official East German media
later announced he was in a hospital for problems related to
gallstones.
   He has ruled the country of 16.6 million people since 1971. He
supervised the building of the Berlin Wall 10 years earlier.
   Honecker has strongly shunned the adoption of Kremlin-style
political reforms, a factor in the recent surge of refugees from
East Germany to the West.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
