<FIRST>r a AM-ForgerFoiled     08-30 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forger Foiled,0214</SECOND>
<UNK>Counterfeiter Who Forged Hospital Pass Recaptured at Campsite</UNK>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twice-convicted counterfeiter who forged a
hospital pass and walked away from a court-ordered residence program
was back in custody Wednesday, authorities said.
   William G. ``Pop'' Kerns, 67, who has spent about 30 of the past
50 years in jail, was arrested on a tip Tuesday at an Indiana
campsite.
   After his arrest July 19 on counterfeiting charges, Kerns was
placed in a pre-trial custody program at the Volunteers of America.
Despite Kerns' age and poor health, a federal magistrate rejected
prosecutors' requests to put him in jail.
   Officials were more confident of keeping Kerns behind bars this
time. He was being held in the Marion County Jail for a hearing
later Wednesday.
   ``I would suspect the court would be highly receptive,'' said
Chief Gary Tingle of the U.S. Marshals Service. ``They're not real
pleased when people take advantage of them and their generosity.''
   Kerns, with at least 45 arrests since 1939, had been arrested in
July after Secret Service agents caught him making counterfeit $100
bills on a printing press, officials said.
   He walked away from the custody program Aug. 22 after forging a
counselor's signature on a pass to Wishard Hospital, authorities
said.
