<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Israel     08-30 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Israel,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabin Says Reports of Israeli Ties to Drug Lords Exaggerated</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reports of ties between
Israelis and Colombian drug lords are overblown and only one or two
companies may have violated the law, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
said Wednesday.
   Rabin, on a visit to the West Bank, also said there were few if
any Israeli mercenaries.
   He and other officials sought to stem the scandal about
allegations that former army officers gave paramilitary training to
assassination squads for the Medellin drug cartel in Colombia.
   Israeli media said the issue also had divided government
officials and could affect lucrative arms exports to Colombia.
   Police questioned two more employee of Hod Hahanit, or Spearhead,
a security and arms trading company said to have provided training
for the cartel.
   Yair Klein, a reserve lieutenant colonel who heads the company,
confirmed Wednesday an Israeli official told him to leave Colombia
because he might be arrested _ raising the possibility the
government knew more of his dealings than it has acknowledged.
   Parliament's law committee rejected a proposal that laws
controlling the export of arms and military expertise be
strengthened to allow prosecution of Israelis for offenses committed
abroad.
   Some lawmakers said even discussing the matter could influence
the current police investigation. Legislator Amnon Rubinstein of the
left-leaning Shinui party said the government was moving too slowly.
   ``What bothers me is that, for a very long time, these things
have been known,'' he said. ``In my opinion, there is no room for
Israelis to be military advisers to unsavory types.''
   Rabin told journalists: ``I believe the media, especially in
Israel, are making unjustified statements based on rumors rather
than on solid information.''
   He said the government was investigating and would punish any
former officers who broke Israeli law. ``We are not trying to hide,
to conceal,'' the defense minister said.
   Israel's controls on exports of military equipment and knowledge
are the most stringent in the world and companies must have Defense
Ministry permits for overseas deals, Rabin said.
   ``I believe basically the number of people who have not obeyed
the law ... is very, very limited,'' he said. ``One or two Israeli
companies either worked without permission or went beyond the
permission. Allow me also to stress the point that Israeli
mercenaries are basically non-existent.''
   News reports from Colombia said five Israelis were among
foreigners involved in training killers for the drug cartels.
   A report in Haaretz, an Israeli papter, said defense officials
ignored advice by the Foreign Ministry two years ago not to issue
permits for deals with private groups in Colombia because the
country was unstable.
   Al Hamishmar, another daily, said Rabin was angered by Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's expression of doubt, after Rabin ordered
an investigation, that any Israeli officers had behaved improperly.
   Israel radio said the allegations were raising questions in
Colombia about whether to order more Kfir jet fighters from Israel.
   Arms exports usually are secret in Israel, but the daily Yediot
Ahronot said Tuesday that Colombia had bought more than $350 million
worth of aircraft, guns and other military hardware from this
country in the past several years.
</TEXT>
