<HEAD>State Department Condemns Syrian Shelling Of Fuel Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Wednesday condemned
Syria's shelling of a tanker carrying badly needed fuel supplies to
the besieged capital of Lebanon.
   ``The United States deeply deplores the Syrian attack on the fuel
transport ship, Sunshield, off the coast of Lebanon, with apparent
loss of life among the crew,'' said spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   ``This incident points out the immediate need for all sides to
accept the cease-fire, lift the blockades, and allow a process of
political dialogue to begin under Arab League auspices,'' she said.
   The Maltese-flagged tanker was hit and set on fire Tuesday as it
tried to run the Syrian blockade along Beirut's Christian enclave.
Seven crewmen were killed and two were wounded. Police said two were
missing and believed dead.
   Nearly six months of fighting between Syria and its Moslem allies
and Lebanon's Christian forces have left at least 803 killed and
2,287 wounded.
