<FIRST>r i AM-Iran     08-30 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader Calls for Higher Living Standard at No Spiritual Cost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Iran's new
spiritual leader, urged the government Wednesday to raise living
standards without sacrificing emphasis on spiritual goals, Tehran
radio reported.
   It quoted Khamenei as telling President Hashemi Rafsanjani and
his new Cabinet:``People mustn't think that. ... untangling the
practical problems in the nation's life ... means moving away from
the revolution's spirituality and its Islamic goals.''
   Khamenei said Islam's ``enemies'' want Iranians to believe that,
if those who govern ``want to solve the problems of the people .. .
increase production in the country ... then probably this means
forgetting, weakening or discoloring the goals of the revolution and
the spiritual.''
   On Tuesday, the parliament approved all 22 ministers chosen by
Rafsanjani, despite speculation that some technocrats would be
rejected by those who wanted a more radical government.
   Rafsanjani seeks to revive the economy and attract foreign
capital to rebuild after the eight-year war with Iraq.
   Approval of the entire Cabinet showed the parliament
``understands well the realities of the country, understands the
issues and knows itself to be responsible in context of these
realities and this nation,'' said Khamenei, who was chosen as
spiritual leader after Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini died June 3.
   Missing from Rafsanjani's government are such hard-liners as
former Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, who is thought to
have links with groups holding foreign hostages in Lebanon, and
Mohammad Reyshahri, the former intelligence minister and a strong
opponent of restorig ties with the West.
   The main opposition group, the Mujahedeen Khalq based in Iraq,
said Rafsanjani will have to continue purging radical elements to
keep his program on track.
   Iranian newspapers repeated Khamenei's call for economic
development.
   ``Today is the beginning of a nationwide effort to construct and
rebuild the country in a manner suitable for an Islamic society,''
said an editorial in the radical, Farsi-language Abrar daily carried
by the official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   During the three-day Cabinet debate, Rafsanjani rebuffed claims
that his ministers lacked political experience. He said they ``have
the necessary political credentials, but this time the emphasis has
been to ensure that they are also functional.''
   ``Right now we have to put more effort into ensuring that the
programs passed by parliament are implemented,'' he said.
</TEXT>
