<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Lesotho     08-30 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Lesotho,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acting President Meets Another Black African Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting President F.W. de Klerk on
Wednesday held his third meeting in six days with a black African
leader, conferring with the chairman of Lesotho's military council
about disputes over a joint water project.
   After de Klerk's meeting with Maj. Gen. Justin Lekhanya, South
African Foriegn Minister Pik Botha said the leaders had resolved
differences in the two countries' interpretation of the treaty
governing the Lesotho Highlands Water Project. South Africa, which
surrounds Lesotho, is to purchase water produced by the project.
   De Klerk traveled Friday to a summit with President Mobutu Sese
Seko of Zaire and flew to Zambia on Monday for talks with President
Kenneth Kaunda, a staunch critic of South Africa's white-run
government.
   In Lesotho's capital of Maseru, a magistrate reconvened an
official inquiry Wednesday investigating Lekhanya's alleged
involvement in the shooting death of a college student.
   The inquiry, which had been in recess for several weeks, conerns
the death of George Ramone, 20, who was shot Dec. 23 at Lesotho
Agricultural College.
   No one has been charged, but newspapers in Britain and the United
States have reported Lekhanya admitted to the military council that
he shot the student.
   The reports said Lekhanya's bodyguard originally told police he
shot Ramone. Later, Lekhanya reportedly told the council he was
patrolling the campus and fired to stop an attempted rape.
   Lekhanya led a military coup in January 1986 that overthrew
left-leaning dictator Leabua Jonathan, whose support of the African
Nationalist Congress guerrilla organization had led to a South
African blockade of the small mountain kingdom.
   Lekhayna said in Pretoria the military council, which generally
enjoys good relations with South Africa, was working on a timetable
for restoring some sort of public participation in government. All
political parties currently are banned.
</TEXT>
