<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-War     08-30 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-War,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Act of Peace, Bells Dedicated in Gdansk Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bells of the St. Catherine's Church
carillon in this port city pealed Wednesday for the first time since
the end of World War II, a symbol of peace and reconciliation 50
years after the conflict began.
   The bells, a gift from the West German people to the residents of
Gdansk, were dedicated at a Mass celebrated by Bishop Tadeusz
Goclowski. Joining in readings during the service, for the intention
of the war's victims, was a German Evangelical minister.
   Afterward, Goclowski consecrated the bells with holy water and
the 1,000-member crowd of Poles and Germans listened to a
computer-directed carillon concert of works of Beethoven and Mozart.
The first melody played by the rededicated carillon was part of
Beethoven's Ninth Symphony.
   Friday is the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of World War II.
The first shots were fired in Gdansk on the morning of Sept. 1, 1939.
   Thirty-seven bells weighing more than 16 tons make up the
carillon, which replaces a set of bells that was lost during the
war, when the former Free City of Danzig was incorporated into the
Third Reich.
   At the end of the war, the city was largely destroyed, subjected
to Allied bombing raids, Soviet artillery and house-to-house
fighting during the Red Army's advance on the city in March 1945.
   The German population fled or was expelled after the war and
Danzig became the Polish city of Gdansk, causing anger among some
Germans toward Poles.
   But the theme of the rededication ceremony stressed
reconciliation between the nations.
   A former Gdansk resident, Hans Eggegrecht, headed the drive to
replace the bells after noticing the destroyed bell tower during a
trip to his native city five years ago.
   He organized a society in his new home of Bremen and even
traveled to the Vatican to obtain Pope John Paul II's spiritual
blessing for the project.
   The fund accumulated about $150,000 for the project, with
contributors including West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and West
German President Richard von Weizsaecker.
   The new bells were cast at the Dutch Royal Enterprise in Asten
and shipped to Gdansk. One of the bells was inscribed ``Peace and
Reconciliation.''
   St. Catherine's, located between the Old Town of Gdansk and the
Lenin Shipyard, birthplace of the Solidarity independent trade
union, has been the site of a St. Catherine's Church since the year
1261.
   The present church dates from the 15th century and was
reconstructed in 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
