<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     08-30 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Defends Interim Role for Khmer Rouge, Blames Cambodia, Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration blamed Vietnam and
Cambodia on Wednesday for the collapse of a 19-nation peace
conference on Cambodia and reiterated its reluctant support for a
Khmer Rouge role in a transitional government.
   The conference, launched in late July in Paris by Secretary of
State James A. Baker III and other foreign ministers, is dissolving
in disagreement over how to end the conflict between rival warring
actions.
   The collapse could result in stepped-up fighting between
government forces and an anti-communist resistance that includes
exiled Cambodian leader Prince Sihanouk and Khmer Rouge elements.
   When Baker flew to Paris to kick off the conference, there
already was recognition that a difficult compromise had to be struck
to end the civil war and that the deliberations could take months.
But there was guarded optimism the blood-letting might be ended with
diplomacy.
   Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen, who hopes to retain power after
the scheduled withdrawal of 26,000 Vietnamese troops from Cambodia a
month from now, strenuously objected to any role for the Khmer
Rouge, who were ousted in an invasion by Vietnam in 1978 and still
have China's support.
   The Khmer Rouge, under then-leader Pol Pot, is believed
responsible for the massacre of at least 1 million Cambodians from
1975 to 1978.
   Speaking in Washington for the Bush administration, Margaret
Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, registered unalterable
U.S. opposition to the Khmer Rouge returning to power. She called it
a ``murderous group.''
   However, she said the United States would continue to support
Sihanouk if he believed that Khmer Rouge elements, along with
members of the Phnom Penh government, ``should have an interim
role.''
   Asked why the conference had collapsed, she said ``it was not
possible to achieve a lasting settlement due to the failure of the
Vietnamese and Hun Sen regime to negotiate constructively on key
issues.''
   At the same time, the spokeswoman said ``progress was made toward
the important goal of a free and independent Cambodia.''
   ``Any progress is welcome and we should build upon it.''
</TEXT>
