<DOCNO> AP890830-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1813EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     08-30 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Says China's Economic Reforms to Continue; Paper Hits Zhao</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Li Peng said China's economic reforms
won't be abandoned, but official media Wednesday attacked a former
leader who helped foster those reforms.
   Li, in a speech seen Wednesday, said reforms adopted before June
will remain in effect and local governments can continue
experimenting with other reforms, Li said.
   ``Our policies can't be changed at will. This helps stabilize
people's hearts, stabilize stabilize the economy,''
Li said in a speech to the State Council, China's Cabinet.
   Protests by students demanding more social reforms to the ranks (and)
match
China's freer economy broke out April 15. China's leaders crushed
the pro-democracy movement with a military raid on demonstrators in
Beijing on June 3-4.
   Li gave the speech Aug. 15 but it was not published until
Tuesday, in Shanghai's Liberation Daily. The paper was seen in
Beijing on Wednesday. The release of speeches in China is often
delayed.
   Zhao Ziyang, the former Communist Party chief who helped carry
out China's liberalized economic reforms, wasn, increase the party's leadership
of enterprises in
ideological education, (and) develop the party's supervisory role.''
   The Beijing Daily commentary accused Zhao and his economic
adviser Bao Tong of violating the party constitution by advocating
policies that sought to reduce party interference in the economy and
to let some market forces rule.
   ``Bao Tong and others did their utmost to distort the supervisory
function of party organizations in enterprises (and) did everything
possible to limit and fetter'' them, the paper said.
   The reforms were beginning to see some success, with lively small
and medium-sized business and rural and township enterprises
invigorating the economy and making profits, unlike the ponderous,
state-owned enterprises. However, their rapid growth also caused
economic problems, such as shortages of raw materials and energy.
   The commentary quoted Zhao as saying in a 1986 meeting with
provincial governors, ``The big problems and issues in an enterprise
need not be discussed by the party committee. Otherwise, it would be
hard to put the (reforms) into effect. It is necessary to make some
some rather large changes to the original regulations.''
   Bao has been arrested and some reports say Zhao is under house
arrest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
