<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0619 08-30 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0619,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Envoy Meets Moslem Side Amid Shelling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS final graf with 3 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. comment on
tanker.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French envoy held talks with Moslem
leaders in west Beirut on Wednesday amid rocket and artillery duels
between Syrian and Christian forces across the embattled Lebanese
capital.
   Police said at least three people were killed and 50 wounded in
the exchanges.
   The casualties raised the overall toll to at least 805 killed and
2,318 wounded since March 8, when fighting erupted between army
commander Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly Christian units and Syrian
forces.
   The French diplomat, Francois Scheer, was accompanied by two
carloads of bodyguards on the trip from Christian east Beirut to the
Moslem sector across the embattled demarcation line.
   As he met with Sheik Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddine, the Shiite
Moslems' senior clergyman, five mortar rounds fired from the
Christian heartland exploded around the 10-story apartment building
in the Tallet Khayat district.
   The white-turbaned clergyman quickly ushered his guest to the
hallway near the elevator shaft for safety and continued their talks
for another 15 minutes.
   East Beirut also was under fire, and the wounded there included
two French communications engineers, police said.
   Scheer arrived in Beirut on Tuesday and met with Aoun and
Maronite Catholic Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir in east Beirut. He has
conferred in west Beirut with acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a
Sunni Moslem, Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite, and
Shiite militia chieftain Nabih Berri.
   Hoss heads a Cabinet competing for legitimacy with a three-man
government under Aoun.
   After his talks with Sfeir, Scheer, secretary-general of the
French Foreign Ministry, said: ``I'm trying to meet several Lebanese
leaders who are interested in inter-Lebanese dialogue.'' He did not
elaborate.
   The French ruled Lebanon from 1918 to 1943 and have traditionally
been the protectors of the Christians. They have antagonized Moslems
by dispatching a naval flotilla to the eastern Mediterranean to
evecuate French citizens if the crisis worsens.
   The French peace plan calls for lifting blockades imposed by both
sides, a halt to arms deliveries to the warring factions, political
reforms that will distribute power equally between Christians and
Moslems and the withdrawal of Syrian and Israeli forces from Lebanon.
   Syria has about 40,000 troops in Lebanon. They moved in under an
Arab League peacekeeping mandate in 1976 and are allied with Moslem
forces. Israel occupies a border strip in south Lebanon.
   The Voice of the People radio, the radio station of the
pro-Syrian Lebanese Communist Party, said Scheer's proposals have
been ``rejected by the nationalist (leftist) forces.''
   Moslems fear that if the blockade of the Christian enclave is
lifted without inspection of ships, Aoun will bring in more weapons
from Iraq, his main backer and Syria's archrival in the Arab world.
   The independent daily An-Nahar said Scheer told Moslems that Aoun
has demanded ``international guarantees to stop Syrian arms
shipments to the Moslem and leftist militias.''
   An Aoun aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
general ``does not accept the formation of an inter-Lebanese
committee to monitor arms supplies because we haven't been fighting
Lebanese factions.''
   The Christian Voice of Lebanon radio accused ``the Syrians and
their allies'' of escalating fighting ``to confuse any effort or
mediation to end the sufferings of the Lebanese...''
   The police spokesman said the duels Wednesday escalated at 1:20
a.m. after Syrian gunners shelled Christian-controlled waters north
of Beirut.
   Police said Aoun's coast guard command called off a search for
two missing sailors of the Maltese-flag tanker Sunshield, which was
hit by Syrian shellfire off the Christian coast on Tuesday.
   ``The two are presumed dead,'' the police spokesman said.
   Two wounded Lebanese sailors of the ship's 11-man crew were
rescued Tuesday and the bodies of seven others washed ashore.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Margaret Tutwiler said
the United States ``deeply deplores'' the Syrian attack on the ship.
   ``This incident points out the immediate need for all sides to
accept the cease-fire, lift the blockades, and allow a process of
political dialogue to begin under Arab League auspices,'' she said.
   Meanwhile, Soviet envoy Gennady Tarasov headed home after a
10-day tour in Syria, Lebanon, Jordan and Iraq, aimed at ending the
fighting.
</TEXT>
