<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Hostages     08-30 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Hostages,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officer in Hostage Crisis Relieved of Command</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Philippine Constabulary officer was
relieved of his command two weeks after he led an assault to free
hostages held by inmates in a siege in which 21 people died, the
military announced Wednesday.
   Legislators have criticized the military's handling of the crisis
in Davao City.
   However, Wilfred Garcia, the constabulary spokesman in Davao
City, gave no reason for the transfer of Capt. Poblio Gildo and
refused to say if it was connected to the hostage crisis.
   Gildo led the assault to end a three-day crisis when an
Australian missionary and 15 other people were held hostage by 16
prisoners.
   All the prisoners and five hostages, including the missionary,
were killed before troops regained control of the jail, 610 miles
southeast of Manila.
   Gildo was reassigned to the regional constabulary headquarters in
Davao but was not immediately given specific duties, Garcia said.
Gildo was succeeded by his deputy as commander of Davao City's 431st
Philippines Constabulary Company.
   Australian officials have said the missionary's wounds indicated
she may have been slain by government snipers who opened fire during
an abortive jailbreak a few hours before the prison was stormed.
