<FIRST>r a AM-TMICracks     08-30 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TMI Cracks,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cracks Confirmed In Three Mile Island's Steel Lining</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HX1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A TV camera lowered into the damaged Three
Mile Island reactor confirmed small cracks in a steel liner,
officials said Wednesday.
   The cracks in the Unit 2 reactor appear to be tears in the thin
stainless steel lining inside the 5-inch-thick carbon steel reactor
vessel, which contains the radioactive fuel and hot water
surrounding it, the plant operator said.
   Still unanswered is whether the cracks extend from the liner into
the reactor vessel.
   ``There isn't any way to tell definitely, but it's not considered
likely,'' said Doug Bedell, spokesman for the plant operator, GPU
Nuclear Corp.
   The reactor was damaged in 1979 in the U.S. nuclear power
industry's worst accident.
   The investigation of the cracks required a newly developed
radiation-resistant, high-resolution camera and special tools to
brush debris from the area, probe the cracks and take measurements
through 40 feet of water.
   The liner, three-sixteenths of an inch thick, prevents corrosion
of the steel below it. High fuel temperatures and the difference in
the contraction rates between the two types of steel caused the
cracks or tears, GPU Nuclear said.
   One crack was 6 inches long, about three-thirty-seconds of an
inch wide and about one-sixteenth of an inch deep, GPU Nuclear said.
Three other cracks were from 3 to 5 inches long, the plant operator
said.
   The color pictures taken Saturday revealed a few additional
cracks in an area where two lines thought to be cracks were spotted
in July, GPU Nuclear said.
   Molten uranium fuel as hot as 5,000 degrees flowed to the
reactor's bottom during the March 1979 accident that damaged the
reactor. A series of operator and mechanical errors cut off cooling
water to the radioactive core and about half the fuel rods melted.
Radioactive gas was released to the atmosphere.
   Since the accident, there has been no evidence that the vessel
was breached, Bedell said.
   TMI's Unit 1 reactor was undamaged and remains in service.
   Under a program sponsored in part by the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, samples of the steel will be removed for study by
researchers from Europe and Japan. The work is expected to take up
to 2{ years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
