<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1925EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AdolescentHealth     08-30 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Adolescent Health,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Educators, Doctors Join to Fight Early Youth Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed with evidence showing that 77 percent of
the nation's adolescent deaths each year are preventable, doctors
and educators joined Wednesday to form a group to attack problems
confronting youth.
   A national commission on adolescent health was formed by the
National Association of State Boards of Education and the American
Medical Association.
   The commission was formed, said Roseann Bentley, president of the
education association, ``when we observed that we could not reduce
our young people's vulnerability to AIDS, alcohol and drug
addiction, heart disease and other preventable illness without
changing their behavior.''
   ``Hungry, sick, violated, abused, doped up kids cannot learn,''
said Bentley. ``Research tells us that `one-shot' education programs
do not work, and that comprehensive multi-component programs that
change behavior are critical. I cannot overemphasize the need for
schools, families and communities to work together. ...''
   Ms. Bentley will serve as commission co-chairman along with Dr.
M. Roy Schwarz of the American Medical Association. Others on the
31-member commission include former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop,
Florida Education Commission Betty Castor, Illinois Gov. James
Thompson, California School Chief Bill Honig and pollster George
Gallup Jr.
   William Hendee, AMA vice president for science and technology,
said an estimated 77 percent of the nation's adolescent deaths each
year are preventable. In the 1950s, 75 percent of deaths of youths
aged 10 to 19 years were due to natural causes, compared with only
27 percent in the 1980s.
   Hendee added that more than 75 percent of seniors who tried
cigarettes first and almost 53 percent of seniors who have gotten
drunk first did so before starting high school. Rates for suicide
and birth for teens 10- to 14-years-old have gone up dramatically in
recent years.
   Both the AMA and education association said national attention
and community based efforts should focus on comprehensive school
health programs for all grades, kindergarten through 12th, and
particularly on programs for the disadvantaged and those involved in
risky or life-threatening behaviors.
</TEXT>
