<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1704EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-Pepper'sSeat-Abortion     08-30 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper's Seat-Abortion,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Groups Claim Pivotal Victory in Florida House Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion activists Wednesday claimed
Republican Ileana Ros-Lehtinen's election to succeed late Florida
Rep. Claude Pepper proves that their movement is ``alive and well''
in the wake of the Supreme Court's July 3 decision on abortion.
   Abortion rights supporters, however, said abortion was not a key
issue in the race between Ms. Ros-Lehtinen and Democrat Gerald
Richman, who had the support of abortion rights activists.
   During the campaign, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, 37, a state senator, said
she favored more restrictions on abortion and Richman said he
favored more choice. However, with polls indicating most voters
supported abortion rights, the GOP candidate said abortion was more
of a state legislative issue than a congressional issue.
   Sandra Faucher, director of the National Right to Life Political
Action Committee, told reporters the organization made a $1,000
contribution to Ms. Ros-Lehtinen in the Republican primary election
and spent about $15,000 for activities on her behalf in the general
election campaign.
   ``Ileana Ros-Lehtinen's win is a pivotal victory for the pro-life
movement,'' Ms. Faucher said at a news conference. ``Clearly, the
net pro-life increment is alive and well after the Webster
decision.''
   The Supreme Court's 5-4 ruling, giving states greater power to
limit abortions, appeared on the court's docket as Webster vs.
Reproductive Health Services.
   Ms. Faucher also said that abortion was ``a highly visible
issue'' in the Aug. 12 special election in Texas in which Republican
Bob Lanier, an abortion opponent, defeated Democrat Jim Lane for the
seat of former Speaker of the House Jim Wright.
   She said anti-abortion candidates also have won six of eight
state legislative races since the Supreme Court decision.
   Abortion rights leaders have contended that state legislative
victories in two races in California and South Carolina indicated
movement in their direction in the wake of the court ruling.
   Ms. Faucher, however, said anti-abortion candidates have won in
races in Missouri, Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia and two Florida
legislative districts.
   Kate Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion
Rights Action League, denied that abortion was a major issue in the
Florida and Texas congressional races or the legislative contests
cited by Ms. Faucher.
   ``The anti-choice movement is stretching a major point to claim
victory on the issue of abortion in that (Florida) race,'' she said.
``That was not the issue.''
   Republicans hailed Ros-Lehtinen's election as a major victory,
noting that Pepper had held the seat for the Democrats since 1962
when the seat was created. Pepper died May 30 at age 88.
   According to unofficial returns, predominantly Latin precincts
had turnouts of more than 60 percent and gave Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, the
first Cuban-American elected to Congress, 80 percent to 90 percent
of the vote. She carried the entire district by a 53 percent to 47
percent margin.
   Ms. Faucher, however, said ``Ileana could not have won the vote
with just the Hispanic vote. There is not a majority of Hispanics in
the district.''
   ``There had to be other issues involved, and we feel that
definitely the abortion issue played a major factor in the race,''
she said.
   Ms. Michelman, however, said, ``Nothing was an issue there that
could supersede the ethnicity issue. The fact is that no issue, even
the issue of choice, could overwhelm the ethnicity issue.''
   Ms. Michelman said the abortion rights group contributed $5,000
to Richman's campaign and spent about $2,500 on get-out-the-vote
efforts.
</TEXT>
