<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-PCBs     08-30 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-PCBs,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Shipload of PCBs Arrives in Quebec Town</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   BAIE-COMEAU, Quebec (AP) _ A second shipload of PCBs arrived at
this St. Lawrence River port Wednesday, the day after riot police
used clubs to disperse protesters so an earlier shipment could be
moved to temporary storage nearby.
   Judge Paul Corriveau of Quebec Superior Court turned down
applications by a citizen coalition in Baie-Comeau, Prime Minister
Brian Mulroney's hometown, for injunctions forbidding long-term
storage of polychlorinated biphenals, or PCBs, from elsewhere in
Quebec.
   It was the second consecutive day the coalition lost a legal
battle to prevent the unloading of toxic PCBs produced in
St.-Basile-le-Grand, Quebec, and destined for a nearby Hydro-Quebec
storage site. The waste was shipped to Britain for destruction, but
longshoremen refused to unload it.
   On Tuesday, shortly after refusal of the first applications,
police cleareed the way to the Manic 2 storage site for six trucks
loaded with PCB-laced oil.
   A V-formation of about 40 helmeted officers, truncheons held
chest-high, pushed through dozens of noisy demonstrators so the
convoy could leave the dock. Police said no one was injured and
there were no arrests.
   The waste had been on the wharf for six days after arriving on
the Nadezhda Obukhova, a Soviet freighter.
   Another Soviet freighter, the Khudozhnik Pakhomov, arrived
Wednesday after a two-week voyage from Britain.
   Provincial police tightened patrols around the dock area and
closed the area to passers-by.
   ``It's not over yet,'' said Shirley Kennedy, a lawyer for the
coalition of citizen groups. ``This is just one battle that has been
lost.''
   The shuttle of PCBs back and forth across the Atlantic has been
seen as an embarrassment for Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa's
Liberal Party as the Sept. 25 provincial election approaches.
   PCBs produce toxic byproducts such as dioxins and furans when
incompletely burned.
</TEXT>
