<FIRST>u w AM-SchoolLunches 1stLd-Writethru a0621 08-30 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Lunches, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Fat-Laden Foods Barrier to Healthy School Lunches</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 7th graf, bgng, Public Voice xxx etc., to clarify that
the reference is to the 1988-89 school year.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School lunchroom cooks are hampered in efforts
to provide nutritious meals because the government donates mainly
``fat-laden foods'' such as ground beef, pork and luncheon meats, a
consumer health group said Wednesday.
   Ellen Haas, director of the Public Voice for Food and Health
Policy, criticized the Agriculture Department, the agency
responsible for administering the National School Lunch Program, for
``not providing the critical leadership necessary to speed progress
in reducing fat in school lunches.''
   Scott Dunn, acting administator of USDA's Food and Nutrition
Service, countered by saying the department is committed to dietary
guidelines developed jointly with the Department of Health and Human
Services. He said the guidelines don't set quantitative standards
for fat.
   ``There is no scientific consensus on appropriate levels of fat
in children's diets,'' Dunn said.
   And the American School Food Service Association noted in a
statement that ``children's eating habits are influenced by multiple
factors such as home, school, and restaurants.'' It said parents and
community groups must share responsibility for improving young
people's dietary preferences.
   The consumer group said its survey of school food service
directors shows, nevertheless, that the government school lunch
program lends little encouragement to dieticians seeking to lower
the fat content of lunches.
   Public Voice said 67 percent of 177 school food service directors
surveyed told it that the USDA's commodity distribution program is
one of the most significant barriers to their efforts to provide
nutritious meals. More than 24 million children participated in
lunch programs at more than 91,000 schools during the 1988-89
academic year.
   The school lunch programs depend, to some extent, on commodities
provided free of charge by the federal government, to help them stay
afloat financially, the group said. ``Yet,'' it said, ``the
commodities offered include a high proportion of fat-laden foods.''
   Public Voice said that Agriculture Department-disbursed commodity
foods account for about 30 percent of foods used for school lunches.
Of the total estimated dollar value of the commodities available _
$817.4 million _ ground beef and pork, luncheon meat and ham,
butter, cheese and eggs constituted well over 50 percent, it said.
   Of the ``bonus'' commodities offered to schools _ or commodities
furnished above the basic allotments _ butter, cheese, pork, beef,
and eggs comprised more than 90 percent of the dollar value, the
group said.
   It said that more than 80 percent of the directors surveyed said
they have taken some steps to reduce fat in their school lunches.
   Contrary to Dunn's statement, Public Voice said there is a
consensus among health professionals that fat in children's diets
should be reduced to about 30 percent of calories.
   Among other findings were these:
   _Only 6 percent of the directors surveyed had established target
levels or ranges for fat in their programs. Central city school
districts were eight times more likely to establish such limits than
were rural districts.
   _Seventy-seven percent reported having limited access to written
matrials or training programs on how to purchase foods or modify
recipes to reduce fat content. Twenty-three percent said they did
not receive any guidance or guidelines.
   _When asked to identify the single most important thing that
could be done to help reduce fat, 50 percent of the respondents said
the commodity program should be changed and 26 percent said more
nutritional education should be provided. The remaining 24 percent
were uncertain.
   Public Voice recommended that the Agriculture Department provide
greater leadership in educating school food service directors and in
offering assistance in planning monthly menus, including suggesting
how often specific foods should be served.
   The USDA also should significantly expand the availability of
lower-fat commodities to the schools, the group said.
   Said Dunn: ``It is important to remember that no matter what
level is deemed appropriate, that level must be applied to a
person's entire diet, not to a single food or a single meal. USDA
cannot at this time support setting quantitative fat standards or
recommended frequency of serving certain foods.''
   The variety of foods donated to schools is under constant review,
he said, adding that ``over the years significant progress has been
made in providing more and more healthy, wholesome foods, including
additional low-and reduced-fat foods.''
   Dunn also said his agency promotes and coordinates nutrition
education and technical assistance for all involved in the school
lunch program, although he said that states ``have great flexibility
in how they spend the money they have available for training.''
   The American Food Service Association said in its statement that
young people's dietary habits are largely affected by national
advertising, which it called ``a major influence on children's food
preferences.''
   ``If change is to become a reality, dietary modifications in
school menus must be supported by parents and the community,'' it
said.
</TEXT>
