<FIRST>r w AM-Weiss-GOP     08-30 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weiss-GOP,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weiss: What, Me Republican?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was an invitation Rep. Ted Weiss was only
too happy to refuse.
   Weiss received a form letter signed by President Bush saying he
had been nominated by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., to the
Republican Senatorial Inner Circle, a clique of party loyalists who
give at least $1,000 a year to the National Republican Senatorial
Committee.
   Problem is, Weiss is a Democrat _ a very liberal Democrat.
   ``The Inner Circle has many outstanding members including Joe
Coors, Estee Lauder, Arnold Schwarzenegger,'' the Bush letter said.
``I know you will enjoy meeting your fellow members at Inner Circle
gatherings both in Washington, D.C., and around the country.''
   Weiss said Wednesday he respectfully declines.
   ``And all this time I thought I was a dyed-in-the-wool liberal,''
he said. ``Either my fellow congressmen from across the aisle have
had a change of heart or I've been terribly misinformed about their
political philosophy.''
   But why would D'Amato nominate Weiss in the first place?
   According to D'Amato spokeswoman Zenia Mucha, he didn't.
   ``The senator lends his name for fund-raising for the party,''
she said. Weiss's name ``must have been on some mailing list that
was not purged.''
   Wendy DeMocker, spokeswoman for the Republican Senatorial
Committee, said: ``We're not going to consider it a mistake. We're
going to say, well, there's hope for everybody.''
   She ticked the names off several onetime Democrats who switched
to the GOP: Ronald Reagan, Elizabeth Dole, Jeane Kirkpatrick.
   ``And so if Congressman Weiss received one of these, well, we've
certainly had a lot of members of Congress in the House of
Representatives recently convert to the Republican Party,'' she said.
</TEXT>
