<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Biden-Drugs     08-30 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Biden-Drugs,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biden Proposes `Debt-for-Drugs' Incentives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., unveiled on
Wednesday ``debt-for-drugs'' legislation intended to offer
debt-relief incentives to Latin American nations that subsidize the
withdrawal of farm land from coca production.
   The legislation, to be introduced when Congress reconvenes next
week, is modeled on debt-for-nature exchanges already in place to
help protect tropical rain forests.
   Biden asserted in a statement that a U.S. investment of $400
million in a debt-for-drugs plan could free up enough funds to
subsidize the withdrawal of every acre in Bolivia, Columbia and Peru
now in coca production.
   Coca crops are refined to produce cocaine, one of the principal
illicit drugs on the U.S. narcotics market.
   Biden, who is to deliver the Democratic response to President
Bush's nationally televised adddress on drug policy next Tuesday
evening, said that for the immediate future the United States must
continue to extradite foreign drug traffickers for trial in U.S.
courts.
   ``But in the long run, the best way to cut coca production is to
provide economic incentives to grow other crops,' Biden said.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., who returned this week from a 14-day
visit to nine Latin American countries, contends that substituting
other crops for coca will simply spread production of the enormously
profitable crop to other countries.
   Lugar said the best hope is an intensive campaign to reduce
narcotic consumption in the United States by discouraging first-time
and casual users and by rehabilitating addicts.
   Biden, however, said his plan can work in the countries involved
and has a ``realistic prospect of winning public support in this
country.''
   ``It is not a giveaway with no strings attached,'' he said.
``Americans love a good deal, and the debt-for-drugs plan is exactly
that.''
   Under the Biden legislation the United States, hopefully with the
help of U.S. allies, would create an international fund to negotiate
debt-for-drugs exchanges.
   The fund would purchase debt owed to foreign banks by the
governments of coca-producing nations.
   Once a sizeable amount of debt had been acquired the fund would
offer to forgive a coca-producing nation's interest on it for a year
in exchange for subsidies to shift farmers out of coca production.
   Once coca reduction targets were reached, the fund would forgive
the outstanding debt in full.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0146 </DOCNO>
