<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     08-30 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Increases Security, Opposition Charges Repression</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government kept secret the formula
it will unveil this week for a new administration, but it increased
security throughout Panama on Wednesday in anticipation of violent
demonstrations.
   Officials of the current administration have made clear that the
new government will be announced and will take office on Friday,
when the term of Acting President Manuel Solis expires.
   It will have the blessing of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who as
commander of the Panamanian Defense Forces is the power behind the
civilian administration. The Defense Forces include both soldiers
and police.
   Paramilitary groups organized into national defense committees
trained in different sites throughout the capital on Wednesday and
government agencies said they were placing themselves on a state of
alert.
   Opposition leaders said they planned no street protests against
the installation of a new government on Friday.
   ``If anything happens, it will be spontaneous,'' said former
opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara in an interview
Wednesday. ``Nothing special is going to happen on Friday. The
government will change some figures and will retain others.''
   Endara claims he won the May 7 elections, which were annulled by
the government.
   The opposition refused a government offer to form a national
reconciliation government. The government rejected opposition
demands that its victory be recognized and that Noriega step down.
   Government officials said all formulas were being considered in
the formation of the new government. However, sources, speaking on
the condition of anonymity, said it appeared the new government
would consist of a junta with civilian and military representatives.
   The governemnt scheduled a special Cabinet session for Thursday
morning.
   A special session of the Organization of American States will be
held in Washington on Thursday at the request of the U.S. government
after a Panamanian OAS delegate challenged the Bush administration
to present evidence of Noriega's alleged involvement in drug
trafficking.
   Noriega was indicted on federal drug trafficking charges in the
United States in February 1988.
   Noriega has commanded the Defense Forces since 1983 and is
considered the country's most powerful figure. He has become the
target of a U.S. campaign to remove him, and internally he is
accused by the political opposition of repression and violation of
human rights.
   Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter called the U.S. request for a
special OAS meeting an attempt ``to divert the continent's attention
away from what should be the main issue.''
   The focus of attention should be U.S. aggression, not Noriega, he
said.
   Noriega denies the drug trafficking charges and accuses the
United States of trying to oust him because of his nationalistic
policies.
   Opposition leaders said Wednesday that arrests announced by the
government were part of the ``propaganda and repression campaign of
the military.''
   Former vice presidential candidate Ricardo Arias Calderon told
The Associated Press that 11 persons had been arrested, most of them
members of this Christian Democrat Party.
</TEXT>
