<FIRST>r a AM-LesbianSlaying     08-30 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lesbian Slaying,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney Says Defendant in Lesbian Slaying Trial Feared for Her Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who contends she killed her
lesbian lover because she was a victim of ``battered spouse
syndrome'' had been abused for years and feared for her life, her
lawyer said at her trial Wednesday.
   Annette Green, 30, was beaten and tormented for 11 years before
she fired a .38-caliber pistol into the head of Ivonne Julio, 32,
after a Halloween party last year, said defense attorney William
Lasley.
   Lasley hopes to introduce expert testimony at the murder trial to
prove she suffered from battered spouse syndrome and acted in
self-defense.
   Attorneys for both sides believe the trial is one of the first in
which the syndrome defense, usually employed in cases involving
long-term abusive heterosexual relationships, has been applied in
one involving a homosexual union.
   Ms. Green's love for Ms. Julio's teen-age twin daughters kept her
from ending the stormy relationship, Lasley said during a break in
the first day of testimony Wednesday.
   ``For 11 years, she was the mother of (Ms. Julio's) twins and
performed the domestic duties of the relationship,'' Lasley said.
``She was frequently battered and abused physically and
psychologically, along with the children.''
   Judge Thomas Waddell is expected to rule next week whether to
allow experts to testify about battered spouse syndrome.
   Assistant State Attorney Bob Johnson has said he'll challenge any
attempt to bring the syndrome into the case because, he said, there
is no research involving homosexual relationships.
   The prosecution maintains that Ms. Julio was killed while she was
in the closet of the mobile home the women shared. ``Ivonne Julio
was down on her knees in the closet begging for her life,'' Johnson
told jurors Tuesday.
   Jurors on Wednesday got a glimpse of the events that night in a
taped interview police had with Ms. Green hours after the shooting.
   The women, who had been drinking, had just returned from the
party when an argument erupted, and Ms. Julio pulled out her gun
from the closet, Ms. Green said on the tape.
   Ms. Green said she grabbed a knife that had been on a nightstand
because she thought Ms. Julio would kill her. ``I was afraid,'' she
said. ``There was a point I thought she was going to shoot me and I
just ran into her'' and grabbed the gun.
   Ms. Green said she didn't recall firing the weapon or what
happened to the knife, but admitted to the slaying.
   Ms. Green, who worked at a plant nursery last year, said the
relationship had been bad for a long time. ``It was driving me
nuts,'' she said.
   If convicted, Ms. Green could face life in prison.
</TEXT>
