<FIRST>u i AM-ChemicalArms     08-30 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Arms,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Superpower Chemical Arms Accord Gets Final Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in Washington and Moscow have approved a
draft U.S.-Soviet accord on how to conduct inspections of chemical
arms sites under a future comprehensive ban on the weapons, a U.S.
negotiator said Wednesday.
   Superpower negotiators in Geneva meanwhile completed a proposed
agreement on guidelines for the gradual destruction of chemical
weapons stockpiles and installations over a 10-year period, U.S.
envoy Max Friedersdorf said.
   Both issues are major parts of long-standing, 40-nation
negotiations in Geneva on a global convention banning production,
stockpiling and use of chemical weapons.
   Friedersdorf said the U.S. side and the Soviets had not yet
agreed on how to carry out a proposed exchange of chemical arms data
between Washington and Moscow before a convention is ready.
   He commented after the latest 10-day round of periodic
U.S.-Soviet expert talks on chemical weapons.
   The paper approved in Washington and Moscow deals with procedures
for so-called challenge inspections in the United States and the
Soviet Union, the two countries with the biggest chemical arsenals.
   Under the proposed worldwide ban, challenge inspection will allow
any country to demand a short-notice, spot probe by international
experts of any suspected chemical weapons site.
   Points covered in the U.S.-Soviet accord include how to trigger
inspections and how to deal with their findings, Friedersdorf said
in an interview in the U.S. mission's daily newsletter.
</TEXT>
