<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Glance     08-30 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Glance,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Developments in Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the latest developments in Colombia's war
with drug traffickers:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CURFEWS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Minister Orlando Vasquez imposed a curfew in Medellin
and nine other cities in cocaine country to curb violence by drug
barons.
   The orders affect about 3 million people and give mayors broader
powers to conduct searches, inspect vehicles and arrest suspects.
   Vasquez said 100 officers had been dispatched to Medellin and
said military forces were ordered to intensify their crackdown.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. EMBASSY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government ordered families of its embassy staff to
leave Colombia because of fears of attacks by drug traffickers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE RESIGNATIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Three more judges resigned in Medellin Tuesday. Since the
government's offensive began, 108 judges have resigned in protest
over what they feel is a lack of adequate security. The Supreme
Court has ordered the judges to resume their duties.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WEAPONS INTERCEPTED</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   National police said they intercepted a Medellin-bound arms
shipment, including 169 grenades for use with a launcher, 40
fragmentation grenades and 600 firearms cartridges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE THREATS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Pablo Escobar Gaviria, reputed leader of the Medellin cartel,
said the drug lords are prepared for total war if the government
refuses to make peace, the French newspaper Liberation said.
   He reportedly said drug traffickers would be willing to let the
government keep all the property it has seized if narcotics
chieftains were allowed to rejoin society. If the government
declines, Liberation quoted him as saying, ``There will be some
deaths, always more deaths.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MEDELLIN MAYOR</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Medellin Mayor Juan Gomez Martinez complained of a lack of
security assistance from the national government, saying it agreed
to provide an extra 100 police officers rather than the 3,000 he
requested to bolster the existing force of 4,000.
   The mayor said his suggestion to negotiate with the traffickers
had been rejected by the government, and that he was carrying out
all anti-narcotics measures ordered by national authorities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ISRAEL-COLOMBIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said allegations that
former army officers gave paramilitary trianing to assassination
squads for Colombian drug lords are overblown.
   Police questioned two more employees of a security and arms
trading company said to have provided training for the Medellin
cartel.
   Yair Klein, a reserve lieutenant colonel who heads the company,
confirmed an Israeli official told him to leave Colombia because he
might be arrested.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. AID</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   An administration source said President Bush's drug control
strategy will call for $250 million to $260 million in economic and
military aid for Colombia, Peru and Bolivia.
   Although Colombia was the focus of Bush's meeting Tuesday with
drug advisers, sources said no specific decisions were made on
future aid to that country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
