<FIRST>u a AM-Swindall     08-30 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swindall Says Father Abused Him and Siblings; Father Denies It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Pat Swindall, sentenced to prison this
week for lying to a federal grand jury, says he didn't take the
stand at his perjury trial for fear of revealing he and his siblings
were abused by their father.
   Swindall's father denied the allegations, and a prosecutor said
the former congressman was suffering from ``a severe case of Monday
morning quarterbacking.''
   Swindall told reporters Tuesday that he and his siblings were all
abused by their father, Nathan Swindall.
   He said he and his brothers, Kevin and Philip, and his sister,
Theresa, discussed the matter and agreed he should come forward.
   He gave no details of his alleged abuse.
   The 38-year-old Republican who represented Atlanta's eastern
suburbs in Congress for two terms until his defeat in 1988 was
sentenced Monday to a year in prison and fined $30,000 on nine
counts of perjury. He is free on appeal.
   Swindall was convicted June 20 of lying to a grand jury in 1988
about negotiations for an $850,000 loan from a federal agent posing
as a drug-money launderer.
   The loan to help finance his $1.5 million Stone Mountain home was
never completed. Swindall was convicted of perjury for denying he
was told the loan might contain drug profits. He later said he was
tired and his memory faulty.
   ``My father's a very sick man,'' Swindall said Tuesday. ``You can
go back to 1966 at Emory University Hospital. You will find that my
sister was admitted in June of 1966 with hysterical paralysis.''
   Emory spokeswoman Judy Smith said Wednesday the hospital would
not release information on Theresa Swindall. ``If she's got her own
medical records, she can do it for herself, but we certainly
wouldn't do that,'' she said.
   Swindall also said he and his brother David were admitted to the
hospital for ulcers that same summer.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr said he did not believe the allegations
would have been raised at trial by the prosecution.
   ``As far as I can tell this has nothing to do with his case; he's
having a severe case of Monday morning quarterbacking,'' Barr said.
``There was nothing in evidence relating to this and, I don't
believe, in any pretrial evidence.''
   Swindall provided reporters with a copy of a 1987 deposition by
his father concerning a dispute over a loan for a family business.
But he said he had removed a number of pages that referred to
allegations of abuse.
   Swindall's sister said in an interview with The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution that her father had sexually abused her as a
teen-ager but that her siblings had agreed not to discuss the matter
publicly until now.
   Swindall's father, Nathan, denied abusing his daughter. ``When
anybody accuses me of incest he better be proving it. I deny that
completely,'' he said.
   ``It's strange this wouldn't come out until there's money
involved,'' Nathan Swindall said. ``I don't know how much he paid
his sister to say these things.''
</TEXT>
