<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-30 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Thunderstorms In The Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms that developed in warm, moist air ahead
of a cold front were scattered across the Southeast on Wednesday,
with locally heavy rain.
   Showers and thunderstorms were most numerous from the Gulf Coast
to the Tennessee Valley, and across southern Missouri, southern
Kansas and northern Oklahoma.
   Heavier rainfall for the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 1.87
inches at Miami and 0.97 of an inch at Crossville, Tenn.
   An extension of the cold front also produced showers and
thunderstorms over western Maine and northern New Hampshire.
   Elsewhere, showers and a few thunderstorms developed over New
Mexico, southern Minnesota and the northern Rocky Mountains.
   Temperatures warmed into the 90s across much of the southern
Plains and parts of the Southeast, but were only in the 60s from
Upper Michigan through eastern North Dakota to northern Montana and
in the 50s and 60s over much of the Northwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 102 at Blythe and Needles, Calif.
Wednesday morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 34 at Gunnison,
Colo.
   For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from Florida and the central Gulf Coast region to the upper Great
Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley, and across the northern half
of the Great Plains region and the northern half of the Rocky
Mountains. Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
over Arizona.
   Highs in the 60s were predicted from northern Montana to northern
Washington state; in the 70s from the rest of the northern Pacific
Coast to North Dakota, and from Minnesota through the Great Lakes to
northern New England, and along the coast of California; in the 90s
from the southern and central Plains to the southern Atlantic Coast,
and from southern New Mexico to the southern and central valleys of
California, and above 100 in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
