<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     08-30 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, who hasn't had any
luck fishing on his summer vacation, jokingly asked a newspaper
Wednesday to stop running a ``no-fish'' logo chronicling his
rod-and-reel failures.
   The Portland Press Herald's graphic consists of a circle with a
line drawn through a bluefish, similar to the ``Ghostbusters'' logo.
   Bush, whose hook has come up empty for 13 days in a row, said he
planned to call the newspaper's editor.
   ``I think they should knock off that advertisement,'' he said
during a presentation by the Chamber of Commerce for this seaside
resort and neighboring Kennebunk.
   Bush pointed out that someone else on his boat had caught a fish.
   But Press Herald Executive Editor John K. Murphy said that wasn't
going to be enough to stop the graphic, which the paper plans to
keep running as long as Bush's luck stays poor.
   ``I think the president's suggestion that we credit any fish
caught on his boat sounds fishy,'' Murphy said. ``We are eagerly
awaiting his first catch of his vacation.''
   Bush has until Tuesday, when he plans to head back to Washington,
to catch a fish.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bears are back. Just ask Betty Klasnya.
   ``I was sitting on my back steps, going through a bag of seeds
for planting, when I felt something was out there looking at me,''
said Klasnya.
   The ``something'' was a 200-pound black bear in her back yard
relishing the aroma of pork chops frying on the stove.
   She ran inside, replaced the pork chops with garlic and onions to
encourage the bear's departure, clapped her hands and made a fuss
until the animal sauntered back into the woods.
   ``I'm not going to fry pork chops or bacon till the bear season
is over,'' she said.
   Since last week's encounter, police have received more than 20
reports of bear sightings around this Lake Superior city.
   The bears are in town for their late-summer gorging in greater
numbers than in the last two years.
   The influx, however, doesn't come close to the invasion of 1985,
when dozens of bears, searching for food here because of poor berry
and nut supplies in the woods, were sighted some days.
   A poor crop of hazelnuts, one of bears' favorite foods, and an
increased bear population, is forcing bears to move as far south as
Duluth, experts say.
   Researcher Lynn Rogers said bears that come to Duluth looking for
a meal feed on clover, apples _ and garbage.
</TEXT>
