<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0641 08-30 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodia Conference Ends Without Peace Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to include comment by Sinhanouk, Dumas, Indonesian
minister and Hun Sen. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAR4,7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international conference on Cambodia could not
produce an agreement and suspended its work Wednesday until warring
factions are ready for a compromise to end a generation of violence.
   ``We need time so the spirit of reconciliation can overcome the
spirit of confrontation, but for Cambodia the hour of peace will
come,'' Roland Dumas, the French foreign minister, told the
delegates just before adjourning the final session.
   Some delegates said the failure increased the likelihood of
full-scale civil war when Vietnam withdraws its military forces
Sept. 27 after nearly 11 years of occupation.
   Last-minute negotiations delayed a final statement by seven
hours. It fell far short of the comprehensive settlement delegates
from 19 nations hoped to achieve when the conference opened in late
July.
   The statement said the meeting ``achieved progress in elaborating
a wide variety of elements necessary for the reaching of a
comprehensive settlement to the tragic conflict in Cambodia,'' but
added: ``It is not yet possible to achieve a comprehensive
settlement. It was therefore decided to suspend the conference.''
   France and Indonesia offered to help mediate between the
Vietnam-sponsored government of Premier Hun Sen and the
three-faction rebel alliance led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, who
ruled Cambodia until a coup in 1970.
   ``We will come back to Paris,'' Sihanouk said as he left the
conference hall. ``The problem is complicated. We must be patient.''
   Dumas told reporters the work of a fact-finding commission sent
to Cambodia and other groundwork by the conference may pay off when
the parties are ready to compromise.
   Ali Alatas, foreign minister of Indonesia, said: ``There have
been too many casualties, too much suffering, too much bitterness.
... The very fact that we can sit down together, I think this was
quite a feat.''
   Delegates left open the possiblity of using committees set up
under conference auspices for future talks between the belligerents.
   According to the final statement, France and Indonesia ``will
begin consultations within six months with the participants in the
conference with a view to reconvening the conference.''
   France called the meeting when a climate of greater cooperation
appeared to make settlement possible, but positions of the Cambodian
factions hardened during three weeks of negotiations in small
working groups.
   Dumas said negotiations broke down on five points, including
composition of a transitional government, how to monitor the
withdrawal and use of the word ``genocide'' in describing Khmer
Rouge rule from April 1975 until Vietnam invaded in December 1978.
   An estimated 1 million Cambodians died under the Khmer Rouge,
which now is the strongest of the three rebel factions.
   Hun Sen told reporters: ``We know it is the Khmer Rouge who have
ruined the outcome of this conference, who have scuttled it.''
   He said the conduct of the Khmer Rouge and its allies suggested
they were preparing for civil war and ``it confirms and presages new
massacres of millions of Cambodians.''
   The Bush administration blamed Vietnam and Cambodia for the
collapse of the peace conference, and reiterated reluctant support
for a Khmer Rouge role in a transitional government.
   Margaret Tutwiler, a State Department spokeswoman in Washington,
said ``it was not possible to achieve a lasting settlement due to
the failure of the Vietnamese and Hun Sen regime to negotiate
constructively on key issues.''
   At the same time, she said ``progress was made toward the
important goal of a free and independent Cambodia. Any progress is
welcome and we should build upon it.''
   Tommy Koh, spokesman for the Singapore delegation, said: ``It
will be like Afghanistan'' after the Vietnamese withdraw. ``There
will be more fighting. The two sides are preparing for war; they're
already fighting.''
   Intransigence that marked the meeting throughout held up the
final session, which was scheduled to begin in the morning but was
delayed until late afternoon.
   Points of disagreement included an item in a draft of the final
statement calling for the Cambodian parties to intensify ``efforts
to achieve national reconciliation.''
   Both China, which supports the Khmer Rouge, and Sihanouk objected
to the reference to national reconciliation and it was deleted.
   Their position remains that the government led by Hun Sen is
merely a Vietnamese puppet.
   Sihanouk said the resistance would reject any international
monitoring of the withdrawal ``before the dismantling of the illegal
regime of Phnom Penh and its replacement by a Cambodian provisional
quadrapartite government'' of the three resistance groups and Hun
Sen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
