<FIRST>u a AM-TroubledMayor     08-30 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Troubled Mayor,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe of L.A. Mayor Uncovers No Criminal Impropriety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City investigators appear ready to conclude
that Mayor Tom Bradley could face civil fines but committed no
crimes when he was paid by banks doing business with the city,
newspapers reported Wednesday.
   The Los Angeles Times and Los Angeles Herald Examiner quoted
unidentified sources as saying the report from City Attorney James
Hahn is due in two weeks.
   But the sources also cautioned that new information could change
the recommendations.
   Bradley still faces an investigation by the U.S. Justice
Department into his finances.
   Hahn plans to recommend the city sue the mayor to collect about
$200,000 in fines for financial reporting violations, the newspapers
said. Such fines are subject to negotiation.
   ``The mayor has said ... he will answer questions once the report
is distributed,'' Bradley spokesman Bill Chandler said Wednesday.
``He will still wait for the final report.''
   A spokesman for the City Attorney's office declined comment.
   The mayor, a former city policeman and councilman, won an
unprecedented fifth term April 11.
   Federal investigators are analyzing Bradley's many investments
with Drexel Burnham Lambert and Michael Milken, the former junk bond
king who recently resigned from the investment firm after he was
indicted on fraud charges.
   Hahn's inquiry focuses on the 71-year-old mayor's connection to
Far East National Bank. The bank paid Bradley $18,000 for consulting.
   After some inquiries by Bradley, City Treasurer Leonard
Rittenberg subsequently had $2 million in city funds deposited with
the bank. Both Bradley and Rittenberg deny pressure was applied to
make the deposit.
   Bradley returned the $18,000 consulting fee after allegations of
favoritism surfaced.
   The city attorney is also looking into whether Bradley violated
conflict-of-interest laws by accepting payments from a savings and
loan association, and is examining more than 100 errors in the
mayor's disclosures regarding his extensive stock portfolio and
property holdings.
   Sources also said Hahn's report will not make any recommendations
related to Juanita St. John, who is being investigated for failure
to account for $180,000 in city funds allocated to the Task Force
for Africa-Los Angeles Relations.
   Ms. St. John, a longtime friend and business partner of
Bradley's, ran the mayoral task force before it was shut down
because of persistent debt problems.
</TEXT>
