<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1902EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Palestine     08-30 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Palestine,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Deplores Israeli Deportation of Arabs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council adopted a resolution
Wednesday deploring Israel's deportation of Arabs suspected of
organizing the Palestinian uprising, the strongest action it has
taken yet on the deportation issue.
   The United States refused to use its veto power to protect
Israel, and abstained. The resolution passed 14-0.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering, a former ambassador to
Israel, said deportations are unhelpful and provoke Arab-Israeli
tension in the region.
   ``The United States continues to feel very strongly about
deportations,'' Pickering said after leaving the council chamber.
   ``It's a view that we've expressed many times to the government
of Israel and it's a view that we expressed in our statement today
when we abstained on the vote.''
   On Sunday, Israel deported five Arabs from the West Bank, sending
four to Lebanon and one to France.
   In July, the council passed a similar resolution using milder
language, saying it ``deeply regrets'' such expulsions. That
resolution also passed 14-0, with America abstaining.
   Israeli Ambassador Johanan Bein said ``wordings are not
important. What is important is that at a time when carnage is going
on in Lebanon and murders are going on in the (occupied) territories
... the Security Council meets here for this nonsense and is very
quick to act.''
   He added that ``what is disturbing is that it looks like the
United States is giving in.''
   Wednesday's resolution ``deplores the continuing deportation by
Israel, the occupying power, of Palestinian civilians.'' It asks
Israel to return those expelled and halt the policy.
   It also asks Israel to abide by the Geneva Convention that
protects the rights of civilians in zones under military occupation.
   Bein castigated the Palestine Liberation Organization for
instigating the 20-month-old insurrection. He said Israel is the
focus of one-sided Security Council criticism.
   Palestinians on Dec. 8, 1987, began their uprising against
Israeli rule in lands occupied in the 1967 Middle East war, often
stoning soldiers and Israeli settlers. At least 554 Palestinians
have been killed in clashes with soldiers or Israeli civilians since
then. Thirty-eight Israelis also have been killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
