<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Britain     08-30 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Britain,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says British Mercenaries Tried To Kill Drug Lord</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British television station reported Wednesday
that 11 British mercenaries were involved in an unsuccessful attempt
in June to kill Pablo Escobar Gaviria, a reputed Colombian cocaine
baron.
   Independent Television News said the men were hired by a rival
drug gang it did not name to kill Escobar, said to be a leader of
the Medellin cartel.
   It showed film of men in camouflage gear in helicopters and in a
jungle, and said the ``exclusive'' footage depicted rehearsals for
the June 4 assassination attempt. Independent Television News said
it understood one of the mercenaries made the film.
   The attempt failed when one of two helicopters crashed while
flying low over the Escobar estate, killing the pilot, according to
the report.
   It said the British mercenaries had intended to drop explosives
on Escobar's house, land and kill everyone in the area. The report
said all the mercenaries survived the crash, implying the pilot was
Colombian.
   Turning to the United States, it said President Bush was
concerned and ``the activities of British mercenaries in Colombia
has been high on his Cabinet's agenda. They want them investigated
by the British government.''
   A Foreign Office spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said: ``While
we are in touch with the Americans about this drug problem, there
has been no specific request for an investigation of this kind.''
   On Tuesday, the State Department said it had asked the British
government to investigate allegations that Britons helped train
teams of assassins for Colombian drug traffickers. The traffickers
have blamed for the assassination of a leading Colombian
presidential candidate on Aug. 18, which prompted an unprecedented
government crackdown on the drug lords.
   George Foulkes, a spokesman for Britain's opposition Labor Party,
said the government should prosecute the mercenaries and cancel
their passports. ``It's illegal for British citizens to take up arms
against a friendly country and Colombia is friendly,'' he told
Independent Television News.
</TEXT>
