<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1935EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PlutoniumWaste     08-30 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plutonium Waste,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Approves Stainless-Steel Waste Transport Container</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT MYGATT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a decade of research and
development culminated Wednesday in federal approval of a steel
container to hold plutonium-contaminated trash during shipment to a
repository in New Mexico.
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission approved TRUPACT-2, which the
Energy Department will use to haul waste to its Waste Isolation
Pilot Plant, a desert repository carved out of salt beds 2,150 feet
below the surface of the Earth.
   TRUPACT-2 _ a cylindrical, stainless-steel vault-within-a-vault
with 10 inches of polyurethane cushioning in between _ was designed
and tested by the Energy Department. It is manufactured by Nuclear
Packaging Inc. of Federal Way, Wash.
   ``This certainly is one of the critical milestones to opening the
Waste Isolation Pilot Plant,'' said Jim Tollison, Energy Department
manager of waste transportation for the plant, 26 miles southeast of
Carlsbad.
   Tollison said the 10-foot containers will cost about $200,000
each and the trailers to haul them about $20,000 apiece.
   Robert Neill, director of the Environmental Evaluation Group, a
federally funded state watchdog agency, said of the NRC's approval,
``We're real pleased it passed muster.''
   But Don Hancock, director of the Southwest Research and
Information Center's nuclear waste safety project, said the product
was not adequately evaluated. The organization is a private,
non-profit watchdog group.
   A longer evaulation ``would have included the NRC reviewing the
quality assurance program,'' said Hancock.
   Tollison said the NRC had been reviewing the container program,
which had its birth in the late 1970s, since 1987.
   TRUPACT stands for Transuranic Packaging Transporter. Transuranic
wastes are those contaminated with radioactive elements heavier than
uranium. The waste includes such things as gloves and tools.
   Each TRUPACT-2 container will hold up to 14 55-gallon drums of
radioactive waste generated by the nation's weapons plants. The
TRUPACT-2 containers will be carried three at a time aboard special
trailers to WIPP.
   The NRC said in a statement that the government expects to ship
600 truckloads to WIPP each year for 25 years, with the trucks
watched by satellite.
   The desert repository has been built, but its 1988 opening was
postponed because of concerns about its safety, delays in getting
the land around the site withdrawn from public use and lack of
certification for the TRUPACT.
   Energy Secretary James Watkins has said the site won't open until
he is sure all the technical concerns are resolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 2052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Liver     08-30 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liver,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethical Rules Say Parent Can Donate Liver to Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors at the University of Chicago have proposed
that transplants in which only a piece of the liver is taken from a
living donor be limited in most cases to parents supplying organs to
their children.
   The idea, published in Thursday's New England Journal of
Medicine, was offered for discussion in hopes the medical profession
eventually will adopt such ethical guidelines.
   Doctors at the University of Chicago drew up the rules before
attempting their first transplant of a section of liver from a
living donor.
   Transplants involving whole or partial livers taken from the dead
are routine in many places. But because these organs are in scarce,
some doctors would like to begin transplanting parts of organs taken
from the living.
   Because the body has only one liver, the organ cannot be entirely
removed for transplant.
   The new surgery would remove one lobe of a healthy person's liver
and transplant it into an infant. The missing part of the donor's
liver eventually grows back, and in the baby, the piece of organ
grows along with the child.
   ``We believe that from the perspectives of both recipient and
donor, the benefits outweigh the risks and that it is ethically
appropriate to proceed with a trial of liver transplantation using a
parent as a living donor,'' wrote Dr. Peter A. Singer and colleagues.
   The guidelines resulted from a year-long series of seminars and
discussions.
   The doctors proposed that the donor should be the child's parent
or, in rare cases, a mature sibling or grandparent.
   They said that when the donor is related to the recipient, the
benefits of saving a life are most rewarding. Such transplants also
have the best chance of succeeding.
   A team led by Dr. Christoph Broelsch of the University of Chicago
surgeons hopes to perform the first such operation in the United
States this fall. The operation has already been done in Brazil.
   Doctors say that because of the shortage of organs from cadavers,
up to half of all babies who need new livers die while awaiting
transplants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0168 </DOCNO>
