<HEAD>Supreme Court Denied Stay of Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday denied a stay of
execution for Alton Waye, scheduled to become the eighth person to
die in Virginia's electric chair since the state reinstituted the
death penalty in 1977.
   By a 7-2 vote, the court rejected emergency requests to postpone
the electrocution, scheduled for 11 p.m. By the same margin, the
court refused Waye's request to have his case formally studied by
the justices.
   Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood Marshall, who oppose the
death penalty under all circumstances, voted to spare Waye.
   Earlier, Gov. Gerald L. Baliles denied clemency for Waye,
convicted of the 1977 rape and murder of a 61-year-old widow.
