<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Refugees     08-30 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Refugees,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Prepares For New Wave of East German Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials are preparing for a new wave
of East German refugees seeking to flee to the West from Hungary,
but denied on Wednesday that a deal was struck to permit a wholesale
exodus.
   Preparations went ahead to set up four tent camps in Bavaria
state to house an expected surge of East German refugees after Sept.
1.
   West German and Hungarian officials say many East German families
will have to decide whether to flee to the West or return home by
then because it marks the end of the school vacation in East Germany.
   The Stuttgarter Nachrichten newspaper said Austrian and West
German rail officials worked out plans for special trains to bring
refugees to West Germany.
   Chief government spokesman Hans Klein said the new refugee
facilities are being erected ``because the government must be
prepared for all possibilities. We have to take this date of Sept. 1
and the days thereafter seriously.''
   West German TV quoted Hungarian Interior Minister Istvan Horvath
as reiterating Hungary's intention not to return any East Germans
against their will and again appealing to Bonn and East Berlin to
work to solve the problem.
   Klein said officials estimate that from 150,000 to 200,000 East
Germans are on vacation in Hungary. Officials earlier speculated as
many as 20,000 could decide to stay in Hungary.
   West German news media reported that 15,000 East Germans would be
allowed to go the West from Hungary by the weekend, carrying newly
issued West German passports.
   A high-ranking government official in Bonn, speaking on condition
of anonymity, denied it and said issuing such passports would not
solve the problem.
   ``The new passports do not have a Hungarian entry visa in them
and thus could not be used to legally leave the country,'' he said.
   Klein said news reports saying that removal of the visa
requirement was imminent ``do not correspond to the facts and
possibilities.''
   In Vienna, an Austrian government source said the International
Red Cross is working on a plan to ferry at least 1,500 East Germans
from Hungary via Austria to West Germany in the next few days.
   West German officials said negotiations were continuing, but no
final arrangement had been concluded.
   At least 6,000 East Germans are thought to have used vacations in
Hungary to flee west to Austria since Budapest began dismantling
fortifications along the border in May.
   The flood of refugees has been fueled by the refusal of the
communist East German leadership to adopt economic and political
reforms similar to those under way in Poland and Hungary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
