<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0692 08-30 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Richardson Chosen to Head UN Operation in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Richardson comments, Sandinista
government reported opposed to him. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elliot L. Richardson, a former U.S.
attorney general with a long record of U.S. government service, will
lead the U.N. team that monitors Nicaraguan elections in February,
officials announced Wednesday.
   Richardson, 69, now is in private law practice in Washington,
said he had no opinions beforehand on the fairness of the elections,
but that he has had plenty of experience in hard-fought campaigns.
   ``I've been a candidate; I've been involved in elections, I once
even ran a recount in a gubernatorial election in Massachusetts many
years ago,'' he remarked in a telephone interview Wednesday night
with The Associated Press.
   A U.N. official, speaking privately, said Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government opposed Richardson's appointment and resisted
it for weeks.
   No one at Nicaragua's U.N. Mission was willing to comment on the
appointment.
   Richardson is best known for resigning as attorney general in
protest during the ``Saturday night massacre'' episode in the
Watergate scandal.
   He quit the night of Oct. 10, 1973, the same night President
Richard M. Nixon fired Watergate special prosecutor Archibald Cox.
   ``Well, I would like that to be remembered,'' Richardson quipped
on Wednesday.
   Richardson and a group of jurists and former U.S. officials
called the Commission on the Independence of Namibia just returned
from that country, where elections leading to independence from
South Africa are set for November.
   On Tuesday, commission members criticized South Africa's
procedures for the vote.
   U.N. officials said Wednesday that Richardson would visit
Nicaragua periodically to assess the situation for Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar, and would oversee the U.N. observer mission.
   Both the Sandinista government and the opposition in Nicaragua
asked the United Nations and Organization of American States to send
monitors.
   The first group of about 160 U.N. poll watchers already is in
Nicaragua. The OAS will send an equal number.
   Richardson had held Nixon administration posts as secretary of
health, education and welfare and defense secretary before being
named attorney general.
   He was ambassador to Britain in 1975-76 and secretary of commerce
in 1976-77 under President Gerald R. Ford. Richardson served
President Jimmy Carter in 1977-80 as a special ambassador and as
U.S. representative to the Third U.N. Conference on the Law of the
Sea.
   From 1980 until June, he was chairman of the U.N. Association of
the United States, a private, non-partisan group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
