<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina-Strike     08-30 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Strike,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tens of Thousands of Teachers Strike for Higher Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of teachers
began a 48-hour strike Wednesday to back demands for a pay raise
that the government says would lead to more inflation.
   ``In many areas, teachers are paid less then what unemployed
people will receive,'' from the government, said Maria Sanchez,
secretary-general of the 230,000-member Confederation of Argentine
Educators.
   Wages have not kept pace with inflation, she said, and are so low
that teachers in many provinces often cannot afford bus tickets to
get to work.
   Teachers receive $46 a month in base pay, and are demanding a
raise to $114.
   The government is trying to hold down wage increases to get a
halt inflation that in July soared by 197 percent. The projection
for August is 35 percent.
   Education Minister Antonio Salonia said a raise for teachers
would encourage other unions to make similar demands, and this
``would run the risk of returning to hyperinflation.'' Salonia said
striking teachers would be docked pay.
   Ms. Sanchez said 85 pecent of her federation went on strike
Wednesday. The goverment gave no estimate.
   Private schools, including those run by the Roman Catholic
Church, remained open, as did many public schools.
   The job action is the first nationwide strike since President
Carlos Menem of the Peronist Party took office July 8, and is seen
as a test in a growing clash of wills between the government and
organized labor.
   Bus drivers, train conductors, doctors in municipal hospitals and
public employees in several provinces all are demanding pay raises.
   The 3 million member General Labor Confederation has opposed
government concessions to businesses, such as a plan to allow
workers to be hired on a temporary basis with no right to severance
pay, and refused to rule out a general strike.
   In an editorial titled ``Changing Times,'' the English-language
newspaper Buenos Aires Herald commented Wednesday: ``By a supreme
irony, the government of a labor-based party seems to be on a
collision course with the trade unions.''
</TEXT>
