<FIRST>u a AM-PhoneStrike     08-30 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Strike,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Phone Strike Ends, NYNEX Last One Left</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan Bell agreed on a tentative contract for 12,800 telephone
workers Wednesday, allowing 37,000 Ameritech workers in five Midwest
states to head back to work and leaving NYNEX the last regional
phone company still on strike.
   Officials of NYNEX Corp., serving New York state and most of New
England, met with union negotiators Wednesday in their first talks
in two weeks.
   Ameritech's operators, repair crews and other union employees in
Michigan, Illinois, Indiana, Ohio and Wisconsin began returning to
work at noon following the agreement with Michigan Bell. Union
workers in the five states had said they would stay off the job
until settlements were reached in each state.
   Management employees had assumed the duties of striking workers,
but backlogs of service and installation requests developed in some
states, as well as some delays in placing directory assistance or
operator-assisted calls.
   The strike at Chicago-based Ameritech began Aug. 13, one week
after strikes began at three other ``Baby Bell'' regional telephone
companies, formed after the 1984 breakup of American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. The strikes had affected nearly 200,000 workers in 20
states.
   Bell Atlantic workers in six states and Washington, D.C., ended
their strike Monday after agreements were reached with
Communications Workers of America locals in Pennsylvania and
Delaware. A tentative contract settlement also has been reached at
Pacific Telesis, which serves California and Nevada.
   But 60,000 workers remained on strike against NYNEX. Since the
strike began Aug. 6, the company and the union had met formally only
twice before.
   Talks resumed with the CWA, representing most of the striking
workers in New York, and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, representing New England Telephone workers. Both sides
agreed to continue Thursday.
   Myles Calvey of IBEW Local 222 in Quincy, Mass., said issues
central to Wednesday's talks with his union in Boston were health
benefits and the company's fixed liablility medical expense plan,
although wages, job safety and job security were also at issue.
   The original NYNEX proposal called for workers to contribute
$10.20 a week for health insurance. NYNEX reduced that Wednesday to
$4.50, Calvey said
   About 90 activists _ roughly half of them striking New England
Telephone workers _ marched Wednesday near the summer White House at
Kennebunkport, Maine, to urge President Bush to institute national
health care.
   ``George Bush, it ain't fair. We don't have no health care,''
chanted the marchers, who were not allowed onto the property of the
Shawmut Inn, where Bush attended a luncheon.
   The Michigan pact includes changes in employee scheduling rules
that give the company greater flexibility and an improved employee
profit-sharing plan, Mark Doman, chairman of Michigan Bell's
bargaining committee, said at a news conference.
   The three-year pact also includes wage increases and improved
health benefits, said Mike Handley, chairman of the CWA bargaining
committee, who appeared with Doman. The two wouldn't discuss details.
   Late Tuesday, Indiana Bell and the CWA announced a tentative
accord on a new three-year pact covering 4,200 striking workers.
Tentative settlements were reached over the weekend with Ohio Bell
and Wisconsin Bell, and on Monday with Illinois Bell.
   New Jersey Bell signed a tentative agreement Monday with CWA, but
has no agreement with about 9,200 workers represented by the IBEW.
The last talks were Tuesday and no new talks are scheduled.
</TEXT>
