<HEAD>Family of Six Killed by Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fast, intense fire killed six members of a
family Wednesday, including two children whose bodies were found
only five feet from the front door, authorities said.
   The 2{-story house was engulfed in flames when firefighters
arrived after a 1:15 a.m. alarm, said Battalian Chief Frank Henry.
The fire spread to an adjacent house and two behind it, causing an
estiamted $100,000 damage in the Northside neighborhood, fire
department officers said.
   Relatives identified the victims as Wilbert Crowell, 47; his
wife, Theresa, 27; her three children, Tina Sharpe, 10, Hope
Lawrence, 5, and Bo Lawrence, 4; and the husband's mother, Sylvia
Thompson, 72.
   ``A neighbor came up and said she heard people inside screaming
but there was nothing she could do,'' said police Lt. Richard Dwyer.
   ``When I got out of my car about 100 feet away I could feel the
heat,'' he said. ``There was no way anybody could get near the
building.''
   Acting fire Chief Robert Kolenda said it was not immediately
known how the fire began or in what part of the home. Kolenda said
he saw no sign that the house was equipped with smoke detectors.
   The two youngest children were found on the first floor near the
door, the man and a woman were at the top of the stairs, the
10-year-old was on the stairwell to the third floor and the other
woman was in a second-floor bedroom, Kolenda said.
