<FIRST>u a AM-MaritalSodomy 1stLd-Writethru a0657 08-30 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marital Sodomy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0657,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Jailed for Violating Sodomy Law Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with comments at news conference;
picking up 5th graf: `Moseley was ...; note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who spent 18 months behind bars for
having oral sex with his wife was freed Wednesday by a judge who
said prosecutors would have to come up with a better reason for
putting him in prison.
   James D. Moseley, a 35-year-old carpenter believed to be the
first man convicted under Georgia's 156-year-old sodomy law for
conduct between marriage partners, was released from the Metro
Correctional Institution.
   Moseley, who had been sentenced to five years in prison, waved to
waiting reporters as he left in a private car.
   ``Sure, I'm bitter,'' he said later at a news conference at the
headquarters of the Georgia chapter of the American Civil Liberties
Union. But he said faith in humanity kept his spirits up.
   ``I knew someone would see this thing as it really was,'' he said.
   Moseley said the first thing he would do is contact the
carpenters' union about a job. He said he hoped to see his sons,
although he does not have visitation rights.
   He said a lengthy domestic dispute resulted in his now-former
wife claiming falsely that he used force to have sex with her. ``I
only did what she wanted me to do, and then she used it against me
to get custody of the kids,'' Moseley said.
   Moseley was charged with rape, aggravated oral sodomy and
aggravated anal sodomy over two encounters with Bette Roberts, his
common-law wife of four years. Aggravated sodomy constitutes oral or
anal sex without consent.
   Moseley was acquitted of those charges, but a jury found him
guilty of sodomy without aggravation, or oral or anal sex with
consent, because he admitted on the stand that he had had oral sex
with Ms. Roberts.
   Sodomy, even between a consenting husband and wife, is a felony
in Georgia.
   On Wednesday, Superior Court Judge Robert Castellani ordered
Moseley freed, noting that he was found guilty ``only of an act
involving an act between two married adults.''
   He said Moseley must be freed on his own recognizance unless the
state could find a reason to hold him.
   Clive Stafford Smith, an American Civil Liberties Union lawyer,
told the judge that the prosecutors should disqualify themselves if
they ever had engaged in oral sex. ``We cannot have a `do as I say
not as I do' syndrome,'' he argued.
   The judge rejected the motion without comment.
   Stafford Smith also argued that the Georgia law violates
constitutional rights to privacy.
   But Mary Beth Westmoreland, a senior assistant attorney general
representing the state, said privacy was not at issue. ``It's not a
matter of police peeking in windows. That's not what is before this
court,'' she said.
   She said the state became involved because Ms. Roberts complained
to authorities. The couple, who had two children, have since
divorced.
</TEXT>
