<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina-Nazi     08-30 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Nazi,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentina Upholds Extraditing Schwammberger as Nazi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PLATA, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court ruled Wednesday that Josef
Schwammberger may be extradited to West Germany to face charges that
as a Nazi camp commander he personally killed dozens of people at
forced labor camps in World War II.
   However, the 77-year-old Schwammberger may appeal the ruling of
the federal appeals court to the Supreme Court and thus stave off
immediate extradition to Stuttgart, West Germany.
   ``Frankly, Schwammberger is not a young man ... We're concerned
that the final appeal not take as long'' as the initial proceedings,
said Rabbi Marvin Hier, director of the Los Angeles branch of the
Simon Wiesenthal Center for Holocaust Studies.
   Schwammberger was discovered living in Argentina in November 1987
and has been held in jail ever since in La Plata, 30 miles south of
Buenos Aires.
   He is being kept in a hospital at the penal center because of his
age and ill health, the government news agency Telam reported.
   A Stuttgart court issued an order for Schwammberger's arrest in
1973. He is accused of being responsible for the deaths of at least
5,000 people, mostly Jews, at two labor camps he commanded in
occupied Poland.
   ``We have witnesses that say he threw men, women and children
alive into bonfires,'' said Hier. ``He smashed children into walls
and then set dogs on them to tear them apart.''
   Defense attorneys have asked Argentine authorities to deny the
extradition request, or to hold any trial in Argentina. They have
five days to appeal to the Supreme Court.
   Hier said the French army arrested Schwammberger in 1945, but he
escaped on Jan. 1, 1948. He came to Argentina in 1949, was
naturalized as a citizen in 1953 and was granted full citizenship in
1965.
   Argentine officials said he lived in La Plata and worked for a
chemical company for many years.
</TEXT>
