<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--ColombianDealer     08-30 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Colombian Dealer,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Dealer Charged With Illegal Entry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian who was twice convicted of
cocaine charges and deported from the United States has been
arrested in San Francisco and charged with illegal re-entry,
authorities said Wednesday.
   If convicted, Francisco Portocarrero could be sentenced to 15
years in prison and fined $250,000 under new federal laws stiffening
punishment for deported drug traffickers who re-enter the country
illegally, said U.S. Attorney Joseph Russoniello.
   He said Portocarrero was convicted in San Francisco in 1983 of
importing and possessing with intent to distribute 340 pounds of
cocaine. He was sentenced to prison for two years and then deported,
Russoniello said.
   Portocarrero returned to the United States and was deported again
in 1985 after being convicted in Louisiana of possessing 18 pounds
of cocaine, Russoniello said.
   He said U.S. immigration agents arrested Portocarrero Aug. 16 in
a San Francisco tavern. He was indicted by a federal grand jury
Wednesday.
