<SECOND>AM-Princess Anne, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0735,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Princess Anne Separating From Husband, His Father Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with palace statement to be made
Thursday morning; picks up 7th pvs, `Anne, 39...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSICA BALDWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Anne, the only daughter of Queen Elizabeth
II, and husband Mark Phillips are separating, his father said
Wednesday. A television report said they will divorce.
   A Buckingham Palace press officer refused to comment on the
reports but said a palace announcement would be issued Thursday
morning.
   Maj. Peter Phillips in a statement said: ``For the moment they
are going to live separately. They are not going to divorce but will
be separating.''
   It added: ``They will not be living far away from each other.
Princess Anne will remain at Gatcombe (Park, the family home in
western England) and Mark will be moving about two miles away.'' The
statement said this would happen ``in the near future.''
   Sky Television said the palace would issue a statement saying the
couple, who have been married 15 years and have two children, would
divorce.
   Anne, 39, was attending an International Olympic Committee
meeting in Puerto Rico Wednesday. Her 40-year-old husband, an
ex-Army captain, was at home at Gatcombe Park.
   The princess, who is the head of the International Equestrian
Federation, was in private meetings in San Juan all day. She was
rarely seen and two bodyguards kept reporters at bay at all times.
   Telephone calls to her room at the Caribe Hilton hotel were
automatically deflected to switchboard operators, who would not
allow calls through.
   Rumors of trouble in the marriage have circulated since 1981, and
in recent years the princess and her husband have spent periods of
up to six months apart.
   She has become one of the busiest members of the royal family as
president of the Save the Children Fund, a charity that works on
behalf of poor children around the world. Her husband has traveled
widely for business and equestrian interests.
   Speculation that their marriage was in trouble arose most
recently in April after letters written to Anne by an aide to the
queen were stolen and sent to the tabloid The Sun.
   The Sun, Britain's biggest circulation newspaper, did not
disclose the content of the four letters and said it gave them to
police.
   Buckingham Palace then identified Timothy Laurence, a 35-year-old
bachelor, as the writer in a bid to stop intense news media
speculation.
   Phillips told reporters at that time that his marriage was ``fine
and happy.''
   On Aug. 23, the queen personally awarded Laurence the Royal
Victorian Order as he left her personal service after three years as
her aide to take command of a frigate. The citation said the order
was awarded for ``extraordinary, important or personal services to
the sovereign or the royal family.''
   Anne's aunt, Princess Margaret, the queen's only sister, was
divorced in 1978 from Lord Snowdon, who has since remarried.
   Anne is sixth in line to the throne.
</TEXT>
