<HEAD>Empty Fuel Tank Falls from Fighter Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REHOBOTH BEACH, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An empty 600-gallon fuel tank fell
from a fighter jet north of a popular beach resort Wednesday,
authorities said.
   There were no injuries or property damage when the 15-foot,
500-pound tank dropped from an F-4 Phantom jet near Rehoboth Beach,
said Capt. Walter Thorp, a Dover Air Force Base spokesman.
   State police said the tank was found in an empty field about half
a mile north of the resort.
   Three fighters, assigned to the Air National Guard's Washington,
D.C.-based 113th Tactical Fighter Wing, took off earlier from
Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland on a training missing, the Air
Force said.
   Thorp said he did not know how fast nor how low the jets were
flying, but he said they were following a certified training route.
The tank was carried directly under the fuselage at the center of
the jet, Thorp said.
   The Air Force planned to recover the tank on Thursday, Thorp said.
