<DOCNO> AP890830-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 2215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Lutherans     08-30 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lutherans,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Ends First Assembly, Passing Socially Oriented Resolutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly merged Lutheran denomination ended
its first national assembly Wednesday with resolutions on social and
political concerns, including South Africa, striking coal miners and
hunger.
   In addition to resolutions urging U.S. economic sanctions against
South Africa and backing the Appalachian miners, delegates to the
Evangelical Church in America meeting approved a measure accusing
Israel of abusing Palestinians.
   The nation's fourth-largest Protestant denomination also urged
participation in a ``Burger-A-Month'' campaign, in which each person
gives $2 a month _ the approximate cost of a hamburger _ to
alleviate world hunger.
   About 1,040, delegates representing 5.3 million U.S. Lutherans
expressed special support for small rural and urban congregations on
the eighth and final day of their meeting in this Chicago suburb.
   In a ``throwaway society'' where ``new is valued more than old
and bigger is often seen as better,'' rural communities are in
economic crisis and inner cities suffer ``blight, poverty'' and
flight of businesses, the resolution said.
   The assembly called for vigorous U.S. efforts to determine the
fate of U.S. prisoners of war and those missing in action in
Vietnam, and encouraged Lutherans to be alert to advances in science
and technology.
   ``We must learn'' from science, said the Rev. Larry Lenning of
Independence, Iowa.
   Regarding the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, the assembly said
achieving peace required ending abuses against Palestinians, but
also stressed security for the Jewish state and confessed past
``sinful complicity as Lutherans'' against Jews.
   The miners backed by the Lutherans have been on strike against
Pittston Coal Group since April 5.
   The assembly was the first since the January 1988 merger of the
Lutheran Church in America, the American Lutheran Church and the
Association of Evangelical Lutheran Churches.
   ``It demonstrated that it is right for us to be together. There
was 100 percent enthusiasim, a marvelous identification of us as a
church,'' Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom of Chicago, president of the
denomination, told a post-meeting news conference.
   Chilstrom said the assembly's decision to join the major
Chrisitian ecumenical bodies, the World Council of Churches and the
National Council of Churches, were ``signs of great maturity.''
   He said he was impressed by the diversity of the delegates. In
addition to whites, there were blacks, Hispanics, Asian-Americans
and American Indians. Nearly half the delegates were women.
   Chilstrom noted that the mainly white church was established with
a mandate to include people of different cultures. ``We've got a
long way to go, but we're on the way,'' he said.
   Asked about the church's budget crunch, he predicted a turnaround
in congregational contributions because of the ``Mission 90''
program adopted here.
   ``It takes a long time to turn around a ship as big as the ELCA,
but it's going to turn around,'' Chilstrom said.
   ``Mission 90,'' a new long-range program for the 1990s,
emphasizes Bible teaching, evangelism, tithing and work for peace,
justice, and the environment.
   Following one of the most heated debates of the assembly, the
delegates earlier set a Sept. 1, 1991, deadline for the church
pension board to sell all shares in companies doing business in
South Africa. Those investments are valued at $84.9 million.
   ``Seting a date to be completely divested could be a problem for
the Board of Pensions,'' Chilstrom said. However, he said all
delegates agreed that apartheid, South Africa's racial system of
government, must be dismantled.
   Another divisive issue was abortion. The assembly on Monday
approved a resolution some interpreted as pro-choice, then
reconsidered and decided to remain neutral on abortion pending a
two-year study. The next assembly is in 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
