<FIRST>r a AM-PavarottiBanned     08-30 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pavarotti Banned,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singer Pavarotti Cancels in Chicago; Told He's No Longer Welcome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenor Luciano Pavarotti cancelled this season's
appearance with the Lyric Opera of Chicago, and was told in return
Wednesday that he's no longer welcome to perform with the company.
   The famed singer's manager, Herbert Breslin, told the Lyric that
a persistent inflammation of Pavarotti's sciatic nerve prevents him
from performing in a live opera at this time, the company said in a
news release.
   The Lyric, which is entering its 35th anniversary season with the
house 99 percent sold out, said the singer cancelled 26 of the 41
performances he was under contract to do for the company this decade.
   ``That's quite a record!'' said Lyric General Director Ardis
Krainik. ``Lyric Opera is now unwilling to take the risk of one more
cancellation by Mr. Pavarotti,'' she said.
   Miss Krainik said the Lyric is not interested in considering any
other future engagements with Pavarotti, and has withdrawn from
negotiations for performances in 1991.
   She said the tenor has had a growing reputation for cancellations.
   In May with the Pittsburgh Opera, Pavarotti walked off the stage
when his voice cracked during the third act of Puccini's ``Tosca.''
   Asked if there was any reason to think his cancellation in
Chicago was motivated by something other than health, Miss Krainik
said, ``That's not the point.The point is, he cancelled.''
   She said she felt that with his record of cancellations, she had
no choice but to sever ties with the singer, who first performed
with the Lyric in 1973.
   Breslin said he and Pavarotti have the greatest respect for the
Lyric and Miss Krainik. But the manager said he believes she is
acting ``a little bit irrational,'' particularly since Pavarotti has
been the greatest fund raiser in the Lyric's history.
   ``I think she gets the impression that he is doing this out of
some kind of spite for the Lyric Opera of Chicago, which is
absolutely wrong,'' Breslin said.
   Pavarotti had been scheduled to perform in ``Tosca'' on six dates
in late September and early October.
   Neither the Lyric nor Breslin would discuss the singer's fees.
</TEXT>
