<DOCNO> AP890830-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 2246EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BarkerLawsuit     08-30 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barker Lawsuit,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Game Show Host Bob Barker Sued for Libel by American Humane Association</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE M. PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Humane Association filed a $10
million libel lawsuit Wednesday against game show host and animal
rights activist Bob Barker and others.
   The lawsuit contends that Barker and animal rights organizations
have conducted a two-year ``vendetta'' against the association and
its West Coast regional director, Betty Denny Smith, said
association attorney Barry Langberg. Ms. Smith also is a plaintiff
in the lawsuit, filed in Superior Court.
   ``From the standpoint from the American Humane Association and
Betty Denny Smith this was a very reluctant suit,'' said Langberg.
``They did not want to sue Barker. They want to devote their
energies to protecting animals.''
   The lawsuit accuses Barker, the United Activists for Animal
Rights and its executive director, Nancy Burnet, of libel, slander,
trade libel, interference with prospective business relations,
conspiracy and false-light invasion of privacy, said Langberg.
   ``I have no legal background but I believe that to be sued for
these things the statements I made had to be untrue. And of course,
they were not,'' Barker said in response to the lawsuit.
   Telephone calls seeking comment from Ms. Burnet and the United
Activists were met with repeated busy signals.
   A separate claim was filed against the city and Department of
Animal Regulation head Robert I. Rush for allegedly assisting Barker
in the campaign, Langberg said.
   ``I haven't even seen it,'' said Rush, ``but the conduct of this
office in the past has been beyond reproach and it is currently
beyond reproach. The claim will be discussed with the city attorney
and a response will be made.''
   Langberg said the lawsuit charges that Barker, on radio, accused
Ms. Smith and the association of condoning animal cruelty. The
association was founded in 1877 for the protection of animals and
children, and the West Coast regional office has been active in
protecting animals used in the entertainment industry.
   Barker, longtime host of the television game show ``The Price Is
Right,'' has been involved with animal rights for many years and in
1987 quit after 19 years as host of the Miss USA Pageant because
contestants wore fur coats.
   He was the 1987 winner of the highest award given by directors of
the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.
   ``I have never been sued but I'm sure it's a very unpleasant
experience. It has to be expensive and it has to be
time-consuming,'' Barker said. ``But if this suit results in the
American public becoming more aware of the extent of animal cruelty
in entertainment then the suit will have served a very valuable
purpose and it will be well worth the money and the time it costs
me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
