<FIRST>u i AM-Haiti-PeaceCorps     08-30 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti-Peace Corps,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Corps To Renew Haitian Mission</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The Peace Corps has decided to send
volunteers to Haiti, U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Susan Clyde said
Wednesday, nearly two years after it suspended its mission here due
to widespread violence.
   Fifteen volunteers will arrive in January, and 15 more in June,
she said. They will work in health, education, and farm programs,
she said.
   Peace Corps director Paul Coverdell said in Washington on
Wednesday he believed the political situation in Haiti had improved.
``There is a stable government now,'' he said.
   Coverdell said the embassy judged security was satisfactory for
foreign nationals in the country.
   For months, Haiti has been plagued by murders and burglaries
while police have done little to maintain security.
   The Peace Corps, operating in 65 countries, suspended its program
to Haiti in December 1987, shortly after violently aborted
presidential elections in which at least 34 voters were massacred at
the polls by thugs protected by soldiers. Nineteen Peace Corps
volunteers were withdrawn.
   Richard Melton, assistant undersecretary of state for Caribbean
affairs, last month expressed U.S. government satisfaction with
progress in democratization made by ruler Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril.
   Also Wednesday, the United States and Haiti signed a $300,000
anti-drug trafficking aid agreement. The funds will be used to equip
the Haitian government with surveillance equipment to help it combat
drug smuggling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
