<HEAD>Report: SC Reactor to Restart in July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy will recommend
restarting the Savannah River tritium-producing reactor in July
1990, The Washington Post reported in its Thursday editions.
   The report, quoting unnamed government sources, said the decision
to restart the reactor was made after a lengthy safety and technical
review. The reactor in Aiken, S.C., was closed for safety reasons a
year ago.
   Tritium, a gas, is used to boost a weapon's explosive force.
   The timetable is later than the target previously set by the
Energy Department, but Energy Secretary James D. Watkins plans to
tell President Bush and other members of the National Security
Council next week that the delay will not threaten national security.
