<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Libya     08-30 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Libya,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua's Ortega Going To Libya For Gadhafi Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ESQUIPULAS, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said
Wednesday he will go to Libya to take part in ceremonies this week
marking 20 years of power for the leader of that radical North
African Arab country, Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   Ortega made the announcement in this city 60 miles north of the
capital at a ceremony handing over 230 property deeds to 508 peasant
families.
   ``We are willing to have good relations with Bush and also with
Gadhafi,'' Ortega said. He said that if the U.S. president invited
him to Washington, ``I would go to the United States to meet with
Bush.''
   Ortega said he would proceed from the Saturday ceremonies in
Libya to Belgrade, Yugoslavia to take part in the four-day summit of
non-aligned nations, which ends Monday.
   The president also said that to date his government has freed
from prison 283 peasants who were accused of supporting the rebels,
known as Contras.
   ``There are still 1,129 counterrevolutionaries in prison who were
counted by the International Red Cross Committee'' last week, Ortega
said. The president emphasized that the government will free the
others, but did not say when.
   Ortega said the U.S.-backed Contras, 11,000 of whom are in camps
in Honduras, have kidnapped 7,478 people. He demanded that ``the
counterrevolutionaries hand over the kidnap victims'' who are still
alive.
   He said that when the Contras hand over their arms ``we are
willing to receive them like brothers.'' The government has
announced a general amnesty for Contras who return to participate in
Nicaraguan life.
   ``But those who do not accept the friendly hand we are extending,
we will give them our fists until we crush them.''
   In a statement in Managua on Wednesday, the Defense Ministry said
two Sandinista soldiers were killed when rebels blew up a truck
carrying soldiers in the town of Mongallo near the Caribbean coast
on Tuesday.
   No claim of responsibility came from rebels.
   Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government has promised democratic
reforms and set an election for Feb. 25 in accordance with an
agreement signed by Central American presidents on Aug. 7 in Tela,
Honduras.
   The accord called for disbanding the Contras by Dec. 8 with a
U.N. team to observe the process.
</TEXT>
