<FIRST>r a AM-US-JapanVisit     08-30 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan Visit,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Arrives in U.S. on 10-Day Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu opened
his first official U.S. visit Wednesday with an impromptu news
conference in which he said he will be discussing trade issues this
week with President Bush.
   Kaifu turned what was supposed to be a 10-minute stop at the
Japanese Cultural Center into a half-hour lunch visit at which he
fielded questions from reporters.
   Asked about the purpose of his visit, Kaifu said: ``I want to
make rock-solid the relationship between Japan and the United
States.''
   Another questioner raised the issue of Japan's $55 billion annual
trade surplus with the United States.
   ``I plan to talk about this with the president of the United
States,'' Kaifu said through an interpreter. ``We will be continuing
the dialogue.''
   Because Kaifu is a relatively little-known political figure,
there have been suggestions that his trip is primarily a
get-acquainted visit that will give him some international exposure
and divert attention from influence-peddling scandals that have
shaken his party.
   A senior Foreign Ministry official in Japan who briefed reporters
before the trip said that Kaifu is not bringing major trade or
diplomatic initiatives.
   Kaifu, 58, took office on Aug. 9 after the resignation of Prime
Minister Sosuke Uno, whose money-for-sex affairs with geisha and
cabaret hostesses contributed to a major defeat for the Liberal
Democratic Party in elections in the upper house of parliament last
month.
   Kaifu planned to meet with Bush Friday in Washington, D.C., and
also make stops in Boston, Mexico City and Canada during his 10-day
trip with his wife, Sachiyo.
   Kaifu told the crowd at the cultural center he had fond memories
of his first visit to the United States 27 years ago, when he rented
a car and drove along the Pacific Coast Highway.
   Kaifu's itinerary was to take him Thursday to Washington,
Saturday to Boston, Monday to Mexico City, Wednesday to Ottawa and
Friday to Vancouver, British Columbia.
</TEXT>
