   Consumer advocates and physicians say there's
no reason to doubt the safety and effectiveness of most generic
drugs, and consumers appear to be heeding that advice.
   ``I don't think there's panic in the streets. I think they're
concerned,'' said Harold Cohen, editor of the trade publication Drug
Store News-Inside Pharmacy, referring to drug consumers. Cohen, who
has been visiting pharmacies in St. Louis, Phoenix and Washington
D.C. for the past week, said Monday he saw few customers switching
from a generic to a brand-name drug.
   Disclosures of fraud and corruption in the Food and Drug
Administration's generic drug division have tainted the agency's
reputation and cast doubts on the industry as well as the safety and
efficacy of generic medicines.
