<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv01   08-30 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 01,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Sept. 1, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With AIDS appearing in many countries, the
National Council of Churches is expanding efforts to inform
missionaries about the virus and how to reduce risks of contracting
it.
   Member denominations are being provided with educational
materials, special sterilized injection kits and other resources for
missionaries as they are sent to their fields.
   ``The risk of AIDS is real for missionaries serving in infected
areas, but not very high if a person takes precautions,'' says Dr.
John Frame, NCC consultant on health affairs.
   Of 40,000 American Protestant missionaries serving overseas, six
are known to have been infected with the AIDS virus, four of them
stationed in Africa and two in the Caribbean.
   Another missionary, a hemophiliac infected through a transfusion,
died of AIDS in Australia, Frame says.
   ``The risk to missionaries is almost certainly related to
profession (medical) or events that cannot be predicted, such as
accident or complications in pregnancy requiring blood
transfusions,'' he says.
   ``There is also the risk of getting an injection from
inadequately sterilized equipment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lilly Endowment has made a $325,000 grant
to Reform Judaism's Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of
Religion and to Conservative Judaism's Jewish Theological Seminary
of America as part of a project to improve religious leadership
among American rabbis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virgil C. Dechant, supreme knight of the
Knights of Columbus, urges Catholic lay people to be more supportive
of their bishops.
   In the 1.5-million-member Catholic organization's monthly
magazine, Columbia, Dechant writes that skepticism and unbelief are
``especially acute'' and that bishops ``need our support and
collaboration.
   ``In this age of widespread unbelief, evangelization calls for
the best efforts of us all.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an history-making ecumenical step, the
recent general assembly of the Christian Church (Disciples of
Christ) elected a Roman Catholic priest, Monsignor Philip Morris, as
a member of the 1.1-million-member denomination's governing board.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A meeting of the central committee of the World
Council of Churches accepted a new member, the Kiribati Protestant
Church. It has 31,000 members, about half the population of the 33
South Pacific islands making up republic of Kiribati.
   The admission brought to 307 the number of the council's
Protestant and Eastern Orthodox member denominations. Their
memberships total more than 400 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A professor at Southern Baptist Union
University has resigned in a conflict with the administration over
his teaching that a saved, believing Christian can fall into
unbelief and be lost.
   The university's administration had cut teaching duties and
salary of the Rev. Clyde Tilley, a religion and philosophy professor
at the school for a quarter century, because of his views on the
issue.
   Tilley says the case was ``part and parcel of the broader
conflict'' among Southern Baptists whose denominational offices have
become dominated by a fundamentalist wing.
   Hyran Barefoot, the university's president, says Tilley didn't
hold to the Baptist doctrine of ``eternal security'' of the
believer, that a person once saved is always saved.
   Tilley says he agrees that ``all believers are eternally
secure,'' but that people can revert into unbelief and deliberately
renounce salvation. He says ``this view is compatible with the
eternal security of the believer, since the apostate would no longer
be a believer.''
   A faculty affairs committee recommended that Tilley be retained
in his regular post at the same pay, but this was not accepted by
the school's trustees, mostly appointed by the denomination's
fundamentalist leaders.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, Sept. 1</NOTE>
