<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-Homeroon Adv01-03   08-30 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-Homeroon, Adv 01-03,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>ABC's `Homeroom' Borrows Heavily, Adds Nothing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``Homeroom'' borrows heavily from other
schoolroom comedies but adds nothing new, other than making its
protagonist black.
   This is a lot of ``Welcome Back, Kotter,'' only not as funny, and
a little ``Head of the Class.'' Just to make sure no originality
sneaks in, the plot of the pilot is heavily inspired by the movie
``Stand and Deliver.''
   Darryl Sivad, a likable sort, stars as Darryl Hudson, who gave up
a successful advertising career to teach inner-city fourth-graders.
Penny Johnson plays Vicki, Darryl's loving wife, who is studying to
become a doctor.
   Conflict is provided Hudson's father, Phil, who is also their
landlord. He is played by the fine Bill Cobbs (``The `Slap' Maxwell
Story''), who thinks his son-in-law has taken leave of his senses to
give up lucrative jingle-writing to try to teach math to juvenile
delinquents.
   ``Homeroom'' is on Sunday, facing tough competition from CBS'
``Murder, She Wrote'' and NBC sitcoms.
   Executive producer and creator Gary Gilbert was a producer-writer
on ``Head of the Class,'' but with laugh lines like, ``Sue me!''
``Homeroom'' flunks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
