<DOCNO> AP890830-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 2140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-FamilyMatters Adv01-03   08-30 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-Family Matters, Adv 01-03,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Family Matters' Doesn't</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Telma is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The producers of the uninspired but
inoffensive sitcom ``The Hogan Family'' on NBC have a new uninspired
but inoffensive sitcom on ABC. ``Family Matters'' is spun off the
elevator operator from ``Perfect Strangers.''
   It is paired on Friday night with Thomas L. Miller and Robert L.
Boyett's other sitcom, the uninspired but inoffensive ``Full House.''
   Do we detect a trend here?
   ``Family Matters'' centers on wise-cracking Harriette Winslow
(JoMarie Payton-France) and her husband, Carl (Reginald VelJohnson).
He is cop who is none too pleased when his wise-cracking mother
(Rosetta Le Noire) comes to live with the already extended family.
   The others include Harriette's sister, Rachel (Telma Hopkins), a
would-be novelist with an infant son; and the Winslows' two
teen-agers and younger daughter.
   The pilot involves a controversy about teen-age Edward's curfew
and Grandma's attempts to impose her rule on the household, with
predictable results.
   VelJohnson _ he played the sympathetic cop who talked to Bruce
Willis throughout ``Die Hard'' _ is no Cosby, but he's a strong
father figure. Beyond that, ``Family Matters'' doesn't.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
