<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 2140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-TeddyZ Adv01-03   08-30 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-Teddy Z, Adv 01-03,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Famous Teddy Z' Hits Heights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The best new comedy of the season is CBS'
``The Famous Teddy Z,'' a fortuitous pairing of producer Hugh Wilson
(``Frank's Place'') and teen-film star Jon Cryer (``Pretty in
Pink'').
   Cryer plays Teddy Zakalokis, a mailroom clerk in the huge
Unlimited Talent Agency who is suddenly thrust into the thick of
show business. When he is sent on a gofer assignment, picking up an
eccentric, Brando-like star at the airport, he winds up punching out
the actor, impressing the guy so much he makes Teddy his agent.
   In-jokes abound, and viewers will delight at being in on them.
   Like Wilson's other comedies (he also did ``WKRP in
Cincinnati''), the supporting characters are as well drawn as the
lead.
   At a television critics meeting this summer, the critics were
going around quoting Al Floss (Alex Rocco), Wilson's quintessential
big-time agent. Floss to secretary: ``What are you, a statue? Screen
the people who come in here!''
   ``Teddy Z'' is well-placed on Monday between ``Murphy Brown'' and
``Designing Women.''
   The only time the comedy drags is when Teddy goes home to his
little Greek ``granny'' and younger brother, Ari. But future plots
sound promising. Teddy gets a new client, a monkey who has been
bounced from a hit network sitcom.
   ``Teddy Z'' is sophisticated fun and everybody in it deserves to
be famous.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
