<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 2141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-PeopleNextDoor Adv01-03   08-30 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-People Next Door, Adv 01-03,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Expect `People Next Door' to Move Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The weak link in CBS' Monday comedy lineup is
the new ``The People Next Door,'' a rare example of too much of a
mediocre thing.
   This special-effects sitcom is about a cartoonist named Walter
Kellogg (Jeffrey Jones) whose imagination becomes reality, producing
visions of talking moose, buzzing airplanes and giant green monsters
other people can see, too.
   There's also a complex sitcom family who are as unfunny as
Walter's creations are weird.
   Walter is about to wed Abigail (Mary Gross) and has moved into
her small-town home where she lives with her crotchety sister
(Christina Pickles), their mother's ashes and Abigail's psychiatry
practice.
   There's more. Walter has two children, a teen-age son and a
daughter, whose alleged overbite supplies most of the attempted
laugh lines in the pilot.
   There are some cute moments in ``People Next Door.'' Steve Allen
does a cameo as one of Walter's imaginings, arriving with grand
piano to croon ``Imagination Is Funny.'' And Geraldo Rivera pops up
on a TV screen, intoning a promo for a show on ``Men with overactive
imaginations _ and the women who love them.'' Walter then envisions
the set exploding.
   The gimmickry can't long carry an unfunny sitcom _ hey, didn't
somebody say the same thing when ``ALF'' premiered? Nevertheless,
expect ``The People Next Door'' to be moving soon.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890830-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 2141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-LifeGoesOn Adv01-03   08-30 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-Life Goes On, Adv 01-03,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>ABC's `Life Goes On' Realistic, Funny Family Drama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``Life Goes On'' is the best family
drama since ``thirtysomething,'' though its style is of the more
traditional ``Family.''
   The title comes from the Beatles song, ``Obla-di, Obla-da,'' and
is the reigning philosophy of the Thachers, a middle-class family
struggling to make ends meet.
   The show is getting a lot of attention because one of its cast
members is Christopher Burke, an actor with Down's syndrome who
plays teen-age son Corky.
   Much of the pilot plot revolves around Corky's challenge, to
``mainstream'' with kids at a regular school, including his younger
sister.
   Patti LuPone (``Evita'') is a surprise as TV mom Libby Thacher,
but she is well cast, as is Bill Smitrovich (``Crime Story'') who
plays her husband, Drew.
   Kellie Martin plays Becca, a perpetually embarrassed
eighth-grader apalled at having to attend junior high school with
her brother. Monique Lanier plays Paige, Drew's daughter from a
previous marriage. She has broken up with her boyfriend and been
forced to move back home.
   The pilot is funny and poignant, nicely written by executive
producer Michael Braverman. In the pilot, Drew is trying to come up
with the money to buy into a construction company. It would help a
lot if he could depend on the extra $5,000 a year the family will
save on Corky's tuition _ IF Corky can make it in a regular, public
junior high school.
   Meanwhile, Libby is facing her 40th birthday and Paige is trying
to figure what she's doing with her life, while Becca learns that
Corky might not be such a bad addition to the social whirl at school
when he immediately befriends the football star.
   ``Life Goes On'' goes into a tough Sunday time period, opposite
CBS' ``60 Minutes.'' Still, that means ABC isn't expecting its
ratings to go through the roof, so it might get to stay around for a
while. And it will get a head start when the pilot is aired a second
time after the hit ``Roseanne.''
   This is a nice show with a lot of heart that deserves to go on
and on.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
