<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-Wolf Adv01-03   08-30 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-Wolf, Adv 01-03,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Wolf' Whimpers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's nothing wrong with CBS' new crime
drama ``Wolf,'' but there's nothing particularly right about it,
either.
   It's ``Rockford Files'' without the humor, ``Wiseguy'' without
the offbeatness, ``Miami Vice'' without the style.
   Jack Scalia plays an Italian-American former cop who was busted
from the force after he was framed. He reunites with his old-country
father, Sal (Joseph Sirola), and buys a fishing boat. A chance to
work as a private eye gives him the opportunity to clear his name.
   The pilot is competent but there's no compelling reason to watch
``Wolf,'' except for the San Francisco setting.
   The series probably won't be around long. It has drawn a Tuesday
time period opposite NBC's ``In the Heat of the Night'' and ABC's
hit ``Roseanne.''
   Expect ``Wolf'' to whimper off soon into the Nielsen woods.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
