<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv03   08-30 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 03,0879</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Another Push Begins to Help Rural America Come Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lot of people say rural America, with its
wide-open spaces and small towns, is in trouble and needs a lift.
   The Senate says a modest infusion of federal funds, around $1.5
billion over five years, is a good place to start. The House is
still working on its rural development plan. The Bush administration
hasn't given details of what it supports, but there are hints.
   ``Establishing a rural development policy requires striking a
balance between long-term strategies to improve rural economies and
shorter term efforts to provide jobs and the infrastructure needed
for long-term development and improved quality of life,'' says
Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter.
   However, he adds, national debt ``as the predominant constraint''
on federal spending puts a lid on how much the government can spend
on domestic programs, including rural development.
   ``But even if funding were available, it is not clear that simply
adding programs or funding would be helpful in solving rural
economic problems,'' Yeutter says.
   Rural development for decades has been a goal of every
administration and most office-seekers and farm organizations. Pet
programs have been promoted from time to time, but the national
commitment has been varied and often fuzzy.
   An Agriculture Department task force earlier this year reported
to Yeutter on how to improve USDA's rural development efforts.
Yeutter's comments about ``striking a balance'' and federal spending
were included in the report.
   The rural economy ``has difficulty keeping pace with national
economic growth,'' it said. There are fundamental problems of being
a rural community: small size, isolation, an unskilled work force
and a lack of institutional support.
   ``Cyclical recovery alone will not solve rural America's
problems,'' the task force said. ``Without structural adjustments to
enhance its productive potential, the rural economy will continue to
lag, and many more rural residents will be forced to leave their
hometowns.''
   The task force made a number of recommendations ``within current
budgetary resources and without major organizational restructuring''
to improve the effectiveness of USDA rural programs.
   ``USDA should begin by committing itself to rural development as
a major departmental mission,'' the task force said. ``USDA should
articulate a clear goal for rural development and base its policy
decisions on this goal. It can also take steps to strengthen its
capacity for effective and concerted program action.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Senate
Agriculture Committee and a long-time supporter of rural
development, saw the Senate give unanimous approval a month ago to
his Rural Partnerships Act of 1989.
   ``Rural America today is in trouble,'' Leahy said. ``Compared to
the nation as a whole, rural unemployment and poverty are higher and
economic opportunities are deteriorating. We cannot have two
Americas _ one, a land of opportunity and a second, rural America _
left behind.''
   Leahy said his bill is aimed at helping rural people, an
estimated 61 million Americans, including farmers, businessmen and
workers, in 14,000 small towns and cities across every state.
   While agriculture is important, only 10 percent of rural
Americans live and work on farms. Leahy said the problems of farmers
will be addressed specifically in the 1990 farm bill and other
initiatives.
   The Rural Partnerships Act would provide federal dollars to be
matched locally to create jobs and economic opportunity through
local revolving funds.
   Through other programs, money would be used to help improve
education and health care. Safe drinking water and waste disposal
would be other objectives sought by the Senate bill.
   Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., chairman of the House subcommittee
on conservation credit and rural development, held field hearings
this summer and says legislation deserves a high priority.
   English warns, however, that significant new spending in rural
communities will be impossible, given the budget crunch.
   But he says that if programs are targeted, modernized and used to
complement each other, rural communities can be given ``a real
opportunity to prosper.''
   There is some feeling in the House that rural development should
be dealt with in legislation to replace the 1985 farm law, contrary
to Leahy's plan for keeping the two separate.
   Regardless of the maneuvering, there is growing evidence that
rural development as an issue is around to stay.
   An environmental group, Renew America, said last week that
``thousands of miles of streams are polluted, pesticides continue to
seep into groundwater, acid rain is changing the face of the
forests, lakes and farmland, and litter is scattered over the
countryside.''
   In a report about ``communities at risk,'' the group said rural
America is changing and not for the better.
   Wes Jackson of The Land Institute, Salina, Kan., a non-profit
research organization, said in the report's introduction that the
countryside represents ``the vulnerable soft underbelly'' of U.S.
society at large.
   ``The simple reality is that rural people are a dispersed
minority with no political clout, marginal isolates rapidly becoming
like Third World peoples,'' he said. ``And increasingly the
landscapes on which they live take on a Third World appearance.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Sept. 3</NOTE>
