<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-30 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0690</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy grew at a healthy 2.7 percent
annual rate this spring, far higher than estimated, the government
said in a report viewed as further evidence that the country's
longest peacetime expansion is in no danger of faltering.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that the increase in the
gross national product from April through June was a full percentage
point higher than the anemic 1.7 percent GNP increase originally
estimated a month ago. Most of the new-found strength came in
consumer spending.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bolstered by falling mortgage rates, sales of
new homes surged 14.4 percent in July, the fastest pace in nearly
three years.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that new single-family homes
were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 739,000 units last
month, compared with a revised rate of 646,000 units in June. The
advance was led by a giant 55.8 percent jump in sales in the
Northeast.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate after-tax profits fell 5.4 percent in
the April-June quarter, the biggest decline in three years, the
Commerce Department said in a report that suggested rising costs are
hurting company bottom lines.
   The decline reported Tuesday followed a smaller 1.1 percent drop
in the first three months of the year and left after-tax profits at
an annual rate of $164.3 billion in the second quarter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators proposed new trading rules
plus intensified trading-floor surveillance to combat alleged fraud
and other abuses in the nation's futures exchanges.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which oversees the
futures industry, voted 5-0 Tuesday to submit the package of rules
changes for public comment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover speculation gripped the airline industry, centering on
the two biggest carriers, United and American.
   Leaders of United Airlines' pilots union conferred Tuesday to
discuss possible participation in a buyout of the carrier's parent,
UAL Corp., targeted for a $6.19 billion takeover offer by investor
Marvin Davis. Stock in AMR, parent of American, jumped $10.25 a
share to $91.50 on rumors of a bid.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
      NEW YORK (AP) _ Advertisements from Japanese and West German
companies are almost entirely absent from recent issues of Time
magazine and U.S. News &amp; World Report, which feature cover stories
on the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of World War II.
   Japanese and West German corporate advertisers said Tuesday the
absence was coincidental. But Time and U.S. News executives said
some, whom they wouldn't identify, had asked the magazines to switch
their ads to other issues.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the scandal enveloping the generic drug
industry, consumer advocates and physicians say they're confident in
lower-priced clones of brand-name medicines.
   Although disclosures of fraud and corruption in the Food and Drug
Administration's generic drug division have tainted the agency's
reputation and cast doubts about the industry, many professionals
said Tuesday that concerns about the safety of generic drugs are
overblown.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian partnership sweetened its offer for
Dunkin' Donuts Inc. to $308 million despite the prospect of court
litigation over the hostile takeover struggle.
   DD Acquisition Corp., a partnership of Kingsbridge Capital Group
and Cara Operations Ltd., said Tuesday it had raised its price to
$45 a share from $43, regardless of the outcome of a trial scheduled
next month in Delaware Chancery Court.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stellar Computer Inc. and its Japanese-backed
rival, Ardent Computer Corp., were expected to announce a merger of
two of the top makers of expensive graphics minisupercomputers.
   Sources close to the deal said Tuesday that both privately held
companies are losing money and are hoping that by uniting they will
be able to stave off mounting competition from others.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined broadly, dominated by computerized
selling strategies. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell
16.73 to 2,726.63. Bond prices rose slightly, the dollar fell, gold
rose, and other commodities were mixed.
</TEXT>
