<FIRST>r f PM-DisneySuit     08-30 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disney Suit,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Suit Alleges Copyright Infringement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. filed suit against 149 New York
area merchants charging they violated copyright laws by illegally
selling and distributing merchandise bearing Disney characters.
   Disney, which has exclusive rights to its well-known creations _
Mickey Mouse, Minnie Mouse, Donald Duck, Roger Rabbit and others _
earns more than $100 million a year in royalties from licensing
fees, according to court papers filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn.
   The merchants allegedly sold watches, shirts, dolls, toys and
other products imprinted with Disney characters without obtaining
permission from Disney or paying fees.
   The suit charges ``irreparable harm and damage'' by merchants
selling unauthorized products of inferior quality.
   Disney is seeking at least $1 million in damages and an order to
stop the merchants from producing and selling counterfeit Disney
products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
