<DOCNO> AP890830-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Italy-AtlantaBank     08-30 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Atlanta Bank,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Branch of Italian Bank in Financial Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian bank said that its branch in Atlanta, Ga.,
had been involved in a major financial scandal regarding letters of
credit for exports to Iraq.
   Claudio Cremona, a spokesman for Banca Nazionale del Lavoro,
Italy's largest, state-owned bank, said Tuesday that bank inspectors
had uncovered as many as 2,500 transactions done by its Atlanta
branch which hadn't been authorized by either the bank's North
American management or by the head office in Rome.
   The unauthorized practices, which were confined to the Atlanta
branch, took place during the 12 months before the operation was
discovered in early August, the spokesman said.
   He said the bank had yet to determine the exact amount of money
involved in the scam because ``the auditing is still going on.''
   The investigation was made more difficult by the sophisticated
methods used to keep the transactions off the official books, he
said.
   Cremona said the letters of credit, while correct technically,
exceeded the credit ceiling that Banca Nazionale set for the branch.
He couldn't say by how much the branch had surpassed its credit
limit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
