<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GenericDrugs-Reax     08-30 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Generic Drugs-Reax,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mild Reaction From Drug Companies to Problems With Generics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Generic Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some major drug companies in effect said ``I
told you so'' at the latest news of a troubled generic drug maker,
but added that it was too early to tell the scope of problems among
their Brand X rivals.
   ``You might expect that problems would eventuate,'' said
Warner-Lambert Co. spokesman Peter Wolf in Morris Plains. Generic
drug companies don't have ``quite the same understanding of the
long-term commitment to research integrity,'' he said Tuesday.
   Hoffmann-La Roche Inc. is ``concerned about the recent findings
because they question the reliability of some generic drugs,'' said
Paul Oestreicher, spokesman for the Nutley-based company. ``It's a
serious issue.''
   The Food and Drug Administration moved Monday to withdraw from
the market a popular generic high-blood pressure medicine made by
Bolar Pharmaceutical Co. Inc. It was the third such action aimed at
a generic company in a week, shaking the $5-billion-a-year industry.
   The FDA is investigating 11 drug makers following allegations of
fraud and corruption involving employees of the agency's generic
drug section and some generic drug companies.
   Generic drugs duplicate brand-name products whose patents have
expired, and can cost up to 70 percent less.
   Some major drug makers also produce generic medicines, often
versions of their own drugs whose patents expired.
   Other research-oriented pharmaceutical companies contacted
Tuesday stayed out of the fray.
   ``We're not in the generic business and we're going to pass on
this one,'' said Ronald Asinari, spokesman for Schering-Plough Corp.
of Madison.
   Nor would Merck &amp; Co. spokeswoman Cindy Zarsky comment, though
she did point out that the Rahway-based company's research and
development budget for 1989 was $750 million.
   ``Our response to generic competition is we will continue to
discover and develop innovative medicines,'' she said.
   Many of the companies said it was too early too tell how
widespread problems were among the generics, or whether the
brand-name companies would be affected.
   ``I think we're all waiting holding our breath, hoping that it
isn't more widespread, because ultimately in the public perception
it affects the whole industry,'' Wolf said.
   Analysts doubted the problems at generic drug makers would change
their big brothers' strategy about entering or leaving the generic
market, or make a difference to their bottom line.
   Analysts noted that the major profits in the research-driven drug
business come from patented drugs.
</TEXT>
