<FIRST>r f PM-LincolnS&amp;L     08-30 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banking Chairman Will Reopen Probe of Lincoln S&amp;L</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Banking Committee
says he will reopen his panel's investigation of the failure of
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, expected to require the
government's largest-ever thrift rescue.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, branded the collapse of the
thrift based in Irvine, Calif., a ``mini-Watergate.'' He said his
committee had suspended its probe only because of the pressing need
to pass emergency legislation bailing out the savings and loan
industry.
   Now that Congress has passed the bill, Gonzalez vowed to clear up
the scandal ``once and for all.''
   Previously Gonzalez has criticized M. Danny Wall, director of the
Office of Thrift Supervision, for delaying regulatory action against
Lincoln and allowing the thrift's losses to balloon.
   The probe is sure to examine political contributions from Charles
H. Keating Jr., the chairman of Lincoln's parent firm, American
Continental Corp. of Phoenix, to five senators who later met with
regulators about Lincoln.
   They are Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; John Glenn, D-Ohio;
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; John McCain, R-Ariz., and Donald W.
Riegle Jr., D-Mich. Riegle, who is chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, later returned Keating's contribution.
   Lincoln is under the control of the Resolution Trust Corp., the
new agency created earlier this month to rescue and close the
nation's insolvent thrift institutions. Analysts expect that Lincoln
will be the costliest of more than 400 resolutions.
   ``We already know that at least $1.5 billion has been lost in the
Lincoln fiasco with more to come as the mess is cleaned up,''
Gonzalez said in a statement Monday.
   ``Lincoln remains a mini-Watergate in federal financial
regulations and it is important that the public and the Congress
know why it happened and specifically who was responsible,'' he said.
   Gonzalez said the committee will also re-examine the spate of
last-minute S&amp;L rescues conducted by the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board last December. And, he said, the panel will be overseeing the
RTC's disposition of real estate, particularly in Texas, where the
savings and loan problem has been concentrated.
</TEXT>
