<FIRST>r f PM-RanchoSeco     08-30 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rancho Seco,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Urge Quick Decision on Selling Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has urged a
California utility to decide soon whether to sell or dismantle its
Rancho Seco nuclear power plant, which voters said last June should
close.
   Thomas Murley, director of the commission's office of nuclear
reactor regulation, told officials of the Sacramento Municipal
Utility District on Tuesday that uncertainty about the fate of the
913-megawatt plant was making it difficult to plan regulatory
changes there.
   ``It does make it awkward to keep carrying these options for a
long period of time,'' Murley told the officials in a meeting at NRC
headquarters. The unusual circumstances of the plant's forced
shutdown has put it in ``uncharted waters,'' he said.
   Other commission staff members noted, for example, that they may
need to know the plant's fate before deciding whether to approve the
utility's plan for reducing its emergency staff or its request to be
exempted from an on-site emergency exercise.
   The NRC must approve any transfer of the utility district's
nuclear license to another operator, but it also must approve the
various regulatory adjustments required in the event the plant is
decommissioned and eventually dismantled.
   David A. Boggs, general manager of the utility district, assured
Murley and other commission staff members that the question of
whether to sell Rancho Seco would be resolved ``very soon.''
   Boggs said efforts to sell the 15-year-old plant probably will be
abandoned if no agreement is reached by Friday with Quadrex Corp. of
Campbell, Calif.
   ``I do not see anyone else coming forward ... to continue this
process,'' of negotiating to buy the plant, Boggs said, adding later
that he was ``cautiously optimistic'' that a deal could be worked
out this week with Quadrex.
   The Rancho Seco station has been shut down since June 7, the day
after utility district residents voted against keeping the plant
running. It was the first time an operating nuclear power plant was
closed by voter initiative.
   The vote did not explicitly prohibit the utility from selling the
plant, and a buyer such as Quadrex could be allowed to run it if the
NRC approves a license transfer. Under such circumstances, Quadrex
would have to restart the reactor.
   If a deal is struck with Quadrex, and arrangements are set for
the utility to buy back some of the power generated by Rancho Seco,
then the district's board of directors would vote on it Sept. 7,
Boggs said.
   Any proposed sale would be put to a public vote, tentatively
scheduled for Dec. 12.
   Boggs and other officials of the utility also told the NRC they
were offering key workers special severance agreements in order to
keep them from quitting. Licensed operators, for example, are being
assured they will get the equivalent of six months salary in the
event they are laid off _ money they wouldn't get if they resigned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
