<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest-Congress     08-30 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest-Congress,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Report Backs Checchi Claim About Northwest Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines' new owners should be able
to repay the carrier's $3.1 billion debt with cash from its
operations, including income from sale-leaseback arrangements on
aircraft, congressional auditors say.
   Through 1993, the airline will have at least $635 million a year
left over after servicing its debt and paying taxes, according to an
analysis by the General Accounting Office.
   The GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, prepared the report
for the chairman of the House aviation subcommittee, Rep. James
Oberstar, D-Minn., who planned a hearing this fall on the sale of
the airline's parent company, NWA Inc., to a group led by California
investor Alfred Checchi.
   The leveraged buyout will give Northwest one of the highest debt
loads in the industry, and Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
is investigating the sale to determine whether it will compromise
the carrier's safety.
   Skinner, who could ground the Eagan, Minn.,-based airline if he
believes it is unsafe, is expected to finish his investigation next
month.
   Checchi filed documents with the Securities and Exchange
Commission saying he expects to repay the carrier's debt through
cash flow from its operations. The GAO report said its analysis
shows the claim ``appears to be true.''
   For 1989, the airline would have $1.8 billion in cash available,
including $364 million in income from operations and $834 million
from selling aircraft and then leasing them back.
   After servicing debt, paying taxes and meeting other expenses,
the airline would have $166 million left over, according to the
report.
   By 1993, the company is projected to have income of $2.1 billion,
including $570 million in revenue from the sale-leaseback
arrangements. After debt payments and other expenses the airline
would have excess cash of $635 million, according to the report.
   The airline could cover any cash shortfalls by selling Japanese
real estate it owns or drawing on a $250 million line of credit, the
GAO said.
   The report confirms what the airline has been saying about the
buyout in public statements and government filings, Kevin Whalen, a
spokesman for the carrier, said Tuesday.
   ``We're committed to continuing to grow the airline, to continue
making it more and more competitive and to handle the debt load
brought on by the purchase in a prudent business manner,'' Whalen
said.
   However, the new debt ``weakens Northwest's financial ratios and
creates lower income due to higher interest payments,'' the GAO said.
</TEXT>
