<FIRST>r f PM-AMR     08-30 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMR,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMR Leads Transportations Stocks Up On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AMR Corp. stock jumped 12 percent on Tuesday as
speculation surfaced that the parent of American Airlines had
retained two investment firms to help defend it against unwanted
takeovers.
   News reports said AMR had retained Salomon Brothers Inc. and
Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. to advise the Fort Worth-based company, but AMR
remained mum on the speculation.
   ``We have been directed by senior management not to comment in
any way,'' spokesman Jim Brown said.
   AMR common stock rose $10.25 to close at $91.50 per share in
composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange. More than 3.86
million shares changed hands, the third most active stock traded on
the Big Board Tuesday.
   Other transportation stocks also increased in what analysts said
was anticipation of continued takeover activity in the industry. The
Dow Jones Transportation Average, which includes AMR and six other
airlines in its 20 stocks, finished up 13.69 at 1,506.58, the fourth
consecutive record close.
   UAL Corp., object of $275 per share, or $6.19 billion, takeover
bid by investor Marvin Davis, closed down $4.25 at $277.25, but
other airline companies, including Delta Air Lines Inc., Texas Air
Corp. and Southwest Airlines Co. were up on various exchanges.
   Transportation stocks have been actively traded in the wake of
Davis' bid for UAL, plus the recent buyout of Northwest Airlines
parent NWA Inc by Alfred Checchi.
   ``The latest fad is airline takeovers,'' said Lee Howard, vice
president of Airline Economics Inc., an industry consultant in
Washington, D.C.
   ``They have substantial assets sitting out there which makes them
good takeover targets. You're seeing a continuation of what happened
to Northwest and United,'' Howard said.
   AMR, estimated by some analysts to be worth $114 per share in a
takeover, recently adopted a shareholders rights plan designed to
make a buyout more expensive.
   AMR has reported four straight quarters of record profits, with
second-quarter earnings jumping 25.8 percent to $177.9 million.
   Within the past year, the airline has replaced United as the
nation's No. 1 carrier and has embarked on a multibillion-dollar
expansion program that includes scores of new jets plus a new
maintenance facility and plans for a $1 billion terminal at its base
at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport.
</TEXT>
