<DOCNO> AP890830-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 0942EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DunkinDonuts     08-30 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dunkin Donuts,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Partnership Raises Hostile Bid in Dunkin' Donuts Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian partnership has raised its hostile bid
for Dunkin' Donuts Inc. to $308 million despite a lawsuit pending in
Delaware Chancery Court, officials said.
   Kingsbridge Capital Group and Cara Operations Ltd. officials,
partners in DD Acquisition Corp., said Tuesday they had raised their
bid from $43 to $45 a share, regardless of how the Delaware judge
rules in the trial that begins Sept. 11.
   Unless extended, the offer expires Sept. 15, the Toronto-based
partnership said.
   ``The offer is there and isn't contingent on success in court,''
said Eric W. Evans, a Kingsbridge associate director.
   He said DD Acquisition would continue its bid if the court finds
Dunkin' Donuts was within its rights when it set up a series of
tough defenses, including an employee stock ownership plan, which
holds about 16 percent of its outstanding common shares.
   The company also has a shareholder rights plan, or ``poison
pill,'' designed to increase the number of shares in the event of a
takeover, making a merger prohibitively expensive.
   And it has sold $28 million of preferred stock, convertible to an
11 percent stake in the company, to an avowedly friendly investor,
General Electric Capital Corp.
   ``We think we have a very good case in court and that the court
will find that those measures were improperly put in place. But even
if they weren't, we'll still continue with the bid,'' Evans said.
   He said the offer was, however, valid only if 50.1 percent of
Dunkin' Donuts' common shares were tendered on a fully diluted basis.
   The board of directors at Dunkin' Donuts said in a prepared
statement Tuesday that a meeting ``to evaluate the revised tender
offer with the assistance of the company's outside legal and
financial advisors'' would be scheduled. The company urged
stockholders not to act until officials had made their
recommendation.
   ``Based on publicly available financial information on Dunkin'
Donuts, including its results for the most recent quarter, we
believe this revised offer is generous and fair,'' Earl I. Rotman,
president of Kingsbridge, said in a prepared statement.
   Dunkin' Donuts reported a 34 percent drop in third-quarter
earnings, much of which it attributed to costs associated with
battling the hostile takeover.
   The doughnut shop chain reported earnings for the three months
ended July 29 of $2.1 million or 24 cents a share on revenue of
$30.3 million, compared with earnings of $3.2 million or 49 cents a
share on revenue of $29.2 million.
   For the nine months ended July 29, Dunkin' Donuts reported
earnings totaled $7.62 million or $1.08 a share on revenue of $89.7
million, down 22.7 percent from $9.86 million or $1.49 a share on
revenue of $82.4 million for the same period a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
