<FIRST>r f PM-Arby's     08-30 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arby's,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Franchisees Offer $200 Million Buyout of Fast Food Chain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of eight franchisees said today it has
offered more than $200 million in cash to buy Arby's fast food chain
from DWG Corp., the holding company controlled by industrialist
Victor Posner.
   The group, calling itself R.B. Partners Ltd., said it made the
offer Aug. 1 in a letter to Posner, who has so far not responded to
the proposal.
   In a letter to fellow franchisees, also released today, the group
said Posner's legal and financial problems could threaten the future
of Atlanta-based Arby's.
   Posner pleaded no contest in 1987 to federal income tax evasion
and was sentenced last year to five years probation on the condition
that he pay all his back taxes, penalties and interest, the cost of
prosecuting his case and create a $3 million homeless fund.
   ``We think it is very unlikely that Arby's could remain
unaffected by all these pressures on Mr. Posner and DWG,'' the
letter to the franchisees said.
   DWG, a Miami-based holding company, controls Arby's Inc., the
marketing, franchising and service company for the 2,100-store
Arby's restaurant chain.
   Officials of Arby's were not immediately available for comment. A
secretary at the chain's Atlanta headquarters said President and
Chief Executive Officer Leonard H. Roberts was in a meeting this
morning.
   The franchisees, who together operate more than 500 Arby's roast
beef restaurants, said their offer represents three times what
Miami-based DWG paid for the chain in 1984 as part of its
acquisition of Royal Crown Cola Companies.
   Arby's reported total revenue of $153.8 million and an operating
profit of $20.7 million in 1988.
</TEXT>
