<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-30 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0313</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures prices climbed, wheat prices dipped
and soybeans were mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   The tone was negative in all the pits, however, falling under the
influence of a bearish weather forecast, analysts said.
   The National Weather Service's forecast for the month of
September calls for normal temperatures and rain across the Midwest,
lessening the chance for an early frost that would curb harvest
yields.
   The corn harvest is a month away.
   Traders saw that forecast, and one calling for more rain in the
region by the end of the week, as negative.
   But analysts said corn traders bought on reports that East
Germany is looking to buy half a million tons of U.S. corn.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.83{ a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1 cent higher with September at $2.32{ a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 1{ cents lower, with September at $1.33 a bushel; and
soybeans were 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher, with September at
$5.81{ a bushel.
   Frozen pork-belly futures prices climbed, hog prices fell and
cattle were mostly lower in early trading at the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   In early trading, live cattle were .02 cent to .23 cent lower,
with the contract for delivery in October at 74.67 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were.17 cent lower to .03 cent higher, with October at
82.05 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .45 cent lower, with
October at 41.30 cents a pound; and pork bellies were .50 cent to
1.28 cents higher, with February at 43.77 cents a pound.
   Pork belly prices soared and kept livestock prices firm in
trading Tuesday.
</TEXT>
