<FIRST>u f PM-UAL 1stLd-Writethru f0042 08-30 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0042,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Meets With Flight Attendants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with five new grafs with Davis meeting with flight attendants;
pick up fourth graf pvs, ``And United's ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>ddamhmltcstbs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With one day to go before directors of UAL Corp.
face a deadline for responding to a $6.19 billion takeover offer,
the unions representing United Airlines' largest worker groups are
scrambling to protect their interests.
   Suitor Marvin Davis, a day after meeting with representatives of
the Association of Flight Attendants, said Tuesday he won't ask for
labor concessions from United's unions, the Chicago Sun-Times
reported today.
   Davis issued a statement saying that Monday's talks with the
flight attendants in San Francisco conclude the first round of talks
between his group and the unions. It was the first admission by
Davis that he has met with United's pilots' union, whose approval is
considered crucial to any takeover, the newspaper reported.
   Meantime, leaders of the pilots' union opened a two-day meeting
Tuesday in New York, where they reportedly were discussing the
possibility of participating in a management buyout of Chicago-based
UAL, United's parent company.
   The Machinists union, which represents United's largest worker
group, met Friday with Davis, the Los Angeles billionaire who is
seeking to buy UAL, to spell out the expectations of United's
mechanics and technical workers should they support his bid.
   And United's flight attendants have urged UAL's board to resume
contract negotiations, saying that in the event of an auction, the
airline will be more valuable with settled contracts. The talks
recently broke down after about two years.
   Davis has given UAL's board until Thursday to respond to his
$275-a-share offer, which he raised from $240 a share on Aug. 16.
   The New York meeting of leaders of the United chapter of the Air
Line Pilots Association was believed to be focused on the
maneuvering for control of the nation's second-largest airline, said
James Hanson, a spokesman for the United pilots in Chicago.
   ``They're dealing with all this takeover stuff and its impact on
the pilots but I couldn't give you any specifics on what is going to
be discussed,'' he said.
   The New York Times reported Tuesday that representatives of the
pilots union and Chicago-based UAL had spent the weekend putting
together a package to present to the United chapter's 27-member
master executive council.
   Pilot leaders and UAL officials reportedly have met several times
in the three weeks since Davis' initial offer was revealed to
discuss an employee-management buyout or a recapitalization that
would put enough stock in an employee stock ownership plan to fend
off a hostile takeover attempt.
   United pilots have been seeking an ownership role in the airline
since 1987. Industry analysts have speculated that management might
invite employees to join in a buyout of UAL in exchange for contract
concessions that could end long-running labor disputes between the
company and its pilots and flight attendants unions.
   Without the support of the flight attendants and Machinists, the
pilots might have to assume a heavier financial burden, in the form
of deeper contract concessions.
   ALPA represents most of United's 6,300 pilots. The Association of
Flight Attendants, which represents another 12,700 United workers,
has urged the UAL board to proceed with caution.
   In a letter to the board last week, the attendants called for a
resumption of contract talks.
   The United chapter of the International Association of Machinists
and Aerospace Workers, which represents 25,000 of UAL's 70,000
employees, said last Friday in a letter to the UAL board that they
would ``vigorously oppose'' any buyout or restructuring of the
company.
   But the Times said Tuesday that Brian Freeman, the adviser to the
Machinists, met Friday with Davis and outlined what the Machinists
would expect if they supported his bid.
   Representatives of the flight attendants and the Machinists did
not return calls Tuesday.
</TEXT>
