<FIRST>d f AM-Bordeaux     08-30 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bordeaux,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heat Brings Early Harvest, Predictions Of Great Wines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BORDEAUX, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grape harvest in the Bordeaux wine
region has begun several weeks earlier than usual because of hot,
dry weather, and growers predict an exceptionally good vintage.
   Jean-Bernard Delmas, director of Chateau Haut-Brion, said picking
of grapes destined for white wines began Tuesday in his vineyards,
with the red wine harvest likely to start later in the week.
   ``I can assure you, at least if it doesn't rain, that the 1989
vintage will be the greatest in the century,'' Delmas said.
   He said it was the first time since 1893 that the harvest has
opened before Sept. 1 at Chateau Haut-Brion.
   Because conditions can differ markedly even between nearby
vineyards, the harvest starts at varying times.
   The hot and dry conditions that lead to early harvest give the
grapes an unusually high sugar level. They are likely to produce a
comparatively small amount of wine but of very high quality,
according to the Interprofessional Council of the Wines of Bordeaux.
</TEXT>
