<FIRST>r f BC-HALSale     08-30 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-HAL Sale,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hawaiian Airlines Parent Signs Definitive Agreement for Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HAL Inc., parent company of Hawaiian Airlines,
has signed a definitive agreement for its sale to an investment
group that includes former baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth.
   The investment group, however, said Tuesday that HAL Chairman
John Magoon Jr. must tender nearly all of his controlling interest
for a proposed takeover to go through.
   The group, headed by former airline executive J. Thomas Talbot of
California, plans to purchase 51 percent of HAL's outstanding stock
_ about 1.2 million shares in all. It offered $22 a share for each
share of common stock, making the deal worth about $21.9 million.
   Talbot was a key member of a Ueberroth-led group that attempted
to acquire strikebound Eastern Airlines earlier this year.
   In a news release about the HAL deal, the group said 1.1 million
shares must come from Magoon and other HAL officers and directors.
Magoon owns a controlling interest in the company with more than 1
million shares.
   The agreement, already approved by HAL's directors, is subject to
approval by government agencies and shareholders, and the airline's
unions.
   HAL has scheduled a stockholders meeting for Oct. 19 to obtain
the required shareholder approval. Shareholders of record as of
Sept. 5 will be eligible to vote.
   HAL lost $13 million in the first half of this year and has lost
a total of $30.6 million over the past 2{ years.
   Hawaiian Airlines, Hawaii's largest inter-island airline, also
serves Los Angeles; San Francisco; Seattle; Anchorage, Alaska; Las
Vegas; Australia; New Zealand and other South Pacific points.
   The 60-year-old airline's fleet of 31 planes carried 5.5 million
passengers in 1988.
</TEXT>
