<FIRST>u f AM-TexasAir-Trump     08-30 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Air-Trump,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Trying to Persuade Trump to Buy Continental</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo has met
with Donald J. Trump in an effort to persuade the New York developer
to buy Continental Airlines, a Trump associate said Wednesday.
   ``Mr. Lorenzo and Mr. Trump have spoken,'' said Bruce Nobles,
president of Trump Shuttle, which the developer purchased from
Lorenzo last June for $365 million.
   But Trump has concerns about a potential purchase of Continental,
a subsidiary of Texas Air, Nobles said, noting that Trump is
concerned about Continental's $2.5 billion debt, its small cash
reserves and the need to refurbish many of its planes.
   While Trump remains interested and believes his name would help
the Houston-based carrier win passengers, he has not been convinced
that the risks are acceptable, Nobles said in a telephone interview.
   ``His (Trump's) concerns are well put,'' said Nobles, a former
Texas Air and Pan Am Corp. official.
   Trump was unavailable for comment Wednesday, a spokesman said.
Art Kent, a Texas Air spokesman in Houston, said Lorenzo had no
comment on the matter.
   In talks with Trump, said to have been held over the past month,
Lorenzo said his negative image has hurt Continental, according to
sources quoted in Wednesday's editions of the New York Times.
   Lorenzo announced last Thursday that Houston-based Texas Air, the
nation's largest airline company, may consider selling a minority or
controlling interest in Continental.
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines, Texas Air's other airline
subsidiary, apparently would not be involved in any Continental
transaction.
   Last week, Lorenzo told The Associated Press that one reason he
was considering selling a stake in Continental was that the bitter
struggle with Eastern's unions had hurt traffic at Continental.
   Texas Air is also involved in talks about selling a major stake
in Continental to Scandinavian Airlines System and an unidentified
partner, The Wall Street Journal reported Monday. Texas Air declined
to comment on the report.
   SAS already has a 9.9 percent stake in Texas Air as part of a
joint marketing agreement.
   Sources were quoted by the Times as saying that Lorenzo was
impressed with the way traffic on the former Eastern Air Shuttle in
the Northeast picked up since Trump bought it.
   Trump's share of the lucrative Northeast shuttle market, split
with Pan Am, has ``approximately doubled since we took over,''
Nobles said. Although he declined to give precise figures, he said
Trump Shuttle's market share has jumped from around 25 percent when
it started operations in early June to about 50 percent currently.
   ``I think being separated from Eastern is a positive; having the
Trump name is a positive; having better service is a positive,''
Nobles said.
   But rival Pan Am disputed Nobles' estimate of current market
share. Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon said the Pan Am Shuttle's
share, at around 75 percent when Trump started up, is now holding at
roughly 60 percent.
   ``We're quite pleased with the clientele that we think we've been
able to keep since they started,'' she said.
   The Times quoted its sources as saying that SAS favored a deal
with Continental involving Trump.
   SAS board member Kaj Ikast said Tuesday that the carrier was not
near a decision on taking a stake in Continental. Ikast told the
Times there have been talks with Texas Air about buying such a stake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
