<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1454EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HCASale     08-30 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HCA Sale,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>HCA Accepting $100 Million Less Than Expected for Psychiatric Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital Corporation of America said
Wednesday that it will take $100 million less than the expected
$1.225 billion for its psychiatric company, the largest HCA unit for
sale to help finance the company's management-led takeover.
   HCA executives said in March, when shareholders voted to sell the
company for $3.6 billion, that subsidiaries would be sold to repay a
$1.3 billion bridge loan due in two years.
   ``We are ahead of schedule of our repayment of the bridge loan,''
HCA spokesman David McFadden said.
   The company said in a news release that it has received senior
loan financing commitments and other financing details involved in
selling HCA Psychiatric Company. Psychiatric company executives and
an employee stock ownership plan support the sale.
   While HCA will accept the lower purchase price, it will retain
ownership of $150 million in the psychiatric company's common stock
and preferred stock along with warrants to buy additional shares of
common stock.
   Officials said $650 million in financing will be provided by GE
Capital and The Bank of Nova Scotia. GE Capital also will buy $60
million of the psychiatric company's senior discount notes.
   Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. will arrange the placement of debt and
preferred stock of HPC for $530 million, accounting for the rest of
the financing.
   Financing still has to be approved by HCA's board with closing
expected to be completed by the end of the year.
   The psychiatric company owns 52 facilities with about 5,500 beds.
   HCA owns 78 medical-surgical hospitals with more than 18,000 beds
in the United States.
   HCA Chairman Thomas Frist Jr. said in March that the company
would likely sell its psychiatric division, its management company
and its international division to held finance the leveraged buyout.
   In a leveraged buyout, the assets of the company are used as
collateral to borrow money needed to purchase the company. Such a
transaction usually increases the company's debt substantially.
   Sale of HCA's Allied Clinical Laboratories already was being
considered when the merger was approved March 15.
   At the time, Frist said he wanted to streamline HCA to get back
to the basic business of owning and managing hospitals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
