<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mixed Wednesday against major
currencies in choppy European trading. Gold prices fell in London
but rose elsewhere.
   Dealers said the market was like a ``yo-yo'' with technical
factors instead of any fresh news moving the dollar up and down
sharply.
   They said dealers were awaiting a report on U.S. unemployment in
August due out Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.07 yen to a closing 143.08 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a higher rate of 143.33 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5815 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5945 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.9465 West German marks, up from 1.9375; 1.6770 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6685; 6.5515 French francs, up from 6.5325; 2.1830 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1940; 1.1760 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1724;
and 1,389.50 Italian lire, down from 1,396.00.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $360.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $364.00.
   In Zurich, gold was higher, closing at a bid $361.80 an ounce,
compared with $360.75 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.55 to close at a bid $362.37
an ounce.
   Silver prices fell in London to $5.11 a troy ounce from Tuesday's
$5.15.
</TEXT>
