<FIRST>r f AM-IBM-Toshiba     08-30 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM-Toshiba,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Japan, Toshiba to Establish Color LCD Manufacturing Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IBM Japan Ltd. and Toshiba Corp. said Wednesday they
plan to establish a joint venture company to make color liquid
crystal displays _ key components in popular computer terminal
screens.
   Plant construction for the new company, called Display
Technologies Inc., will begin in March 1990 in Himeji, about 375
miles west of Tokyo, with completion scheduled in April 1991, the
companies said.
   The equally owned Display Technologies, with an initial capital
of 1 billion yen, or about $7 million, will have an annual
production capability of 1 million 10-inch or larger LCDs by 1994,
said Toshiba managing director Tsuyoshi Kawanishi at a joint news
conference.
   LCDs are among the most important technologies for future
products for both Toshiba and IBM, the companies said.
   IBM Japan managing director, Nobuo Mii, said color LCDs made be
Display Technologies would be sold to the parent companies. He said
Toshiba, Japan's second-largest electric machinery maker, and IBM
would incorporate these devices in their products, including
personal computers and work stations, for marketing worldwide.
</TEXT>
