<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-30 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Dip; Corn, Soybeans Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices dipped while corn and
soybeans were mixed in trading Wednesday at the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   With little news to affect the market, traders sold on the
National Weather Service's 30-day forecast that predicts normal
temperatures and rain for the month of September.
   The forecast dims any talk of an early frost that would curb
harvest yields. The corn harvest is a month away.
   In addition, more rain is expected to move into the Midwest by
the end of the week, adding further downward pressure to prices,
analysts said.
   Corn futures rose early in the session on reports that East
Germany is looking to buy half a million tons of U.S. corn, but
quickly fell under the negative weather influences.
   At the close of trading, wheat was } cent to 2 cents lower, with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.83} a bushel; corn was
\ cent lower to } cent higher with September at $2.32 a bushel; oats
were 1 cent to 2 cents lower with September at $1.32{ a bushel; and
soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 2 cents higher, with September at
$5.82{ a bushel.
