<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     08-30 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0331</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ended modestly higher today
after a seesaw session in which prices were pushed up and down by
program trading.
   Continuing takeover speculation regarding airlines and other
companies benefited selected stocks.
   The market sported moderate gains in the morning before rounds of
futures-related program selling rocked stocks this afternoon and
temporarly knocked down share prices.
   Stock prices bobbed back up, however, amid renewed buying when
traders seized oppportunities to profit from the price difference
between stock-index futures and actual stocks.
   A government report that furnished further evidence of economic
health failed to have much impact on Wall Street. The Commerce
Department said U.S. personal income rose 0.7 percent in July, the
best gain in four months, while consumer spending climbed at its
fastest pace in three months.
   With the economy apparently doing better than many analysts had
thought, it is much less likely that the Federal Reserve Board will
nudge interest rates lower to spur growth.
   An upward revision in the gross national product, the broadest
measure of the economy's performance, reported Tuesday already had
diminished hopes that the central bank would cut interest rates.
   The Commerce Department said the GNP grew by 2.7 percent from
April through July, a significant change from the 1.7 percent growth
rate originally reported last month.
   The Big Board's most heavily traded share was Upjohn which was
bid higher amid talk that a foreign firm might be interested in
acquiring the drug company but Upjohn said there was no corporate
news to account for the heavy trading. Upjohn jumped 2{ to 40~ on
volume of more than 4.5 million shares.
   Takeover speculation continued to steer investors toward airline
stocks. AMR, parent of American Airlines, spurted another 1\ to 92},
adding to Tuesday's gain of 10\. AMR reportedly has hired investment
banks to help defend itself against unwanted suitors.
</TEXT>
