<FIRST>u f AM-Exxon-Appointee     08-30 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-Appointee,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Appoints Environmentalist To Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. said Wednesday it has named marine
scientist John H. Steele as a director, in response to shareholder
demands for the addition of an environmental expert following the
nation's worst oil spill.
   Steele, 62, is president and a senior scientist at Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution. He also will serve on the board's newly
formed public issues committee, which will monitor the company's
environmental policies.
   ``This is a good day for the environment and Exxon
shareholders,'' said Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin, trustee for New
York's employee, firefighter and police pension funds.
   New York was one of several pension funds with large holdings of
Exxon stock that has publicized its dissatisfaction with the oil
giant's handling of the March 24 spill and cleanup effort.
   The funds, which included New York State and the California
Public Employee Retirement System, the largest individual U.S.
public pension fund, had called for Exxon to appoint a director with
expertise and interest in the environment.
   Goldin said the appointment ``demonstrates environmental and
social responsibility'' in the aftermath of the disaster in which
the tanker Exxon Valdez hit a charted reef and spewed millions of
gallons of oil into Prince William Sound.
   In a telephone interview from his office in Woods Hole, Mass.,
about 70 miles south of Boston on the southeast end of Cape Cod,
Steele spoke of the spill.
   ``I think it's a terrible tragedy and a major disaster not just
for the animals but for the people in Alaska,'' Steele said.
   He declined to comment on Exxon's handling of the cleanup but
said he would visit Alaska in about two weeks for a separate
scientific meeting on arctic research and would view the remnants of
the spill at that time.
   ``It will give me an opportunity to discuss these research and
scientific questions with colleagues in Alaska,'' he said.
   Steele will serve on the board until Exxon's annual shareholder's
meeting next April, when his name will be submitted for shareholder
approval along with the other directors, said Exxon spokesman Bill
Smith.
   At the company's annual shareholders last May, shareholders
demanded changes in what they called Exxon's ``inadequate state of
preparedness'' for dealing with future problems.
   Although the funds ultimately voted for management this year,
they warned of a major shareholder revolt next year if the Exxon
appointment was unsatisfactory to dissident shareholders.
   At the May meeting, Exxon management agreed to create the
six-member public issues committee, which includes four non-Exxon
employees. Exxon said the committee would review the corporation's
``policies, programs and practices on public issues of significance
including their effects on the environment and worker safety and
health.''
   Steele's appointment increases the size of the Exxon board to 15,
including ten non-employee directors.
   Born in Edinburgh, Scotland, Steele's career includes 26 years at
the Marine Laboratory at Aberdeen, Scotland. He joined Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution in 1977.
   Steele's principal research includes the marine environment. He
is the U.S. delegate to the International Council for Exploration of
the Sea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
