<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-30 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply Wednesday against key
foreign currencies after a mixed performance overseas.
   Gold prices slipped. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery closed at $361.80 a troy ounce, down
$1.80 from late Tuesday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
late bid for gold of $360.35 an ounce, down $1.65.
   Currency dealers said market sentiment toward the dollar was
bullish following the release of U.S. government reports showing
continued economic strength, which lessens the possibility of lower
interest rates.
   ``The economic numbers ... continued to keep the dollar well
supported in spite of technical selling,'' said Ronald H. Holzer,
chief currency dealer for Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago.
   The government reported Wednesday that personal incomes rose a
brisk 0.7 percent in July while consumer spending climbed at the
fastest rate since April.
   On Tuesday, the government revised upward its estimate of total
economic growth, putting the increase in the gross national product
during the second quarter at a healthy 2.7 percent annual rate
instead of the anemic 1.7 percent rate reported a month ago.
   Dealers say they're now awaiting a report on August unemployment
due out Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.07 Japanese yen to a closing 143.08 yen. It was
quoted higher in London at 143.33 yen, and in New York at 144.25
yen, up from 143.01 late Tuesday.
   The dollar rose against the British pound. It cost $1.5815 to buy
one pound in London, cheaper than $1.5945 late Tuesday. Sterling
fetched $1.5779 in New York, down from $1.5870.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday,
included: 1.9533 West German marks, up from 1.9362; 1.6832 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6704; 6.5775 French francs, up from 6.5285; 1.1769
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1754; and 1,400.50 Italian lire, up from
1,391.25.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,
included: 1.9465 West German marks, up from 1.9375; 1.6770 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6685; 6.5515 French francs, up from 6.5325; 2.1830
Dutch guilders, down from 2.1940; 1.1760 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1724; and 1,389.50 Italian lire, down from 1,396.00.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $360.75 an ounce from
Tuesday's $364.00. But it closed higher in Zurich, Switzerland, at
$361.80 an ounce from $360.75.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.55 to close at a bid $362.37
an ounce.
   Silver prices declined. On New York's Comex, silver for current
delivery fell to $5.085 a troy ounce from $5.091 late Tuesday.
Silver fell in London to $5.11 an ounce from $5.15.
</TEXT>
