<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1724EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Arby'sBuyout     08-30 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arby's Buyout,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arby's Owner Spurns Franchisees' $200 Million Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of franchisees operating more than 500
Arby's fast-food restaurants said Wednesday it had offered over $200
million for the chain, but the owner says it's not interested in
selling.
   Arby's Inc. is owned by a company controlled by DWG Corp., a
Miami-based holding company controlled by industrialist Victor
Posner.
   The group of eight franchisees said it wanted to buy the
Atlanta-based chain because DWG's continued ownership could threaten
the stability of Arby's, partly because of Posner's legal and
financial problems.
   ``We believe strongly that Arby's Inc. should be owned by its
franchisees,'' the group, incorporated as R.B. Partners Ltd., said
in a letter Tuesday to fellow franchisees.
   ``We are not trying to profit from taking the lead here,'' said
the letter, released Wednesday. ``We are trying to protect the
Arby's system.''
   Posner pleaded no contest in 1987 to federal income tax evasion
and was sentenced last year to five years probation on the condition
that he pay all his back taxes, penalties and interest, the cost of
prosecuting his case and create a $3 million fund to benefit the
homeless.
   ``We think it is very unlikely that Arby's could remain
unaffected by all these pressures on Mr. Posner and DWG,'' read the
franchisees' letter.
   Arby's is a wholly owned subsidiary of Miami Beach-based
Chesapeake Financial Corp., of which DWG is a 60 percent owner.
   Chesapeake, in a statement released Wednesday, termed the R.B.
Partners proposal ``an unsolicited purported offer.'' Chesapeake
also said, ``as it had previously informed such franchisees, it
presently had no interest in pursuing such a sale.''
   Posner, who is chairman of Arby's Inc., is ``committed to the
continued growth and expansion of Arby's _ a process which, under
his management, had resulted in outstanding performance and growth
since its acquisition in June 1984,'' Chesapeake stated.
   Officials at Arby's headquarters in Atlanta could not be reached
for comment Wednesday. A secretary said President and Chief
Executive Officer Leonard H. Roberts was in a meeting.
   The franchisees said their offer represents three times what DWG
paid for the chain in 1984 as part of its acquisition of Royal Crown
Cola Companies. Arby's, with about 2,100 restaurants, reported total
revenue of $153.8 million and an operating profit of $20.7 million
in 1988.
   A spokesman for the franchisees, who asked that his name not be
used, said Wednesday the group wass confident it could raise the
money for the deal and had been assured by a number of institutions
that it could get financing.
   Howard Hansen, a restaurant industry analyst with Kidder Peabody
in New York, said there have been some cases of successful
franchisee buyouts. But he said the main obstacle for the group
would be raising the money.
   ``I don't believe there would be any legal hurdles. You have to
come up with the money,'' Hansen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
