<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-30 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Rise as Demand for Heating Oil Increases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increased demand for home heating oil helped
boost prices for energy futures across the board Wednesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
heating oil rose 0.94 cent to close at 53.11 cents a gallon after
rising 0.45 cent on Tuesday.
   Demand for heating oil surged after an American Petroleum
Institute supply report issued late Tuesday indicated that
inventories of the fuel did not increase as expected, said Andrew
Lebow, an analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline futures also rose, continuing the
momentum begun in Tuesday's session. Gasoline for September delivery
picked up 0.39 cent to close at 55.00 cents a gallon, adding to a
0.96 cent advance Tuesday.
   ``The rising (refined) products market helped to bring crude
up,'' Lebow said. More crude oil is needed when demand for heating
oil and gasoline increases.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 19 cents to settle at $18.83 a barrel
after having closed unchanged on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
