<DOCNO> AP890830-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1920EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Butcher-Fraud     08-30 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Butcher-Fraud,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jake Butcher, Wilson, Hit With New Fraud Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Tennessee gubernatorial nominee Jake
Butcher, already serving 20 years in prison for bank fraud, was hit
Wednesday with a new federal indictment accusing him of receiving
illegal bank loans.
   Indicted along with Butcher was his one-time partner, Earl D.
Wilson, currently serving a 10-year bank fraud term, Wilson's wife
Harriette, and nine other people.
   ``We feel the alleged criminal acts represent utter contempt for
the criminal justice system,'' said U.S. Attorney Robert W. Genzman
of the Middle District of Florida.
   Named as an unindicted co-conspirator was Joe F. Justice, the
imprisoned former president of the Florida Center Bank of Orlando,
which went out of business in 1986.
   Genzman called the case ``round three of a continuing
investigation into the collapse of the bank.''
   The 51-count indictment accuses the defendants of involvement in
a scheme to obtain $3.5 million from ``nominee borrowers'' for
Butcher and Wilson after they had declared bankruptcy in 1984 and
1985. They were also facing a federal fraud investigation in
Tennessee relating to the collapse of their banking empire.
   Justice allegedly accepted $75,000 in kickbacks to arrange the
loans from Florida Center Bank. The loans were nominally for other
bank clients, but were actually delivered to Butcher and the
Wilsons, according to the indictment.
   The indictment includes counts of making false statements on loan
applications, bank fraud, conspiracy to commit bank fraud and
misapplication of funds.
   Genzman said prosecutors anticipate having all the defendants
present for arraignment within 12 days.
   Butcher could face a maximum 71 years in prison and fines of $4.5
million on the charges, while Wilson faces 126 years and $8 million
in fines. Mrs. Wilson, who lives in Longwood, could be sentenced to
57 years and a fine of $3.5 million.
   Also indicted were Allen L. ``Red Dog'' Hicks, of Knoxville,
Tenn.; David Ogle, also of Knoxville; Michael R. Allen, of Altamonte
Springs; Frederick C. Streck, of Atlanta, James P. Gresham and his
girlfriend Sandra K. Chitwood, both also of Atlanta; Harold G. and
Margaret F. Artrip, of Longwood and Michael F. Thomas, of
Cookeville, Tenn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
