<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-Merger     08-30 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Merger,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Admits Urging Clients to Buy Stock During Merger Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two Japanese banks planning a major merger
admitted Wednesday it had urged its clients to buy stock in the bank
in June, but said this had no connection with the merger talks then
under way.
   ``It was intended to increase the number of stable shareholders
of the bank's stock,'' said Fukio Yamamoto, a spokesman for Taiyo
Kobe Bank.
   Mitsui Bank, the seventh-largest bank in both Japan and the
world, and Taiyo Kobe, the eighth-largest, announced Tuesday they
will merge April 1 to meet intensifying competition from domestic
and foreign banks. The new bank will be the world's second largest.
   Wednesday's disclosure triggered criticism that Taiyo Kobe Bank
was using insider information for its own advantage, but Yamamoto
said the stock campaign ``had no connection with the merger talks.''
   Taiyo Kobe has been seen as the main beneficiary of the merger in
terms of its stock price. Taiyo Kobe stock had been steady at the
equivalent of about $9.80 a share until late June, when it began
rising. It closed at $11.40 Monday, the day before the merger was
announced.
   Trading in both banks' stock was suspended Tuesday to give
investors time to digest details of the merger plan.
   On Wednesday, buy orders in anticipation of further rises in
Taiyo Kobe's stock amounted to 64 million shares, while 450,000
shares were offered for sale.
   The stock closed Wednesday at $13.50 after the maximum one-day
gain of $2.10 allowed under stock exchange rules.
   Officials of the Tokyo Stock Exchange said they would investigate
the merger, but stressed that it would be a ``routine'' probe, not
based on any suspicion that insider trading or illegality was
involved.
   Hitoshi Shimakura, head of the Transaction Inspection Division of
the world's largest exchange, said his office would look into recent
price fluctuations of both banks' stocks.
   ``The real key is when the actual decision on the merger was
made,'' he said. ``As far as insider trading laws are concerned,
anything that occurred before the final decision to merge has to be
handled separately.''
   Kenichi Suematsu, president of Mitsui Bank, told reporters at a
news conference Tuesday that the merger was formally approved by the
boards of directors of both banks on Monday. He said negotiations
for the merger began in March.
   On Wednesday, it was learned from a report compiled by the
Securities Industries Association that Shinei Ishino Securities Co.,
a brokerage affiliated with Taiyo Kobe Bank, bought 4.7 million
Taiyo Kobe shares in June and July, when merger negotiations were in
their final stage.
   Analysts said the huge purchase of Taiyo Kobe shares by
medium-size Shinei Ishino was caused by the bank's campaign to urge
its clients to buy shares. Taiyo Kobe officials said they usually
recommend that their clients use Shinei Ishino.
   Junzo Yamakawa, a vice president of Shinei Ishino, was quoted in
the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, a major economic newspaper, as saying his
company knew nothing about the merger before the announcement, and
it was ``entirely our customers' decision'' to buy Taiyo Kobe shares.
   ``There had been speculation that Taiyo Kobe was about to
announce an important decision because its share prices began
soaring while most other bank shares remained sluggish,'' said
Keiichi Nishida, an analyst at Kidder Peabody Securities. ``What's
clear now is that the information did leak out and apparently
affected its stock price well ahead of the announcement of the
merger.''
</TEXT>
