<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0135 08-30 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0135,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Plans to Boost Schedule, But May Be Short On Cash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `George Brennan ...,' to CORRECT to 601 flights
on Sept. 7 sted 600.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines, nearing the seventh month of its
strike, on Wednesday said it will add another 101 daily flights Oct.
1 and is ahead of its rebuilding schedule.
   The announcement of new flights, most between Florida and
Northeast cities, came a day before Eastern officials were scheduled
to make a presentation in New York to creditors on their rebuilding
plan. While Eastern says it's making good progress on efforts to
rebuild without its unions, The Wall Street Journal reported
Wednesday that Eastern faces $400 million in revenue shortfalls and
may have to revise its plan for emerging from Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection.
   ``We do have a meeting with the creditors and we'll give them an
overall status report,'' said Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
She declined to comment further, but said ``one thing that hasn't
changed is that the creditors will all be paid.''
   The Journal, quoting unidentified sources, said parent Texas Air
Corp. may underwrite some of Eastern's operations because Eastern's
negotiations with rival American Airlines on the sale of Latin
American routes have stalled. The sale had been expected to bring in
as much as $400 million for Miami-based Eastern.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said recently the carrier may not
sell the full $1.8 billion in assets envisaged in its original
rebuilding plan, and he said the coveted Latin American routes
wouldn't necessarily be sold.
   While Bakes said Eastern intends to be bigger than first planned,
union officials say the effort to rebuild since the strike began
March 4 is foundering.
   ``Obviously this is a setback for (Texas Air Chairman Frank)
Lorenzo and the creditors,'' pilots union spokesman Hank Weber said.
``To say he's 20 to 25 percent short on his cash projections has to
have an unfavorable response from the creditors.''
   Referring to Eastern's planned schedule increase, Weber said: ``I
don't know where they will get the aircraft.''
   He said Eastern, whose pilots, Machinists and flight attendants
unions remain on strike and hope for a new owner, is falling behind
on aircraft maintenance.
   Weber said the pilots union is exploring bringing more pressure
on Lorenzo by threatening to remove $800 million in pension fund
investments from banks doing business with Texas Air. He said
details were still being worked out for the effort, which the pilots
union hopes will be joined by other unions.
   George Brennan, Eastern's vice president for marketing, said the
carrier has sufficient numbers of pilots and planes to boost its
schedule again. Eastern earlier announced it will move from 390
daily flights to 601 on Sept. 7, and Brennan said it will jump to
702 on Oct. 1.
   There will be several more additions in the month after that,
Brennan said, putting Eastern near its target _ 800 daily flights by
year's end.
   ``What this says is we're going to get the airline rebuilt faster
than we thought,'' Brennan said.
   Eastern had nearly 1,100 daily flights and 30,000 employees when
it was struck last spring. The company is now back to 12,000
employees and will have 17,000 by year's end, Brennan said.
   Eastern, which is leasing 15 planes and crews from Texas Air
sister Continental Airlines, doesn't plan to lease more from
Continental, Brennan said. He said Eastern has 155 planes of its own
to fly.
   The carrier is continuing to offer discount fares such as $79 one
way between Miami and New York, Brennan said. Although Eastern loses
money flying passengers at such low prices, he said the priority
this year is winning back customers to the rebuilding carrier.
   ``Ultimately, of course, we've got to prove we can be
profitable,'' Brennan said.
   The new schedule increases, adding new nonstop services from
Miami, Washington, Philadelphia, Boston and New York, move Eastern
close to its goal of nearly 300 flights for its Atlanta hub while
moving the rebuilding focus to its ``traditional stronghold'' in
Florida, Brennan said.
</TEXT>
