<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-GeneralCinema     08-30 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-General Cinema,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Cinema Corp.'s Earnings Up 23 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Cinema Corp. said Wednesday its
earnings rose 26 percent in the three months ended July 31, in part
because of a 23 percent rise in attendance at the company's theaters.
   General Cinema said the boost in earnings also could be
attributed to improved performance by Neiman Marcus Group, a 59.9
percent-owned subsidiary whose results are consolidated with a
one-quarter lag.
   For the quarter, earnings were $25.6 million, or 35 cents a
share, on revenue of $491.3 million, compared with earnings of $21.7
million, or 30 cents a share, on revenue of $390 million for the
same period in 1988.
   The year-ago results included after-tax earnings of $19.3
million, or 26 cents a share, from operations at the company's soft
drink bottling business, which was sold in March 1989.
   The profit for the first nine months of fiscal 1989, including
after-tax income of $865.9 million from the discontinued operations,
was $98 million, or $13.06 a share, on revenue of $1.46 billion,
compared with earnings of $963.9 million, or $1.16 a share, on
revenue of $1.24 billion in the 1988 period.
   ``General Cinema Theatres benefited from an outstandinng crop of
summer pictures and reported strong gains in attendance, revenues
and operating earnings in the third quarter,'' Chairman Richard A.
Smith said in a statement.
   During the quarter, General Cinema added 28 screens and closed 10
older ones, bringing to 1,451 the number of screens at 318 theaters.
</TEXT>
