<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 2217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Pickens-Gubernatorial     08-30 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pickens-Gubernatorial,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickens Says He Won't Run For Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA WEISGERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oilman and corporate raider T. Boone Pickens said
Wednesday he will not run for governor in 1990, but left open his
options for 1994.
   The 61-year-old Pickens said the crush of his business would not
allow him to commit 100 percent of his time to the needs of the
state.
   ``It's not the time,'' he told about 500 people at a Dallas
Rotary luncheon, ending weeks of speculation.
   Pickens said he had prepared two versions of his speech _ one
announcing his candidacy and the one he delivered. He and his wife,
Beatrice, reached their decision late Tuesday at their hotel room in
Dallas, Pickens said, and were still discussing it Wednesday morning.
   Pickens did not rule out a run in 1994. ``That's an option,'' he
said.
   Pickens would not endorse any of the Republican candidates who
would have been his rivals in the GOP primary.
   His decision not to run, Pickens said, was based on his
involvement in his Mesa Limited Partnership, Koito Manufacturing and
his United Shareholders Association.
   Mesa, an oil and gas firm, lost $13.4 million in the second
quarter and will likely post a loss in the third quarter, Pickens
said, refusing to speculate on how large the loss might be.
   He blamed the losses on declining natural gas prices. Pickens,
once feared as a corporate raider and who made a $518 million pretax
profit in a 1983 attempted takeover of Gulf Oil Corp., said it was
the first loss for the company in 16 years.
   Pickens also said he plans to continue his efforts to open up
opportunities for U.S. investment in Japan, and may
``significantly'' increase his stake in Koito Manufacturing, a
Japanese auto parts supplier.
   Pickens' Boone Co. owns 20.2 percent of Koito. Although Pickens
is Koito's largest shareholder, he has been denied a seat on the
company's board.
   He said he plans to call for a special Koito shareholders meeting
in coming weeks and will continue to work with Congress and U.S.
trade officials to ``level the playing field'' in trade and
investment with the Japanese. ``I think the Japanese are just not
playing a fair game,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
